{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.21.2510;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\lang9\f0\fs20 _Chapter 1_\par
Minas Tirith\par
Pippin looked out from the shelter of Gandalf's cloak. He wondered if he\par
was awake or still sleeping, still in the swift-moving dream in which he had\par
been wrapped so long since the great ride began. The dark world was rushing by\par
and the wind sang loudly in his ears. He could see nothing but the wheeling\par
stars, and away to his right vast shadows against the sky where the mountains\par
of the South marched past. Sleepily he tried to reckon the times and stages of\par
their journey, but his memory was drowsy and uncertain.\par
There had been the first ride at terrible speed without a halt, and then\par
in the dawn he had seen a pale gleam of gold, and they had come to the silent\par
town and the great empty house on the hill. And hardly had they reached its\par
shelter when the winged shadow had passed over once again, and men wilted with\par
fear. But Gandalf had spoken soft words to him, and he had slept in a corner,\par
tired but uneasy, dimly aware of comings and goings and of men talking and\par
Gandalf giving orders. And then again riding, riding in the night. This was\par
the second, no, the third night since he had looked in the Stone. And with\par
that hideous memory he woke fully, and shivered, and the noise of the wind\par
became filled with menacing voices.\par
A light kindled in the sky, a blaze of yellow fire behind dark barriers\par
Pippin cowered back, afraid for a moment, wondering into what dreadful country\par
Gandalf was bearing him. He rubbed his eyes, and then he saw that it was the\par
moon rising above the eastern shadows, now almost at the full. So the night\par
was not yet old and for hours the dark journey would go on. He stirred and\par
spoke.\par
'Where are we, Gandalf?' he asked.\par
'In the realm of Gondor,' the wizard answered. 'The land of An\'f3rien is\par
still passing by.'\par
There was a silence again for a while. Then, 'What is that?' cried Pippin\par
suddenly, clutching at Gandalf's cloak. 'Look! Fire, red fire! Are there\par
dragons in this land? Look, there is another!'\par
For answer Gandalf cried aloud to his horse. 'On, Shadowfax! We must\par
hasten. Time is short. See! The beacons of Gondor are alight, calling for aid.\par
War is kindled. See, there is the fire on Amon D\'een, and flame on Eilenach; and\par
there they go speeding west: Nardol, Erelas, Min-Rimmon, Calenhad, and the\par
Halifirien on the borders of Rohan.'\par
But Shadowfax paused in his stride, slowing to a walk, and then he lifted\par
up his head and neighed. And out of the darkness the answering neigh of other\par
horses came; and presently the thudding of hoofs was heard, and three riders\par
swept up and passed like flying ghosts in the moon and vanished into the West.\par
Then Shadowfax gathered himself together and sprang away, and the night flowed\par
over him like a roaring wind.\par
Pippin became drowsy again and paid little attention to Gandalf telling\par
him of the customs of Gondor, and how the Lord of the City had beacons built\par
on the tops of outlying hills along both borders of the great range, and\par
maintained posts at these points where fresh horses were always in readiness\par
to bear his errand-riders to Rohan in the North, or to Belfalas in the South.\par
'It is long since the beacons of the North were lit,' he said; 'and in the\par
ancient days of Gondor they were not needed, for they had the Seven Stones.'\par
Pippin stirred uneasily.\par
'Sleep again, and do not be afraid!' said Gandalf. 'For you are not going\par
like Frodo to Mordor, but to Minas Tirith, and there you will be as safe as\par
you can be anywhere in these days. If Gondor falls, or the Ring is taken, then\par
the Shire will be no refuge.'\par
'You do not comfort me,' said Pippin, but nonetheless sleep crept over\par
him. The last thing that he remembered before he fell into deep dream was a\par
glimpse of high white peaks, glimmering like floating isles above the clouds\par
as they caught the light of the westering moon. He wondered where Frodo was,\par
and if he was already in Mordor, or if he was dead; and he did not know that\par
Frodo from far away looked on that same moon as it set beyond Gondor ere the\par
coming of the day.\par
Pippin woke to the sound of voices. Another day of hiding and a night of\par
journey had fleeted by. It was twilight: the cold dawn was at hand again, and\par
chill grey mists were about them. Shadowfax stood steaming with sweat, but he\par
held his neck proudly and showed no sign of weariness. Many tall men heavily\par
cloaked stood beside him, and behind them in the mist loomed a wall of stone.\par
Partly ruinous it seemed, but already before the night was passed the sound of\par
hurried labour could be heard: beat of hammers, clink of trowels, and the\par
creak of wheels. Torches and flares glowed dully here and there in the fog.\par
Gandalf was speaking to the men that barred his way, and as he listened Pippin\par
became aware that he himself was being discussed.\par
'Yea truly, we know you, Mithrandir,' said the leader of the men, 'and\par
you know the pass-words of the Seven Gates and are free to go forward. But we\par
do not know your companion. What is he? A dwarf out of the mountains in the\par
North? We wish for no strangers in the land at this time, unless they be\par
mighty men of arms in whose faith and help we can trust.'\par
'I will vouch for him before the seat of Denethor,' said Gandalf. 'And as\par
for valour, that cannot be computed by stature. He has passed through more\par
battles and perils than you have, Ingold, though you be twice his height; and\par
he comes now from the storming of Isengard, of which we bear tidings, and\par
great weariness is on him, or I would wake him. His name is Peregrin, a very\par
valiant man.'\par
'Man?' said Ingold dubiously; and the others laughed.\par
'Man!' cried Pippin, now thoroughly roused. 'Man! Indeed not! I am a\par
hobbit and no more valiant than I am a man, save perhaps now and again by\par
necessity. Do not let Gandalf deceive you!'\par
'Many a doer of great deeds might say no more,' said Ingold. 'But what is\par
a hobbit?'\par
'A Halfling,' answered Gandalf. 'Nay, not the one that was spoken of,' he\par
added seeing the wonder in the men's faces. 'Not he, yet one of his kindred.'\par
'Yes, and one who journeyed with him,' said Pippin. 'And Boromir of your\par
City was with us, and he saved me in the snows of the North, and at the last\par
he was slain defending me from many foes.'\par
'Peace!' said Gandalf. 'The news of that grief should have been told\par
first to the father.'\par
'It has been guessed already,' said Ingold; 'for there have been strange\par
portents here of late. But pass on now quickly! For the Lord of Minas Tirith\par
will be eager to see any that bear the latest tidings of his son, be he man\par
or-'\par
'Hobbit,' said Pippin. 'Little service can I offer to your lord, but what\par
I can do, I would do, remembering Boromir the brave.'\par
'Fare you well!' said Ingold; and the men made way for Shadow fax, and he\par
passed through a narrow gate in the wall. 'May you bring good counsel to\par
Denethor in his need, and to us all, Mithrandir!' Ingold cried. 'But you come\par
with tidings of grief and danger, as is your wont, they say.'\par
'Because I come seldom but when my help is needed,' answered Gandalf.\par
'And as for counsel, to you I would say that you are over-late in repairing\par
the wall of the Pelennor. Courage will now be your best defence against the\par
storm that is at hand \endash  that and such hope as I bring. For not all the tidings\par
that I bring are evil. But leave your trowels and sharpen your swords!'\par
'The work will be finished ere evening,' said Ingold. 'This is the last\par
portion of the wall to be put in defence: the least open to attack, for it\par
looks towards our friends of Rohan. Do you know aught of them? Will they\par
answer the summons, think you?'\par
'Yes, they will come. But they have fought many battles at your back.\par
This road and no road looks towards safety any longer. Be vigilant! But for\par
Gandalf Stormcrow you would have seen a host of foes coming out of An\'f3rien and\par
no Riders of Rohan. And you may yet. Fare you well, and sleep not!'\par
Gandalf passed now into the wide land beyond the Rammas Echor. So the men\par
of Gondor called the out wall that they had built with great labour, after\par
Ithilien fell under the shadow of their Enemy. For ten leagues or more it ran\par
from the mountains' feet and so back again, enclosing in its fence the fields\par
of the Pelennor: fair and fertile townlands on the long slopes and terraces\par
falling to the deep levels of the Anduin. At its furthest point from the Great\par
Gate of the City, north-eastward, the wall was four leagues distant, and there\par
from a frowning bank it overlooked the long flats beside the river, and men\par
had made it high and strong; for at that point, upon a walled causeway, the\par
road came in from the fords and bridges of Osgiliath and passed through a\par
guarded gate between embattled towers. At its nearest point the wall was\par
little more than one league from the City, and that was south-eastward. There\par
Anduin, going in a wide knee about the hills of Emyn Arnen in South Ithilien,\par
bent sharply west, and the out-wall rose upon its very brink; and beneath it\par
lay the quays and landings of the Harlond for craft that came upstream from\par
the southern fiefs.\par
The townlands were rich, with wide tilth and many orchards, and\par
homesteads there were with oast and garner, fold and byre, and many rills\par
rippling through the green from the highlands down to Anduin. Yet the herdsmen\par
and husbandmen that dwelt there were not many, and the most part of the people\par
of Gondor lived in the seven circles of the City, or in the high vales of the\par
mountain-borders, in Lossarnach, or further south in fair Lebennin with its\par
five swift streams. There dwelt a hardy folk between the mountains and the\par
sea. They were reckoned men of Gondor, yet their blood was mingled, and there\par
were short and swarthy folk among them whose sires came more from the\par
forgotten men who housed in the shadow of the hills in the Dark Years ere the\par
coming of the kings. But beyond, in the great fief of Belfalas, dwelt Prince\par
Imrahil in his castle of Dol Amroth by the sea, and he was of high blood, and\par
his folk also, tall men and proud with sea-grey eyes.\par
Now after Gandalf had ridden for some time the light of day grew in the\par
sky, and Pippin roused himself and looked up. To his left lay a sea of mist,\par
rising to a bleak shadow in the East; but to his right great mountains reared\par
their heads, ranging from the West to a steep and sudden end, as if in the\par
making of the land the River had burst through a great barrier, carving out a\par
mighty valley to be a land of battle and debate in times to come. And there\par
where the White Mountains of Ered Nimrais came to their end he saw, as Gandalf\par
had promised, the dark mass of Mount Mindolluin, the deep purple shadows of\par
its high glens, and its tall face whitening in the rising day. And upon its\par
out-thrust knee was the Guarded City, with its seven walls of stone so strong\par
and old that it seemed to have been not builded but carven by giants out of\par
the bones of the earth.\par
Even as Pippin gazed in wonder the walls passed from looming grey to\par
white, blushing faintly in the dawn; and suddenly the sun climbed over the\par
eastern shadow and sent forth a shaft that smote the face of the City. Then\par
Pippin cried aloud, for the Tower of Ecthelion, standing high within the\par
topmost walls' shone out against the sky, glimmering like a spike of pearl and\par
silver, tall and fair and shapely, and its pinnacle glittered as if it were\par
wrought of crystals; and white banners broke and fluttered from the\par
battlements in the morning breeze' and high and far he heard a clear ringing\par
as of silver trumpets.\par
So Gandalf and Peregrin rode to the Great Gate of the Men of Gondor at\par
the rising of the sun, and its iron doors rolled back before them.\par
'Mithrandir! Mithrandir!' men cried. 'Now we know that the storm is\par
indeed nigh!'\par
'It is upon you,' said Gandalf. 'I have ridden on its wings. Let me pass!\par
I must come to your Lord Denethor, while his stewardship lasts. Whatever\par
betide, you have come to the end of the Gondor that you have known. Let me\par
pass!'\par
Then men fell back before the command of his voice and questioned him no\par
further, though they gazed in wonder at the hobbit that sat before him and at\par
the horse that bore him. For the people of the City used horses very little\par
and they were seldom seen in their streets, save only those ridden by the\par
errand-riders of their lord. And they said: 'Surely that is one of the great\par
steeds of the King of Rohan? Maybe the Rohirrim will come soon to strengthen\par
us.' But Shadowfax walked proudly up the long winding road.\par
For the fashion of Minas Tirith was such that it was built on seven\par
levels, each delved into the hill, and about each was set a wall, and in each\par
wall was a gate. But the gates were not set in a line: the Great Gate in the\par
City Wall was at the east point of the circuit, but the next faced half south,\par
and the third half north, and so to and fro upwards; so that the paved way\par
that climbed towards the Citadel turned first this way and then that across\par
the face of the hill. And each time that it passed the line of the Great Gate\par
it went through an arched tunnel, piercing a vast pier of rock whose huge outthrust\par
bulk divided in two all the circles of the City save the first. For\par
partly in the primeval shaping of the hill, partly by the mighty craft and\par
labour of old, there stood up from the rear of the wide court behind the Gate\par
a towering bastion of stone, its edge sharp as a ship-keel facing east. Up it\par
rose, even to the level of the topmost circle, and there was crowned by a\par
battlement; so that those in the Citadel might, like mariners in a mountainous\par
ship, look from its peak sheer down upon the Gate seven hundred feet below.\par
The entrance to the Citadel also looked eastward, but was delved in the heart\par
of the rock; thence a long lamp-lit slope ran up to the seventh gate. Thus men\par
reached at last the High Court, and the Place of the Fountain before the feet\par
of the White Tower: tall and shapely, fifty fathoms from its base to the\par
pinnacle, where the banner of the Stewards floated a thousand feet above the\par
plain.\par
A strong citadel it was indeed, and not to be taken by a host of enemies,\par
if there were any within that could hold weapons; unless some foe could come\par
behind and scale the lower skirts of Mindolluin, and so come upon the narrow\par
shoulder that joined the Hill of Guard to the mountain mass. But that\par
shoulder, which rose to the height of the fifth wall, was hedged with great\par
ramparts right up to the precipice that overhung its western end; and in that\par
space stood the houses and domed tombs of bygone kings and lords, for ever\par
silent between the mountain and the tower.\par
Pippin gazed in growing wonder at the great stone city, vaster and more\par
splendid than anything that he had dreamed of; greater and stronger than\par
Isengard, and far more beautiful. Yet it was in truth falling year by year\par
into decay; and already it lacked half the men that could have dwelt at ease\par
there. In every street they passed some great house or court over whose doors\par
and arched gates were carved many fair letters of strange and ancient shapes:\par
names Pippin guessed of great men and kindreds that had once dwelt there; and\par
yet now they were silent, and no footsteps rang on their wide pavements, nor\par
voice was heard in their halls, nor any face looked out from door or empty\par
window.\par
At last they came out of shadow to the seventh gate, and the warm sun\par
that shone down beyond the river, as Frodo walked in the glades of Ithilien,\par
glowed here on the smooth walls and rooted pillars, and the great arch with\par
keystone carven in the likeness of a crowned and kingly head. Gandalf\par
dismounted, for no horse was allowed in the Citadel, and Shadowfax suffered\par
himself to be led away at the soft word of his master.\par
The Guards of the gate were robed in black, and their helms were of\par
strange shape, high-crowned, with long cheek-guards close-fitting to the face,\par
and above the cheek-guards were set the white wings of sea-birds; but the\par
helms gleamed with a flame of silver, for they were indeed wrought of\par
_mithril_, heirlooms from the glory of old days. Upon the black surcoats were\par
embroidered in white a tree blossoming like snow beneath a silver crown and\par
many-pointed stars. This was the livery of the heirs of Elendil, and none wore\par
it now in all Gondor, save the Guards of the Citadel before the Court of the\par
Fountain where the White Tree once had grown.\par
Already it seemed that word of their coming had gone before them: and at\par
once they were admitted, silently, and without question. Quickly Gandalf\par
strode across the white-paved court. A sweet fountain played there in the\par
morning sun, and a sward of bright green lay about it; but in the midst.\par
drooping over the pool, stood a dead tree, and the falling drops dripped sadly\par
from its barren and broken branches back into the clear water.\par
Pippin glanced at it as he hurried after Gandalf. It looked mournful, he\par
thought, and he wondered why the dead tree was left in this place where\par
everything else was well tended.\par
_Seven stars and seven stones and one white tree._\par
The words that Gandalf had murmured came back into his mind. And then he\par
found himself at the doors of the great hall beneath the gleaming tower; and\par
behind the wizard he passed the tall silent door-wardens and entered the cool\par
echoing shadows of the house of stone.\par
They walked down a paved passage, long and empty, and as they went\par
Gandalf spoke softly to Pippin. 'Be careful of your words, Master Peregrin!\par
This is no time for hobbit pertness. Th\'e9oden is a kindly old man. Denethor is\par
of another sort, proud and subtle, a man of far greater lineage and power,\par
though he is not called a king. But he will speak most to you, and question\par
you much, since you can tell him of his son Boromir. He loved him greatly: too\par
much perhaps; and the more so because they were unlike. But under cover of\par
this love he will think it easier to learn what he witches from you rather\par
than from me. Do not tell him more than you need, and leave quiet the matter\par
of Frodo's errand. I will deal with that in due time. And say nothing about\par
Aragorn either, unless you must.'\par
'Why not? What is wrong with Strider?' Pippin whispered. 'He meant to\par
come here, didn't he? And he'll be arriving soon himself anyway.'\par
'Maybe, maybe,' said Gandalf. 'Though if he comes, it is likely to be in\par
some way that no one expects, not even Denethor. It will be better so. At\par
least he should come unheralded by us.'\par
Gandalf halted before a tall door of polished metal. 'See, Master Pippin,\par
there is no time to instruct you now in the history of Gondor; though it might\par
have been better, if you had learned something of it, when you were still\par
birds-nesting and playing truant in the woods of the Shire. Do as I bid! It is\par
scarcely wise when bringing the news of the death of his heir to a mighty lord\par
to speak over much of the coming of one who will, if he comes, claim the\par
kingship. Is that enough?'\par
'Kingship?' said Pippin amazed.\par
'Yes,' said Gandalf. 'If you have walked all these days with closed ears\par
and mind asleep, wake up now!' He knocked on the door.\par
The door opened, but no one could be seen to open it. Pippin looked into\par
a great hall. It was lit by deep windows in the wide aisles at either side,\par
beyond the rows of tall pillars that upheld the roof. Monoliths of black\par
marble, they rose to great capitals carved in many strange figures of beasts\par
and leaves; and far above in shadow the wide vaulting gleamed with dull gold,\par
inset with flowing traceries of many colours. No hangings nor storied webs,\par
nor any things of woven stuff or of wood, were to be seen in that long solemn\par
hall; but between the pillars there stood a silent company of tall images\par
graven in cold stone.\par
Suddenly Pippin was reminded of the hewn rocks of Argonath, and awe fell\par
on him, as he looked down that avenue of kings long dead. At the far end upon\par
a dais of many steps was set a high throne under a canopy of marble shaped\par
like a crowned helm; behind it was carved upon the wall and set with gems an\par
image of a tree in flower. But the throne was empty. At the foot of the dais,\par
upon the lowest step which was broad and deep, there was a stone chair, black\par
and unadorned, and on it sat an old man gazing at his lap. In his hand was a\par
white rod with a golden knob. He did not look up. Solemnly they paced the long\par
floor towards him, until they stood three paces from his footstool. Then\par
Gandalf spoke.\par
'Hail, Lord and Steward of Minas Tirith, Denethor son of Ecthelion! I am\par
come with counsel and tidings in this dark hour.'\par
Then the old man looked up. Pippin saw his carven face with its proud\par
bones and skin like ivory, and the long curved nose between the dark deep\par
eyes; and he was reminded not so much of Boromir as of Aragorn. 'Dark indeed\par
is the hour,' said the old man, 'and at such times you are wont to come,\par
Mithrandir. But though all the signs forebode that the doom of Gondor is\par
drawing nigh, less now to me is that darkness than my own darkness. It has\par
been told to me that you bring with you one who saw my son die. Is this he?'\par
'It is,' said Gandalf. 'One of the twain. The other is with Th\'e9oden of\par
Rohan and may come hereafter. Halflings they are, as you see, yet this is not\par
he of whom the omens spoke.'\par
'Yet a Halfling still,' said Denethor grimly, 'and little love do I bear\par
the name, since those accursed words came to trouble our counsels and drew\par
away my son on the wild errand to his death. My Boromir! Now we have need of\par
you. Faramir should have gone in his stead.'\par
'He would have gone,' said Gandalf. 'Be not unjust in your grief! Boromir\par
claimed the errand and would not suffer any other to have it. He was a\par
masterful man, and one to take what he desired. I journeyed far with him and\par
learned much of his mood. But you speak of his death. You have had news of\par
that ere we came?'\par
'I have received this,' said Denethor, and laying down his rod he lifted\par
from his lap the thing that he had been gazing at. In each hand he held up one\par
half of a great horn cloven through the middle: a wild-ox horn bound with\par
silver.\par
'That is the horn that Boromir always wore!' cried Pippin.\par
'Verily,' said Denethor. 'And in my turn I bore it, and so did each\par
eldest son of our house, far back into the vanished years before the failing\par
of the kings, since Vorondil father of Mardil hunted the wild kine of Araw in\par
the far fields of Rh\'fbn. I heard it blowing dim upon the northern marches\par
thirteen days ago, and the River brought it to me, broken: it will wind no\par
more.' He paused and there was a heavy silence. Suddenly he turned his black\par
glance upon Pippin. 'What say you to that, Halfling?'\par
'Thirteen, thirteen days,' faltered Pippin. 'Yes, I think that would be\par
so. Yes, I stood beside him, as he blew the horn. But no help came. Only more\par
orcs.'\par
'So,' said Denethor, looking keenly at Pippin's face. 'You were there?\par
Tell me more! Why did no help come? And how did you escape, and yet he did\par
not, so mighty a man as he was, and only orcs to withstand him?'\par
Pippin flushed and forgot his fear. 'The mightiest man may be slain by\par
one arrow,' he said; 'and Boromir was pierced by many. When last I saw him he\par
sank beside a tree and plucked a black-feathered shaft from his side. Then I\par
swooned and was made captive. I saw him no more, and know no more. But I\par
honour his memory, for he was very valiant. He died to save us, my kinsman\par
Meriadoc and myself, waylaid in the woods by the soldiery of the Dark Lord;\par
and though he fell and failed, my gratitude is none the less.'\par
Then Pippin looked the old man in the eye, for pride stirred strangely\par
within him, still stung by the scorn and suspicion in that cold voice. 'Little\par
service, no doubt, will so great a lord of Men think to find in a hobbit, a\par
halfling from the northern Shire; yet such as it is, I will offer it, in\par
payment of my debt.' Twitching aside his grey cloak, Pippin drew forth his\par
small sword and laid it at Denethor's feet.\par
A pale smile, like a gleam of cold sun on a winter's evening, passed over\par
the old man's face; but he bent his head and held out his hand, laying the\par
shards of the horn aside. 'Give me the weapon!' he said.\par
Pippin lifted it and presented the hilt to him. 'Whence came this?' said\par
Denethor. 'Many, many years lie on it. Surely this is a blade wrought by our\par
own kindred in the North in the deep past?'\par
'It came out of the mounds that lie on the borders of my country ' said\par
Pippin. 'But only evil wights dwell there now, and I will not willingly tell\par
more of them.'\par
'I see that strange tales are woven about you,' said Denethor, 'and once\par
again it is shown that looks may belie the man \endash  or the halfling. I accept\par
your service. For you are not daunted by words; and you have courteous speech,\par
strange though the sound of it may be to us in the South. And we shall have\par
need of all folk of courtesy, be they great or small, in the days to come.\par
Swear to me now!'\par
'Take the hilt,' said Gandalf, 'and speak after the Lord, if you are\par
resolved on this.'\par
'I am,' said Pippin.\par
The old man laid the sword along his lap, and Pippin put his hand to the\par
hilt, and said slowly after Denethor:\par
'Here do I swear fealty and service to Gondor, and to the Lord and\par
Steward of the realm, to speak and to be silent, to do and to let be, to come\par
and to go, in need or plenty, in peace or war, in living or dying, from this\par
hour henceforth, until my lord release me, or death take me, or the world end.\par
So say I, Peregrin son of Paladin of the Shire of the Halflings.'\par
And this do I hear, Denethor son of Ecthelion, Lord of Gondor, Steward of\par
the High King, and I will not forget it, nor fail to reward that which is\par
given: fealty with love, valour with honour, oath-breaking with vengeance.'\par
Then Pippin received back his sword and put it in its sheath.\par
'And now,' said Denethor, 'my first command to you: speak and be not\par
silent! Tell me your full tale, and see that you recall all that you can of\par
Boromir, my son. Sit now and begin!' As he spoke he struck a small silver gong\par
that stood near his footstool, and at once servants came forward. Pippin saw\par
then that they had been standing in alcoves on either side of the door, unseen\par
as he and Gandalf entered.\par
'Bring wine and food and seats for the guests,' said Denethor, 'and see\par
that none trouble us for one hour.'\par
'It is all that I have to spare, for there is much else to heed,' he said\par
to Gandalf. 'Much of more import, it may seem, and yet to me less pressing.\par
But maybe we can speak again at the end of the day.'\par
'And earlier, it is to be hoped,' said Gandalf. 'For I have not ridden\par
hither from Isengard, one hundred and fifty leagues, with the speed of wind,\par
only to bring you one small warrior, however courteous. Is it naught to you\par
that Th\'e9oden has fought a great battle and that Isengard is overthrown, and\par
that I have broken the staff of Saruman?'\par
'It is much to me. But I know already sufficient of these deeds for my\par
own counsel against the menace of the East.' He turned his dark eyes on\par
Gandalf, and now Pippin saw a likeness between the two, and he felt the strain\par
between them, almost as if he saw a line of smouldering fire, drawn from eye\par
to eye, that might suddenly burst into flame.\par
Denethor looked indeed much more like a great wizard than Gandalf did,\par
more kingly, beautiful, and powerful; and older. Yet by a sense other than\par
sight Pippin perceived that Gandalf had the greater power and the deeper\par
wisdom, and a majesty that was veiled. And he was older, far older. 'How much\par
older?' he wondered, and then he thought how odd it was that he had never\par
thought about it before. Treebeard had said something about wizards, but even\par
then he had not thought of Gandalf as one of them. What was Gandalf? In what\par
far time and place did he come into the world, and when would he leave it? And\par
then his musings broke off, and he saw that Denethor and Gandalf still looked\par
each other in the eye, as if reading the other's mind. But it was Denethor who\par
first withdrew his gaze.\par
'Yea,' he said; 'for though the Stones be lost, they say, still the lords\par
of Gondor have keener sight than lesser men, and many messages come to them.\par
But sit now!'\par
Then men came bearing a chair and a low stool, and one brought a salver\par
with a silver flagon and cups, and white cakes. Pippin sat down, but he could\par
not take his eyes from the old lord. Was it so, or had he only imagined it,\par
that as he spoke of the Stones a sudden gleam of his eye had glanced upon\par
Pippin's face?\par
'Now tell me your tale, my liege,' said Denethor, half kindly; half\par
mockingly. 'For the words of one whom my son so befriended will be welcome\par
indeed.'\par
Pippin never forgot that hour in the great hall under the piercing eye of\par
the Lord of Gondor, stabbed ever and anon by his shrewd questions, and all the\par
while conscious of Gandalf at his side, watching and listening, and (so Pippin\par
felt) holding in check a rising wrath and impatience. When the hour was over\par
and Denethor again rang the gong, Pippin felt worn out. 'It cannot be more\par
than nine o'clock,' he thought. 'I could now eat three breakfasts on end.'\par
'Lead the Lord Mithrandir to the housing prepared for him,' said\par
Denethor, 'and his companion may lodge with him for the present, if he will.\par
But be it known that I have now sworn him to my service, and he shall be known\par
as Peregrin son of Paladin and taught the lesser pass-words. Send word to the\par
Captains that they shall wait on me here, as soon as may be after the third\par
hour has rung.\par
'And you, my Lord Mithrandir, shall come too, as and when you will. None\par
shall hinder your coming to me at any time, save only in my brief hours of\par
sleep. Let your wrath at an old man's folly run off and then return to my\par
comfort!'\par
'Folly?' said Gandalf. 'Nay, my lord, when you are a dotard you will die.\par
You can use even your grief as a cloak. Do you think that I do not understand\par
your purpose in questioning for an hour one who knows the least, while I sit\par
by?'\par
'If you understand it, then be content,' returned Denethor. 'Pride would\par
be folly that disdained help and counsel at need; but you deal out such gifts\par
according to your own designs. Yet the Lord of Gondor is not to be made the\par
tool of other men's purposes, however worthy. And to him there is no purpose\par
higher in the world as it now stands than the good of Gondor; and the rule of\par
Gondor, my lord, is mine and no other man's, unless the king should come\par
again.'\par
'Unless the king should come again?' said Gandalf. 'Well, my lord\par
Steward, it is your task to keep some kingdom still against that event, which\par
few now look to see. In that task you shall have all the aid that you are\par
pleased to ask for. But I will say this: the rule of no realm is mine, neither\par
of Gondor nor any other, great or small. But all worthy things that are in\par
peril as the world now stands, those are my care. And for my part, I shall not\par
wholly fail of my task, though Gondor should perish, if anything passes\par
through this night that can still grow fair or bear fruit and flower again in\par
days to come. For I also am a steward. Did you not know?' And with that he\par
turned and strode from the hall with Pippin running at his side.\par
Gandalf did not look at Pippin or speak a word to him as they went. Their\par
guide brought them from the doors of the hall, and then led them across the\par
Court of the Fountain into a lane between tall buildings of stone. After\par
several turns they came to a house close to the wall of the citadel upon the\par
north side, not far from the shoulder that linked the hill with the mountain.\par
Within, upon the first floor above the street, up a wide carven stair, he\par
showed them to a fair room, light and airy, with goodly hangings of dull gold\par
sheen unfigured. It was sparely furnished, having but a small table, two\par
chairs and a bench; but at either side there were curtained alcoves and wellclad\par
beds within with vessels and basins for washing. There were three high\par
narrow windows that looked northward over the great curve of Anduin, still\par
shrouded in mists, towards the Emyn Muil and Rauros far away. Pippin had to\par
climb on the bench to look out over the deep stone sill.\par
'Are you angry with me, Gandalf?' he said, as their guide went out and\par
closed the door. 'I did the best I could.'\par
'You did indeed!' said Gandalf, laughing suddenly; and he came and stood\par
beside Pippin, putting his arm about the hobbit's shoulders and gazing out of\par
the window. Pippin glanced in some wonder at the face now close beside his\par
own, for the sound of that laugh had been gay and merry. Yet in the wizard's\par
face he saw at first only lines of care and sorrow; though as he looked more\par
intently he perceived that under all there was a great joy: a fountain of\par
mirth enough to set a kingdom laughing, were it to gush forth.\par
'Indeed you did your best,' said the wizard; 'and I hope that it may be\par
long before you find yourself in such a tight corner again between two such\par
terrible old men. Still the Lord of Gondor learned more from you than you may\par
have guessed, Pippin. You could not hide the fact that Boromir did not lead\par
the Company from Moria, and that there was one among you of high honour who\par
was coming to Minas Tirith; and that he had a famous sword. Men think much\par
about the stories of old days in Gondor; and Denethor has given long thought\par
to the rhyme and to the words _Isildur's Bane_, since Boromir went away.\par
'He is not as other men of this time, Pippin, and whatever be his descent\par
from father to son, by some chance the blood of Westernesse runs nearly true\par
in him; as it does in his other son, Faramir, and yet did not in Boromir whom\par
he loved best. He has long sight. He can perceive, if he bends his will\par
thither, much of what is passing in the minds of men, even of those that dwell\par
far off. It is difficult to deceive him, and dangerous to try.\par
'Remember that! For you are now sworn to his service. I do not know what\par
put it into your head, or your heart, to do that. But it was well done. I did\par
not hinder it, for generous deed should not be checked by cold counsel. It\par
touched his heart, as well (may I say it) as pleasing his humour. And at least\par
you are free now to move about as you will in Minas Tirith \endash  when you are not\par
on duty. For there is another side to it. You are at his command; and he will\par
not forget. Be wary still!'\par
He fell silent and sighed. 'Well, no need to brood on what tomorrow may\par
bring. For one thing, tomorrow will be certain to bring worse than today, for\par
many days to come. And there is nothing more that I can do to help it. The\par
board is set, and the pieces are moving. One piece that I greatly desire to\par
find is Faramir, now the heir of Denethor. I do not think that he is in the\par
City; but I have had no time to gather news. I must go. Pippin. I must go to\par
this lords' council and learn what I can. But the Enemy has the move, and he\par
is about to open his full game. And pawns are likely to see as much of it as\par
any, Peregrin son of Paladin, soldier of Gondor. Sharpen your blade!'\par
Gandalf went to the door, and there he turned. 'I am in haste Pippin,' he\par
said. 'Do me a favour when you go out. Even before you rest, if you are not\par
too weary. Go and find Shadowfax and see how he is housed. These people are\par
kindly to beasts, for they are a good and wise folk, but they have less skill\par
with horses than some.'\par
With that Gandalf went out; and as he did so, there came the note of a\par
clear sweet bell ringing in a tower of the citadel. Three strokes it rang,\par
like silver in the air, and ceased: the third hour from the rising of the sun.\par
After a minute Pippin went to the door and down the stair and looked\par
about the street. The sun was now shining warm and bright, and the towers and\par
tall houses cast long clear-cut shadows westward. High in the blue air Mount\par
Mindolluin lifted its white helm and snowy cloak. Armed men went to and fro in\par
the ways of the City, as if going at the striking of the hour to changes of\par
post and duty.\par
'Nine o'clock we'd call it in the Shire,' said Pippin aloud to himself.\par
'Just the time for a nice breakfast by the open window in spring sunshine. And\par
how I should like breakfast! Do these people ever have it, or is it over? And\par
when do they have dinner, and where?'\par
Presently he noticed a man, clad in black and white, coming along the\par
narrow street from the centre of the citadel towards him. Pippin felt lonely\par
and made up his mind to speak as the man passed; but he had no need. The man\par
came straight up to him.\par
'You are Peregrin the Halfling?' he said. 'I am told that you have been\par
sworn to the service of the Lord and of the City. Welcome! He held out his\par
hand and Pippin took it.\par
'I am named Beregond son of Baranor. I have no duty this morning, and I\par
have been sent to you to teach you the pass-words, and to tell you some of the\par
many things that no doubt you will wish to know. And for my part, I would\par
learn of you also. For never before have we seen a halfling in this land and\par
though we have heard rumour of them, little is said of them in any tale that\par
we know. Moreover you are a friend of Mithrandir. Do you know him well?'\par
'Well,' said Pippin. 'I have known _of_ him all my short life, as you\par
might say; and lately I have travelled far with him. But there is much to read\par
in that book, and I cannot claim to have seen more than a page or two. Yet\par
perhaps I know him as well as any but a few. Aragorn was the only one of our\par
Company, I think, who really knew him.'\par
'Aragorn?' said Beregond. 'Who is he?'\par
'Oh,' stammered Pippin, 'he was a man who went about with us. I think he\par
is in Rohan now.'\par
'You have been in Rohan, I hear. There is much that I would ask you of\par
that land also; for we put much of what little hope we have in its people. But\par
I am forgetting my errand, which was first to answer what you would ask. What\par
would you know, Master Peregrin?'\par
'Er well,' said Pippin, 'if I may venture to say so, rather a burning\par
question in my mind at present is, well, what about breakfast and all that? I\par
mean, what are the meal-times, if you understand me, and where is the diningroom,\par
if there is one? And the inns? I looked, but never a one could I see as\par
we rode up, though I had been borne up by the hope of a draught of ale as soon\par
as we came to the homes of wise and courtly men.'\par
Beregond looked at him gravely. 'An old campaigner, I see,' he said.\par
'They say that men who go warring afield look ever to the next hope of food\par
and of drink; though I am not a travelled man myself. Then you have not yet\par
eaten today?'\par
'Well, yes, to speak in courtesy, yes,' said Pippin. 'But no more than a\par
cup of wine and a white cake or two by the kindness of your lord; but he\par
racked me for it with an hour of questions, and that is hungry work.'\par
Beregond laughed. 'At the table small men may do the greater deeds, we\par
say. But you have broken your fast as well as any man in the Citadel, and with\par
greater honour. This is a fortress and a tower of guard and is now in posture\par
of war. We rise ere the Sun, and take a morsel in the grey light, and go to\par
our duties at the opening hour. But do not despair!' He laughed again, seeing\par
the dismay in Pippin's face. 'Those who have had heavy duty take somewhat to\par
refresh their strength in the mid-morning. Then there is the nuncheon, at noon\par
or after as duties allow; and men gather for the daymeal, and such mirth as\par
there still may be, about the hour of sunset.\par
'Come! We will walk a little and then go find us some refreshment, and\par
eat and drink on the battlement, and survey the fair morning.'\par
'One moment!' said Pippin blushing. 'Greed, or hunger by your courtesy,\par
put it out of my mind. But Gandalf, Mithrandir as you call him, asked me to\par
see to his horse \endash  Shadowfax, a great steed of Rohan, and the apple of the\par
king's eye, I am told, though he has given him to Mithrandir for his services.\par
I think his new master loves the beast better than he loves many men, and if\par
his good will is of any value to this city, you will treat Shadowfax with all\par
honour: with greater kindness than you have treated this hobbit, if it is\par
possible.'\par
'Hobbit?' said Beregond.\par
'That is what we call ourselves,' said Pippin.\par
'I am glad to learn it,' said Beregond, 'for now I may say that strange\par
accents do not mar fair speech, and hobbits are a fair-spoken folk. But come!\par
You shall make me acquainted with this good horse. I love beasts, and we see\par
them seldom in this stony city; for my people came from the mountain-vales,\par
and before that from Ithilien. But fear not! The visit shall be short, a mere\par
call of courtesy, and we will go thence to the butteries.'\par
Pippin found that Shadowfax had been well housed and tended. For in the\par
sixth circle, outside the walls of the citadel, there were some fair stables\par
where a few swift horses were kept, hard by the lodgings of the errand-riders\par
of the Lord: messengers always ready to go at the urgent command of Denethor\par
or his chief captains. But now all the horses and the riders were out and\par
away.\par
Shadowfax whinnied as Pippin entered the stable and turned his head.\par
'Good morning!' said Pippin. 'Gandalf will come as soon as he may. He is busy,\par
but he sends greetings, and I am to see that all is well with you; and you\par
resting, I hope, after your long labours.'\par
Shadowfax tossed his head and stamped. But he allowed Beregond to handle\par
his head gently and stroke his great flanks.\par
'He looks as if he were spoiling for a race, and not newly come from a\par
great journey,' said Beregond. 'How strong and proud he is! Where is his\par
harness? It should be rich and fair.'\par
'None is rich and fair enough for him,' said Pippin. 'He will have none.\par
If he will consent to bear you, bear you he does; and if not, well, no bit,\par
bridle, whip, or thong will tame him. Farewell, Shadowfax! Have patience.\par
Battle is coming.'\par
Shadowfax lifted up his head and neighed, so that the stable shook, and\par
they covered their ears. Then they took their leave, seeing that the manger\par
was well filled.\par
'And now for our manger,' said Beregond, and he led Pippin back to the\par
citadel, and so to a door in the north side of the great tower. There they\par
went down a long cool stair into a wide alley lit with lamps. There were\par
hatches in the walls at the side, and one of these was open.\par
'This is the storehouse and buttery of my company of the Guard.' said\par
Beregond. 'Greetings, Targon!' he called through the hatch. 'It is early yet,\par
but here is a newcomer that the Lord has taken into his service. He has ridden\par
long and far with a tight belt, and has had sore labour this morning, and he\par
is hungry. Give us what you have!'\par
They got there bread, and butter, and cheese and apples: the last of the\par
winter store, wrinkled but sound and sweet; and a leather flagon of new-drawn\par
ale, and wooden platters and cups. They put all into a wicker basket and\par
climbed back into the sun; and Beregond brought Pippin to a place at the east\par
end of the great out-thrust battlement where there was an embrasure in the\par
walls with a stone seat beneath the sill. From there they could look out on\par
the morning over the world.\par
They ate and drank; and they talked now of Gondor and its ways and\par
customs, now of the Shire and the strange countries that Pippin had seen. And\par
ever as they talked Beregond was more amazed, and looked with greater wonder\par
at the hobbit, swinging his short legs as he sat on the seat, or standing\par
tiptoe upon it to peer over the sill at the lands below.\par
'I will not hide from you, Master Peregrin,' said Beregond, 'that to us\par
you look almost as one of our children, a lad of nine summers or so; and yet\par
you have endured perils and seen marvels that few of our greybeards could\par
boast of. I thought it was the whim of our Lord to take him a noble page,\par
after the manner of the kings of old, they say. But I see that it is not so,\par
and you must pardon my foolishness.'\par
'I do,' said Pippin. 'Though you are not far wrong. I am still little\par
more than a boy in the reckoning of my own people, and it will be four years\par
yet before I "come of age", as we say in the Shire: But do not bother about\par
me. Come and look and tell me what I can see.'\par
The sun was now climbing, and the mists in the vale below had been drawn\par
up. The last of them were floating away, just overhead, as wisps of white\par
cloud borne on the stiffening breeze from the East, that was now flapping and\par
tugging the flags and white standards of the citadel. Away down in the valleybottom,\par
five leagues or so as the eye leaps, the Great River could now be seen\par
grey and glittering, coming out of the north-west, and bending in a mighty\par
sweep south and west again, till it was lost to view in a haze and shimmer,\par
far beyond which lay the Sea fifty leagues away.\par
Pippin could see all the Pelennor laid out before him, dotted into the\par
distance with farmsteads and little walls, barns and byres, but nowhere could\par
he see any kine or other beasts. Many roads and tracks crossed the green\par
fields, and there was much coming and going: wains moving in lines towards the\par
Great Gate, and others passing out. Now and again a horseman would ride up,\par
and leap from the saddle and hasten into the City. But most of the traffic\par
went out along the chief highway, and that turned south, and then bending\par
swifter than the River skirted the hills and passed soon from sight. It was\par
wide and well-paved, and along its eastern edge ran a broad green ridingtrack,\par
and beyond that a wall. On the ride horsemen galloped to and fro, but\par
all the street seemed to be choked with great covered wains going south. But\par
soon Pippin saw that all was in fact well-ordered: the wains were moving in\par
three lines, one swifter drawn by horses; another slower, great waggons with\par
fair housings of many colours, drawn by oxen; and along the west rim of the\par
road many smaller carts hauled by trudging men.\par
'That is the road to the vales of Tumladen and Lossarnach, and the\par
mountain-villages, and then on to Lebennin,' said Beregond. 'There go the last\par
of the wains that bear away to refuge the aged the children, and the women\par
that must go with them. They must all be gone from the Gate and the road clear\par
for a league before noon: that was the order. It is a sad necessity.' He\par
sighed. 'Few, maybe, of those now sundered will meet again. And there were\par
always too few children in this city; but now there are none-save some young\par
lads that will not depart, and may find some task to do: my own son is one of\par
them.'\par
They fell silent for a while. Pippin gazed anxiously eastward, as if at\par
any moment he might see thousands of orcs pouring over the fields. 'What can I\par
see there?' he asked, pointing down to the middle of the great curve of the\par
Anduin. 'Is that another city, or what is it?'\par
'It was a city,' said Beregond, 'the chief city of Gondor, of which this\par
was only a fortress. For that is the ruin of Osgiliath on either side of\par
Anduin, which our enemies took and burned long ago. Yet we won it back in the\par
days of the youth of Denethor: not to dwell in, but to hold as an outpost, and\par
to rebuild the bridge for the passage of our arms. And then came the Fell\par
Riders out of Minas Morgul.'\par
'The Black Riders?' said Pippin, opening his eyes, and they were wide and\par
dark with an old fear re-awakened.\par
'Yes, they were black,' said Beregond, 'and I see that you know something\par
of them, though you have not spoken of them in any of your tales.'\par
'I know of them,' said Pippin softly, 'but I will not speak of them now,\par
so near, so near.' He broke off and lifted his eyes above the River, and it\par
seemed to him that all he could see was a vast and threatening shadow. Perhaps\par
it was mountains looming on the verge of sight, their jagged edges softened by\par
wellnigh twenty leagues of misty air; perhaps it was but a cloud-wall, and\par
beyond that again a yet deeper gloom. But even as he looked it seemed to his\par
eyes that the gloom was growing and gathering, very slowly, slowly rising to\par
smother the regions of the sun.\par
'So near to Mordor?' said Beregond quietly. 'Yes, there it lies. We\par
seldom name it; but we have dwelt ever in sight of that shadow: sometimes it\par
seems fainter and more distant; sometimes nearer and darker. It is growing and\par
darkening now; and therefore our fear and disquiet grow too. And the Fell\par
Riders, less than a year ago they won back the crossings, and many of our best\par
men were slain. Boromir it was that drove the enemy at last back from this\par
western shore, and we hold still the near half of Osgiliath. For a little\par
while. But we await now a new onslaught there. Maybe the chief onslaught of\par
the war that comes.'\par
'When?' said Pippin. 'Have you a guess? For I saw the beacons last night\par
and the errand-riders; and Gandalf said that it was a sign that war had begun.\par
He seemed in a desperate hurry. But now everything seems to have slowed up\par
again.'\par
'Only because everything is now ready,' said Beregond. 'It is but the\par
deep breath before the plunge.'\par
'But why were the beacons lit last night?'\par
'It is over-late to send for aid when you are already besieged,' answered\par
Beregond. 'But I do not know the counsel of the Lord and his captains. They\par
have many ways of gathering news. And the Lord Denethor is unlike other men:\par
he sees far. Some say that as he sits alone in his high chamber in the Tower\par
at night, and bends his thought this way and that, he can read somewhat of the\par
future; and that he will at times search even the mind of the Enemy, wrestling\par
with him. And so it is that he is old, worn before his time. But however that\par
may be, my lord Faramir is abroad, beyond the River on some perilous errand,\par
and he may have sent tidings.\par
'But if you would know what I think set the beacons ablaze, it was the\par
news that came yestereve out of Lebennin. There is a great fleet drawing near\par
to the mouths of Anduin, manned by the corsairs of Umbar in the South. They\par
have long ceased to fear the might of Gondor, and they have allied them with\par
the Enemy, and now make a heavy stroke in his cause. For this attack will draw\par
off much of the help that we looked to have from Lebennin and Belfalas, where\par
folk are hardy and numerous. All the more do our thoughts go north to Rohan;\par
and the more glad are we for these tidings of victory that you bring.\par
'And yet' \endash  he paused and stood up, and looked round, north, east, and\par
south \endash  'the doings at Isengard should warn us that we are caught now in a\par
great net and strategy. This is no longer a bickering at the fords, raiding\par
from Ithilien and from An\'f3rien, ambushing and pillaging. This is a great war\par
long-planned, and we are but one piece in it, whatever pride may say. Things\par
move in the far East beyond the Inland Sea, it is reported; and north in\par
Mirkwood and beyond; and south in Harad. And now all realms shall be put to\par
the test, to stand, or fall \endash  under the Shadow.\par
'Yet, Master Peregrin, we have this honour: ever we bear the brunt of the\par
chief hatred of the Dark Lord, for that hatred comes down out of the depths of\par
time and over the deeps of the Sea. Here will the hammer-stroke fall hardest.\par
And for that reason Mithrandir came hither in such haste. For if we fall, who\par
shall stand? And, Master Peregrin, do you see any hope that we shall stand?'\par
Pippin did not answer. He looked at the great walls, and the towers and\par
brave banners, and the sun in the high sky, and then at the gathering gloom in\par
the East; and he thought of the long fingers of that Shadow: of the orcs in\par
the woods and the mountains, the treason of Isengard, the birds of evil eye,\par
and the Black Riders even in the lanes of the Shire \endash  and of the winged\par
terror, the Nazg\'fbl. He shuddered, and hope seemed to wither. And even at that\par
moment the sun for a second faltered and was obscured, as though a dark wing\par
had passed across it. Almost beyond hearing he thought he caught, high and far\par
up in the heavens, a cry: faint, but heart-quelling, cruel and cold. He\par
blanched and cowered against the wall.\par
'What was that?' asked Beregond. 'You also felt something?'\par
'Yes,' muttered Pippin. 'It is the sign of our fall, and the shadow of\par
doom, a Fell Rider of the air.'\par
'Yes, the shadow of doom,' said Beregond. 'I fear that Minas Tirith shall\par
fall. Night comes. The very warmth of my blood seems stolen away.'\par
For a time they sat together with bowed heads and did not speak. Then\par
suddenly Pippin looked up and saw that the sun was still shining and the\par
banners still streaming in the breeze. He shook himself. 'It is passed,' he\par
said. 'No, my heart will not yet despair. Gandalf fell and has returned and is\par
with us. We may stand, if only on one leg, or at least be left still upon our\par
knees.'\par
'Rightly said!' cried Beregond, rising and striding to and fro. 'Nay,\par
though all things must come utterly to an end in time, Gondor shall not perish\par
yet. Not though the walls be taken by a reckless foe that will build a hill of\par
carrion before them. There are still other fastnesses, and secret ways of\par
escape into the mountains. Hope and memory shall live still in some hidden\par
valley where the grass is green.'\par
'All the same, I wish it was over for good or ill.' said Pippin. 'I am no\par
warrior at all and dislike any thought of battle; but waiting on the edge of\par
one that I can't escape is worst of all. What a long day it seems already! I\par
should be happier, if we were not obliged to stand and watch, making no move,\par
striking nowhere first. No stroke would have been struck in Rohan, I think,\par
but for Gandalf.'\par
'Ah, there you lay your finger on the sore that many feel!' said\par
Beregond. 'But things may change when Faramir returns. He is bold, more bold\par
than many deem; for in these days men are slow to believe that a captain can\par
be wise and learned in the scrolls of lore and song, as he is, and yet a man\par
of hardihood and swift judgement in the field. But such is Faramir. Less\par
reckless and eager than Boromir, but not less resolute. Yet what indeed can he\par
do? We cannot assault the mountains of \endash  of yonder realm. Our reach is\par
shortened, and we cannot strike till some foe comes within it. Then our hand\par
must be heavy!' He smote the hilt of his sword.\par
Pippin looked at him: tall and proud and noble, as all the men that he\par
had yet seen in that land; and with a glitter in his eye as he thought of the\par
battle. 'Alas! my own hand feels as light as a feather,' he thought, but he\par
said nothing. 'A pawn did Gandalf say? Perhaps but on the wrong chessboard.'\par
So they talked until the sun reached its height, and suddenly the noonbells\par
were rung, and there was a stir in the citadel; for all save the\par
watchmen were going to their meal.\par
'Will you come with me?' said Beregond. 'You may join my mess for this\par
day. I do not know to what company you will be assigned; or the Lord may hold\par
you at his own command. But you will be welcome. And it will be well to meet\par
as many men as you may, while there is yet time.'\par
'I shall be glad to come,' said Pippin. 'I am lonely, to tell you the\par
truth. I left my best friend behind in Rohan, and I have had no one to talk to\par
or jest with. Perhaps I could really join your company? Are you the captain?\par
If so, you could take me on, or speak for me?'\par
'Nay, nay,' Beregond laughed, 'I am no captain. Neither office nor rank\par
nor lordship have I, being but a plain man of arms of the Third Company of the\par
Citadel. Yet, Master Peregrin, to be only a man of arms of the Guard of the\par
Tower of Gondor is held worthy in the City, and such men have honour in the\par
land.'\par
'Then it is far beyond me,' said Pippin. 'Take me back to our room, and\par
if Gandalf is not there, I will go where you like \endash  as your guest.'\par
Gandalf was not in the lodging and had sent no message; so Pippin went\par
with Beregond and was made known to the men of the Third Company. And it\par
seemed that Beregond got as much honour from it as his guest, for Pippin was\par
very welcome. There had already been much talk in the citadel about\par
Mithrandir's companion and his long closeting with the Lord; and rumour\par
declared that a Prince of the Halflings had come out of the North to offer\par
allegiance to Gondor and five thousand swords. And some said that when the\par
Riders came from Rohan each would bring behind him a halfling warrior, small\par
maybe, but doughty.\par
Though Pippin had regretfully to destroy this hopeful tale, he could not\par
be rid of his new rank, only fitting, men thought, to one befriended by\par
Boromir and honoured by the Lord Denethor; and they thanked him for coming\par
among them, and hung on his words and stories of the outlands, and gave him as\par
much food and ale as he could wish. Indeed his only trouble was to be 'wary'\par
according to the counsel of Gandalf, and not to let his tongue wag freely\par
after the manner of a hobbit among friends.\par
At length Beregond rose. 'Farewell for this time!' he said. 'I have duty\par
now till sundown, as have all the others here, I think. But if you are lonely,\par
as you say, maybe you would like a merry guide about the City. My son would go\par
with you gladly. A good lad, I may say. If that pleases you, go down to the\par
lowest circle and ask for the Old Guesthouse in the Rath Celerdain, the\par
Lampwrights' Street. You will find him there with other lads that are\par
remaining in the City. There may be things worth seeing down at the Great Gate\par
ere the closing.'\par
He went out, and soon after all the others followed. The day was still\par
fine, though it was growing hazy, and it was hot for March, even so far\par
southwards. Pippin felt sleepy, but the lodging seemed cheerless, and he\par
decided to go down and explore the City. He took a few morsels that he had\par
saved to Shadowfax, and they were graciously accepted, though the horse seemed\par
to have no lack. Then he walked on down many winding ways.\par
People stared much as he passed. To his face men were gravely courteous,\par
saluting him after the manner of Gondor with bowed head and hands upon the\par
breast; but behind him he heard many calls, as those out of doors cried to\par
others within to come and see the Prince of the Halflings, the companion of\par
Mithrandir. Many used some other tongue than the Common Speech, but it was not\par
long before he learned at least what was meant by _Ernil i Pheriannath_ and\par
knew that his title had gone down before him into the City.\par
He came at last by arched streets and many fair alleys and pavements to\par
the lowest and widest circle, and there he was directed to the Lampwrights'\par
Street, a broad way running towards the Great Gate. In it he found the Old\par
Guesthouse, a large building of grey weathered stone with two wings running\par
back from the street, and between them a narrow greensward, behind which was\par
the many-windowed house, fronted along its whole width by a pillared porch and\par
a flight of steps down on to the grass. Boys were playing among the pillars,\par
the only children that Pippin had seen in Minas Tirith, and he stopped to look\par
at them. Presently one of them caught sight of him, and with a shout he sprang\par
across the grass and came into the street, followed by several others. There\par
he stood in front of Pippin, looking him up and down.\par
'Greetings!' said the lad. 'Where do you come from? You are a stranger in\par
the City.'\par
'I was,' said Pippin; 'but they say I have become a man of Gondor.'\par
'Oh come!' said the lad. 'Then we are all men here. But how old are you,\par
and what is your name? I am ten years already, and shall soon be five feet. I\par
am taller than you. But then my father is a Guard, one of the tallest. What is\par
your father?'\par
'Which question shall I answer first?' said Pippin. 'My father farms the\par
lands round Whitwell near Tuckborough in the Shire. I am nearly twenty-nine,\par
so I pass you there; though I am but four feet, and not likely to grow any\par
more, save sideways.'\par
'Twenty-nine!' said the lad and whistled. 'Why, you are quite old! As old\par
as my uncle Iorlas. Still,' he added hopefully, 'I wager I could stand you on\par
your head or lay you on your back.'\par
'Maybe you could, if I let you,' said Pippin with a laugh. 'And maybe I\par
could do the same to you: we know some wrestling tricks in my little country.\par
Where, let me tell you, I am considered uncommonly large and strong; and I\par
have never allowed anyone to stand me on my head. So if it came to a trial and\par
nothing else would serve, I might have to kill you. For when you are older,\par
you will learn that folk are not always what they seem; and though you may\par
have taken me for a soft stranger-lad and easy prey, let me warn you: I am\par
not, I am a halfling, hard, bold, and wicked!' Pippin pulled such a grim face\par
that the boy stepped back a pace, but at once he returned with clenched fists\par
and the light of battle in his eye.\par
'No!' Pippin laughed. 'Don't believe what strangers say of themselves\par
either! I am not a fighter. But it would be politer in any case for the\par
challenger to say who he is.'\par
The boy drew himself up proudly. 'I am Bergil son of Beregond of the\par
Guards,' he said.\par
'So I thought,' said Pippin, 'for you look like your father. I know him\par
and he sent me to find you.'\par
'Then why did you not say so at once?' said Bergil, and suddenly a look\par
of dismay came over his face. 'Do not tell me that he has changed his mind,\par
and will send me away with the maidens! But no, the last wains have gone.'\par
'His message is less bad than that, if not good.' said Pippin. 'He says\par
that if you would prefer it to standing me on my head, you might show me round\par
the City for a while and cheer my loneliness. I can tell you some tales of far\par
countries in return.'\par
Bergil clapped his hands, and laughed with relief. 'All is well,' he\par
cried. 'Come then! We were soon going to the Gate to look on. We will go now.'\par
'What is happening there?'\par
'The Captains of the Outlands are expected up the South Road ere sundown.\par
Come with us and you will see.'\par
Bergil proved a good comrade, the best company Pippin had had since he\par
parted from Merry, and soon they were laughing and talking gaily as they went\par
about the streets, heedless of the many glances that men gave them. Before\par
long they found themselves in a throng going towards the Great Gate. There\par
Pippin went up much in the esteem of Bergil, for when he spoke his name and\par
the pass-word the guard saluted him and let him pass through; and what was\par
more, he allowed him to take his companion with him.\par
'That is good!' said Bergil. 'We boys are no longer allowed to pass the\par
Gate without an elder. Now we shall see better.'\par
Beyond the Gate there was a crowd of men along the verge of the road and\par
of the great paved space into which all the ways to Minas Tirith ran. All eyes\par
were turned southwards, and soon a murmur rose: 'There is dust away there!\par
They are coming!'\par
Pippin and Bergil edged their way forward to the front of the crowd, and\par
waited. Horns sounded at some distance, and the noise of cheering rolled\par
towards them like a gathering wind. Then there was a loud trumpet-blast, and\par
all about them people were shouting.\par
'Forlong! Forlong!' Pippin heard men calling. 'What do they say?' he\par
asked.\par
'Forlong has come,' Bergil answered; 'old Forlong the Fat, the Lord of\par
Lossarnach. That is where my grandsire lives. Hurrah! Here he is. Good old\par
Forlong!'\par
Leading the line there came walking a big thick-limbed horse, and on it\par
sat a man of wide shoulders and huge girth, but old and grey-bearded, yet\par
mail-clad and black-helmed and bearing a long heavy spear. Behind him marched\par
proudly a dusty line of men, well-armed and bearing great battle-axes; grimfaced\par
they were, and shorter and somewhat swarthier than any men that Pippin\par
had yet seen in Gondor.\par
'Forlong!' men shouted. 'True heart, true friend! Forlong!' But when the\par
men of Lossarnach had passed they muttered: 'So few! Two hundreds, what are\par
they? We hoped for ten times the number. That will be the new tidings of the\par
black fleet. They are sparing only a tithe of their strength. Still every\par
little is a gain.'\par
And so the companies came and were hailed and cheered and passed through\par
the Gate, men of the Outlands marching to defend the City of Gondor in a dark\par
hour; but always too few, always less than hope looked for or need asked. The\par
men of Ringl\'f3 Vale behind the son of their lord, Dervorin striding on foot:\par
three hundreds. From the uplands of Morthond, the great Blackroot Vale, tall\par
Duinhir with his sons, Duilin and Derufin, and five hundred bowmen. From the\par
Anfalas, the Langstrand far away, a long line of men of many sorts, hunters\par
and herdsmen and men of little villages, scantily equipped save for the\par
household of Golasgil their lord. From Lamedon, a few grim hillmen without a\par
captain. Fisher-folk of the Ethir, some hundred or more spared from the ships.\par
Hirluin the Fair of the Green Hills from Pinnath Gelin with three hundreds of\par
gallant green-clad men. And last and proudest, Imrahil, Prince of Dol Amroth,\par
kinsman of the Lord, with gilded banners bearing his token of the Ship and the\par
Silver Swan, and a company of knights in full harness riding grey horses; and\par
behind them seven hundreds of men at arms, tall as lords, grey-eyed, darkhaired,\par
singing as they came.\par
And that was all, less than three thousands full told. No more would\par
come. Their cries and the tramp of their feet passed into the City and died\par
away. The onlookers stood silent for a while. Dust hung in the air, for the\par
wind had died and the evening was heavy. Already the closing hour was drawing\par
nigh, and the red sun had gone behind Mindolluin. Shadow came down on the\par
City.\par
Pippin looked up, and it seemed to him that the sky had grown ashen-grey,\par
as if a vast dust and smoke hung above them, and light came dully through it.\par
But in the West the dying sun had set all the fume on fire, and now Mindolluin\par
stood black against a burning smoulder flecked with embers. 'So ends a fair\par
day in wrath!' he said forgetful of the lad at his side.\par
'So it will, if I have not returned before the sundown-bells,' said\par
Bergil. 'Come! There goes the trumpet for the closing of the Gate.'\par
Hand in hand they went back into the City, the last to pass the Gate\par
before it was shut; and as they reached the Lampwrights' Street all the bells\par
in the towers tolled solemnly. Lights sprang in many windows, and from the\par
houses and wards of the men at arms along the walls there came the sound of\par
song.\par
'Farewell for this time,' said Bergil. 'Take my greetings to my :father,\par
and thank him for the company that he sent. Come again soon, I beg. Almost I\par
wish now that there was no war, for we might have had some merry times. We\par
might have journeyed to Lossarnach, to my grandsire's house; it is good to be\par
there in Spring, the woods and fields are full of flowers. But maybe we will\par
go thither together yet. They will never overcome our Lord, and my father is\par
very valiant. Farewell and return!'\par
They parted and Pippin hurried back towards the citadel. It seemed a long\par
way, and he grew hot and very hungry; and night closed down swift and dark.\par
Not a star pricked the sky. He was late for the daymeal in the mess, and\par
Beregond greeted him gladly, and sat him at his side to hear news of his son.\par
After the meal Pippin stayed a while, and then took his leave, for a strange\par
gloom was on him, and now he desired very much to see Gandalf again.\par
'Can you find your way?' said Beregond at the door of the small hall, on\par
the north side of the citadel, where they had sat. 'It is a black night, and\par
all the blacker since orders came that lights are to be dimmed within the\par
City, and none are to shine out from the walls. And I can give you news of\par
another order: you will be summoned to the Lord Denethor early tomorrow. I\par
fear you will not be for the Third Company. Still we may hope to meet again.\par
Farewell and sleep in peace!'\par
The lodging was dark, save for a little lantern set on the table. Gandalf\par
was not there. Gloom settled still more heavily on Pippin. He climbed on the\par
bench and tried to peer out of a window, but it was like looking into a pool\par
of ink. He got down and closed the shutter and went to bed. For a while he lay\par
and listened for sounds of Gandalf's return, and then he fell into an uneasy\par
sleep.\par
In the night he was wakened by a light, and he saw that Gandalf had come\par
and was pacing to and fro in the room beyond the curtain of the alcove. There\par
were candles on the table and rolls of parchment. He heard the wizard sigh,\par
and mutter: 'When will Faramir return?'\par
'Hullo!' said Pippin, poking his head round the curtain. 'I thought you\par
had forgotten all about me. I am glad to see you back. It has been a long\par
day.'\par
'But the night will be too short,' said Gandalf. 'I have come back here,\par
for I must have a little peace, alone. You should sleep, in a bed while you\par
still may. At the sunrise I shall take you to the Lord Denethor again. No,\par
when the summons comes, not at sunrise. The Darkness has begun. There will be\par
no dawn.'\par
_Chapter 2_\par
The Passing of the Grey Company\par
Gandalf was gone, and the thudding hoofs of Shadowfax were lost in the\par
night, when Merry came back to Aragorn. He had only a light bundle, for he had\par
lost his pack at Parth Galen, and all he had was a few useful things he had\par
picked up among the wreckage of Isengard. Hasufel was already saddled. Legolas\par
and Gimli with their horse stood close by.\par
'So four of the Company still remain,' said Aragorn. 'We will ride on\par
together. But we shall not go alone, as I thought. The king is now determined\par
to set out at once. Since the coming of the winged shadow, he desires to\par
return to the hills under cover of night.'\par
'And then whither?' said Legolas.\par
'I cannot say yet,' Aragorn answered. 'As for the king, he will go to the\par
muster that he commanded at Edoras, four nights from now. And there, I think,\par
he will hear tidings of war, and the Riders of Rohan will go down to Minas\par
Tirith. But for myself, and any that will go with me . . .'\par
'I for one!' cried Legolas. 'And Gimli with him!' said the Dwarf.\par
'Well, for myself,' said Aragorn, 'it is dark before me. I must go down\par
also to Minas Tirith, but I do not yet see the road. An hour long prepared\par
approaches.'\par
'Don't leave me behind!' said Merry. 'I have not been of much use yet;\par
but I don't want to be laid aside, like baggage to be called for when all is\par
over. I don't think the Riders will want to be bothered with me now. Though,\par
of course, the king did say that I was to sit by him when he came to his house\par
and tell him all about the Shire.'\par
'Yes,' said Aragorn, 'and your road lies with him, I think, Merry. But do\par
not look for mirth at the ending. It will be long, I fear, ere Th\'e9oden sits at\par
ease again in Meduseld. Many hopes will wither in this bitter Spring.'\par
Soon all were ready to depart: twenty-four horses, with Gimli behind\par
Legolas, and Merry in front of Aragorn. Presently they were riding swiftly\par
through the night. They had not long passed the mounds at the Fords of Isen,\par
when a Rider galloped up from the rear of their line.\par
'My lord,' he said to the king, 'there are horsemen behind us. As we\par
crossed the fords I thought that I heard them. Now we are sure. They are\par
overtaking us, riding hard.'\par
Th\'e9oden at once called a halt. The Riders turned about and seized their\par
spears. Aragorn dismounted and set Merry on the ground, and drawing his sword\par
he stood by the king's stirrup. \'c9omer and his esquire rode back to the rear.\par
Merry felt more like unneeded baggage than ever, and he wondered, if there was\par
a fight, what he should do. Supposing the king's small escort was trapped and\par
overcome, but he escaped into the darkness \endash  alone in the wild fields of Rohan\par
with no idea of where he was in all the endless miles? 'No good!' he thought.\par
He drew his sword and tightened his belt.\par
The sinking moon was obscured by a great sailing cloud, but suddenly it\par
rode out clear again. Then they all heard the sound of hoofs, and at the same\par
moment they saw dark shapes coming swiftly on the path from the fords. The\par
moonlight glinted here and there on the points of spears. The number of the\par
pursuers could not be told, but they seemed no fewer than the king's escort,\par
at the least.\par
When they were some fifty paces off, \'c9omer cried in a loud voice: 'Halt!\par
Halt! Who rides in Rohan?'\par
The pursuers brought their steeds to a sudden stand. A silence followed:\par
and then in the moonlight, a horseman could be seen dismounting and walking\par
slowly forward. His hand showed white as he held it up, palm outward, in token\par
of peace; but the king's men gripped their weapons. At ten paces the man\par
stopped. He was tall, a dark standing shadow. Then his clear voice rang out.\par
'Rohan? Rohan did you say? That is a glad word. We seek that land in\par
haste from long afar.'\par
'You have found it,' said \'c9omer. 'When you crossed the fords yonder you\par
entered it. But it is the realm of Th\'e9oden the King. None ride here save by\par
his leave. Who are you? And what is your haste?'\par
'Halbarad D\'fanadan, Ranger of the North I am,' cried the man. 'We seek one\par
Aragorn son of Arathorn, and we heard that he was in Rohan.'\par
'And you have found him also!' cried Aragorn. Giving his reins to Merry,\par
he ran forward and embraced the newcomer. 'Halbarad!' he said. 'Of all joys\par
this is the least expected!'\par
Merry breathed a sigh of relief. He had thought that this was some last\par
trick of Saruman's, to waylay the king while he had only a few men about him;\par
but it seemed that there would be no need to die in Th\'e9oden's defence, not yet\par
at any rate. He sheathed his sword.\par
'All is well,' said Aragorn, turning back. 'Here are some of my own kin\par
from the far land where I dwelt. But why they come, and how many they be,\par
Halbarad shall tell us.'\par
'I have thirty with me,' said Halbarad. 'That is all of our kindred that\par
could be gathered in haste; but the brethren Elladan and Elrohir have ridden\par
with us, desiring to go to the war. We rode as swiftly as we might when your\par
summons came.'\par
'But I did not summon you,' said Aragorn, 'save only in wish. My thoughts\par
have often turned to you, and seldom more than tonight; yet I have sent no\par
word. But come! All such matters must wait. You find us riding in haste and\par
danger. Ride with us now, if the king will give his leave.'\par
Th\'e9oden was indeed glad of the news. 'It is well!' he said. 'If these\par
kinsmen be in any way like to yourself, my lord Aragorn, thirty such knights\par
will be a strength that cannot be counted by heads.'\par
Then the Riders set out again, and Aragorn for a while rode with the\par
D\'fanedain; and when they had spoken of tidings in the North and in the South,\par
Elrohir said to him:\par
'I bring word to you from my father: _The days are short. If thou art in\par
haste, remember the Paths of the Dead_.'\par
'Always my days have seemed to me too short to achieve my desire,'\par
answered Aragorn. 'But great indeed will be my haste ere I take that road.'\par
'That will soon be seen,' said Elrohir. 'But let us speak no more of\par
these things upon the open road!'\par
And Aragorn said to Halbarad: 'What is that that you bear, kinsman?' For\par
he saw that instead of a spear he bore a tall staff, as it were a standard,\par
but it was close-furled in a black cloth bound about with many thongs.\par
'It is a gift that I bring you from the Lady of Rivendell,' answered\par
Halbarad. 'She wrought it in secret, and long was the making. But she also\par
sends word to you: _The days now are short. Either our hope cometh, or all\par
hopes end. Therefore I send thee what I have made for thee. Fare well,\par
Elfstone!_'\par
And Aragorn said: 'Now I know what you bear. Bear it still for me a\par
while!' And he turned and looked away to the North under the great stars, and\par
then he fell silent and spoke no more while the night's journey lasted.\par
The night was old and the East grey when they rode up at last from\par
Deeping-coomb and came back to the Hornburg. There they were to lie and rest\par
for a brief while and take counsel.\par
Merry slept until he was roused by Legolas and Gimli. 'The Sun is high,'\par
said Legolas. 'All others are up and doing. Come, Master Sluggard, and look at\par
this place while you may!'\par
'There was a battle here three nights ago,' said Gimli, 'and here Legolas\par
and I played a game that I won only by a single orc. Come and see how it was!\par
And there are caves, Merry, caves of wonder! Shall we visit them, Legolas, do\par
you think?'\par
'Nay! There is no time,' said the Elf. 'Do not spoil the wonder with\par
haste! I have given you my word to return hither with you, if a day of peace\par
and freedom comes again. But it is now near to noon, and at that hour we eat,\par
and then set out again, I hear.'\par
Merry got up and yawned. His few hours' sleep had not been nearly enough;\par
he was tired and rather dismal. He missed Pippin, and felt that he was only a\par
burden, while everybody was making plans for speed in a business that he did\par
not fully understand. 'Where is Aragorn?' he asked.\par
'In a high chamber of the Burg,' said Legolas. 'He has neither rested nor\par
slept, I think. He went thither some hours ago, saying that he must take\par
thought, and only his kinsman, Halbarad, went with him; but some dark doubt or\par
care sits on him.'\par
'They are a strange company, these newcomers,' said Gimli. 'Stout men and\par
lordly they are, and the Riders of Rohan look almost as boys beside them; for\par
they are grim men of face, worn like weathered rocks for the most part, even\par
as Aragorn himself; and they are silent.'\par
'But even as Aragorn they are courteous, if they break their silence.'\par
said Legolas. 'And have you marked the brethren Elladan and Elrohir? Less\par
sombre is their gear than the others', and they are fair and gallant as Elvenlords;\par
and that is not to be wondered at in the sons of Elrond of Rivendell.'\par
'Why have they come? Have you heard?' asked Merry. He had now dressed,\par
and he flung his grey cloak about his shoulders; and the three passed out\par
together towards the ruined gate of the Burg.\par
'They answered a summons, as you heard,' said Gimli. 'Word came to\par
Rivendell, they say: _Aragorn has need of his kindred. Let the D\'fanedain ride\par
to him in Rohan!_ But whence this message came they are now in doubt. Gandalf\par
sent it, I would guess.'\par
'Nay, Galadriel,' said Legolas. 'Did she not speak through Gandalf of the\par
ride of the Grey Company from the North?'\par
'Yes, you have it,' said Gimli. 'The Lady of the Wood! She read many\par
hearts and desires. Now why did not we wish for some of our own kinsfolk,\par
Legolas?'\par
Legolas stood before the gate and turned his bright eyes away north and\par
east, and his fair face was troubled. 'I do not think that any would come,' he\par
answered. 'They have no need to ride to war; war already marches on their own\par
lands.'\par
For a while the three companions walked together, speaking of this and\par
that turn of the battle, and they went down from the broken gate, and passed\par
the mounds of the fallen on the greensward beside the road, until they stood\par
on Helm's Dike and looked into the Coomb. The Death Down already stood there,\par
black and tall and stony, and the great trampling and scoring of the grass by\par
the Huorns could be plainly seen. The Dunlendings and many men of the garrison\par
of the Burg were at work on the Dike or in the fields and about the battered\par
walls behind; yet all seemed strangely quiet: a weary valley resting after a\par
great storm. Soon they turned back and went to the midday meal in the hall of\par
the Burg.\par
The king was already there, and as soon as they entered he called for\par
Merry and had a seat set for him at his side. 'It is not as I would have it,'\par
said Th\'e9oden; 'for this is little like my fair house in Edoras. And your\par
friend is gone, who should also be here. But it may be long ere we sit, you\par
and I, at the high table in Meduseld; there will be no time for feasting when\par
I return thither. But come now! Eat and drink, and let us speak together while\par
we may. And then you shall ride with me.'\par
'May I?' said Merry, surprised and delighted. 'That would be splendid!'\par
He had never felt more grateful for any kindness in words. 'I am afraid I am\par
only in everybody's way,' he stammered; 'but I should like to do anything I\par
could, you know.'\par
'I doubt it not,' said the king. 'I have had a good hill-pony made ready\par
for you. He will bear you as swift as any horse by the roads that we shall\par
take. For I will ride from the Burg by mountain paths, not by the plain, and\par
so come to Edoras by way of Dunharrow where the Lady \'c9owyn awaits me. You\par
shall be my esquire, if you will. Is there gear of war in this place, \'c9omer,\par
that my sword-thain could use?'\par
'There are no great weapon-hoards here, lord.' answered \'c9omer. 'Maybe a\par
light helm might be found to fit him; but we have no mail or sword for one of\par
his stature.'\par
'I have a sword,' said Merry, climbing from his seat, and drawing from\par
its black sheath his small bright blade. Filled suddenly with love for this\par
old man, he knelt on one knee, and took his hand and kissed it. 'May I lay the\par
sword of Meriadoc of the Shire on your lap Th\'e9oden King?' he cried. 'Receive\par
my service, if you will!'\par
'Gladly will I take it,' said the king; and laying his long old hands\par
upon the brown hair of the hobbit; he blessed him. 'Rise now, Meriadoc,\par
esquire of Rohan of the household of Meduseld!' he said. 'Take your sword and\par
bear it unto good fortune!'\par
'As a father you shall be to me,' said Merry.\par
'For a little while,' said Th\'e9oden.\par
They talked then together as they ate, until presently \'c9omer spoke. 'It\par
is near the hour that we set for our going, lord,' he said. 'Shall I bid men\par
sound the horns? But where is Aragorn? His place is empty and he has not\par
eaten.'\par
'We will make ready to ride,' said Th\'e9oden; 'but let word be sent to the\par
Lord Aragorn that the hour is nigh.'\par
The king with his guard and Merry at his side passed down from the gate\par
of the Burg to where the Riders were assembling on the green. Many were\par
already mounted. It would be a great company; for the king was leaving only a\par
small garrison in the Burg, and all who could be spared were riding to the\par
weapontake at Edoras. A thousand spears had indeed already ridden away at\par
night; but still there would be some five hundred more to go with the king,\par
for the most part men from the fields and dales of Westfold.\par
A little apart the Rangers sat, silent, in an ordered company, armed with\par
spear and bow and sword. They were clad in cloaks of dark grey, and their\par
hoods were cast now over helm and head. Their horses were strong and of proud\par
bearing, but rough-haired; and one stood there without a rider, Aragorn's own\par
horse that they had brought from the North; Roheryn was his name. There was no\par
gleam of stone or gold, nor any fair thing in all their gear and harness: nor\par
did their riders bear any badge or token, save only that each cloak was pinned\par
upon the left shoulder by a brooch of silver shaped like a rayed star.\par
The king mounted his horse, Snowmane, and Merry sat beside him on his\par
pony: Stybba was his name. Presently \'c9omer came out from the gate, and with\par
him was Aragorn, and Halbarad bearing the great staff close-furled in black,\par
and two tall men, neither young nor old So much alike were they, the sons of\par
Elrond, that few could tell them apart: dark-haired, grey-eyed, and their\par
faces elven-fair, clad alike in bright mail beneath cloaks of silver-grey.\par
Behind them walked Legolas and Gimli. But Merry had eyes only for Aragorn, so\par
startling was the change that he saw in him, as if in one night many years had\par
fallen on his head. Grim was his face, grey-hued and weary.\par
'I am troubled in mind, lord,' he said, standing by the king's horse. 'I\par
have heard strange words, and I see new perils far off. I have laboured long\par
in thought, and now I fear that I must change my purpose. Tell me, Th\'e9oden,\par
you ride now to Dunharrow, how long will it be ere you come there?'\par
'It is now a full hour past noon,' said \'c9omer. 'Before the night of the\par
third day from now we should come to the Hold. The Moon will then be one night\par
past his full, and the muster that the king commanded will be held the day\par
after. More speed we cannot make, if the strength of Rohan is to be gathered.'\par
Aragorn was silent for a moment. 'Three days,' he murmured, 'and the\par
muster of Rohan will only be begun. But I see that it cannot now be\par
hastened.' He looked up, and it seemed that he had made some decision; his\par
face was less troubled. Then, by our leave, lord, I must take new counsel for\par
myself and my kindred. We must ride our own road, and no longer in secret. For\par
me the time of stealth has passed. I will ride east by the swiftest way, and I\par
will take the Paths of the Dead.'\par
'The Paths of the Dead!' said Th\'e9oden, and trembled. 'Why do you speak of\par
them?' \'c9omer turned and gazed at Aragorn, and it seemed to Merry that the\par
faces of the Riders that sat within hearing turned pale at the words. 'If\par
there be in truth such paths,' said Th\'e9oden, 'their gate is in Dunharrow; but\par
no living man may pass it.'\par
'Alas! Aragorn my friend!' said \'c9omer. 'I had hoped that we should ride\par
to war together; but if you seek the Paths of the Dead, then our parting is\par
come, and it is little likely that we shall ever meet again under the Sun.'\par
'That road I will take, nonetheless,' said Aragorn. 'But I say to you,\par
\'c9omer, that in battle we may yet meet again, though all the hosts of Mordor\par
should stand between.'\par
'You will do as you will, my lord Aragorn,' said Th\'e9oden. 'It is your\par
doom, maybe, to tread strange paths that others dare not. This parting grieves\par
me, and my strength is lessened by it; but now I must take the mountain-roads\par
and delay no longer. Farewell!'\par
'Farewell, lord!' said Aragorn. 'Ride unto great renown! Farewell, Merry!\par
I leave you in good hands, better than we hoped when we hunted the orcs to\par
Fangorn. Legolas and Gimli will still hunt with me, I hope; but we shall not\par
forget you.'\par
'Good-bye!' said Merry. He could find no more to say. He felt very small,\par
and he was puzzled and depressed by all these gloomy words. More than ever he\par
missed the unquenchable cheerfulness of Pippin. The Riders were ready, and\par
their horses were fidgeting; he wished they would start arid get it over.\par
Now Th\'e9oden spoke to \'c9omer, and he lifted up his hand and cried aloud,\par
and with that word the Riders set forth. They rode over the Dike and down the\par
Coomb, and then, turning swiftly eastwards, they took a path that skirted the\par
foothills for a mile or so, until bending south it passed back among the hills\par
and disappeared from view. Aragorn rode to the Dike and watched till the\par
king's men were far down the Coomb. Then he turned to Halbarad.\par
'There go three that I love, and the smallest not the least,' he said.\par
'He knows not to what end he rides; yet if he knew, he still would go on.'\par
'A little people, but of great worth are the Shire-folk,' said Halbarad.\par
'Little do they know of our long labour for the safekeeping of their borders,\par
and yet I grudge it not.'\par
'And now our fates are woven together,' said Aragorn. 'And yet, alas!\par
here we must part. Well, I must eat a little, and then we also must hasten\par
away. Come, Legolas and Gimli! I must speak with you as I eat.'\par
Together they went back into the Burg; yet for some time Aragorn sat\par
silent at the table in the hall, and the others waited for him to speak.\par
'Come!' said Legolas at last. 'Speak and be comforted, and shake off the\par
shadow! What has happened since we came back to this grim place in the grey\par
morning?'\par
'A struggle somewhat grimmer for my part than the battle of the\par
Hornburg,' answered Aragorn. 'I have looked in the Stone of Orthanc, my\par
friends.'\par
'You have looked in that accursed stone of wizardry!' exclaimed Gimli\par
with fear and astonishment in his face. 'Did you say aught to \endash  him? Even\par
Gandalf feared that encounter.'\par
'You forget to whom you speak,' said Aragorn sternly, and his eyes\par
glinted. 'Did I not openly proclaim my title before the doors of Edoras? What\par
do you fear that I should say to him? Nay, Gimli,' he said in a softer voice,\par
and the grimness left his face, and he looked like one who has laboured in\par
sleepless pain for many nights. 'Nay, my friends, I and the lawful master of\par
the Stone, and I had both the right and the strength to use it, or so I\par
judged. The right cannot be doubted. The strength was enough \endash  barely.'\par
He drew a deep breath. 'It was a bitter struggle, and the weariness is\par
slow to pass. I spoke no word to him, and in the end I wrenched the Stone to\par
my own will. That alone he will find hard to endure. And he beheld me. Yes,\par
Master Gimli, he saw me, but in other guise than you see me here. If that will\par
aid him, then I have done ill. But I do not think so. To know that I lived and\par
walked the earth was a blow to his heart, I deem; for he knew it not till now.\par
The eyes in Orthanc did not see through the armour of Th\'e9oden; but Sauron has\par
not forgotten Isildur and the sword of Elendil. Now in the very hour of his\par
great designs the heir of Isildur and the Sword are revealed; for I showed the\par
blade re-forged to him. He is not so mighty yet that he is above fear; nay,\par
doubt ever gnaws him.'\par
'But he wields great dominion, nonetheless,' said Gimli; 'and now he will\par
strike more swiftly.'\par
'The hasty stroke goes oft astray,' said Aragorn. 'We must press our\par
Enemy, and no longer wait upon him for the move. See my friends, when I had\par
mastered the Stone, I learned many things. A grave peril I saw coming\par
unlooked-for upon Gondor from the South that will draw off great strength from\par
the defence of Minas Tirith. If it is not countered swiftly, I deem that the\par
City will be lost ere ten days be gone.'\par
'Then lost it must be,' said Gimli. 'For what help is there to send\par
thither, and how could it come there in time?'\par
'I have no help to send, therefore I must go myself,' said Aragorn. 'But\par
there is only one way through the mountains that will bring me to the\par
coastlands before all is lost. That is the Paths of the Dead.'\par
'The Paths of the Dead!' said Gimli. 'It is a fell name; and little to\par
the liking to the Men of Rohan, as I saw. Can the living use such a road and\par
not perish? And even if you pass that way, what will so few avail to counter\par
the strokes of Mordor?'\par
'The living have never used that road since the coming of the Rohirrim,'\par
said Aragorn, 'for it is closed to them. But in this dark hour the heir of\par
Isildur may use it, if he dare. Listen! This is the word that the sons of\par
Elrond bring to me from their father in Rivendell, wisest in lore: _Bid\par
Aragorn remember the words of the seer, and the Paths of the Dead_.'\par
'And what may be the words of the seer?' said Legolas.\par
"Thus spoke Malbeth the Seer, in the days of Arvedui, last king at\par
Fornost,' said Aragorn:\par
Over the land there lies a long shadow,\par
westward reaching wings of darkness.\par
The Tower trembles; to the tombs of kings\par
doom approaches. The Dead awaken;\par
for the hour is come for the oathbreakers;\par
at the Stone of Erech they shall stand again\par
and hear there a horn in the hills ringing.\par
Whose shall the horn be? Who shall call them\par
from the prey twilight, the forgotten people?\par
The heir of him to whom the oath they swore.\par
From the North shall he come, need shall drive him:\par
he shall pass the Door to the Paths of the Dead.\par
'Dark ways doubtless, said Gimli, but no darker than these staves are to\par
me.'\par
'If you would understand them better, then I bid you come with me,' said\par
Aragorn; 'for that way I now shall take. But I do not go gladly; only need\par
drives me. Therefore, only of your free will would I have you come, for you\par
will find both toil and great fear, and maybe worse.'\par
'I will go with you even on the Paths of the Dead, and to whatever, end\par
they may lead,' said Gimli.\par
'I also will come,' said Legolas, 'for I do not fear the Dead.'\par
'I hope that the forgotten people will not have forgotten how to fight,'\par
said Gimli; 'for otherwise I see not why we should trouble them.'\par
'That we shall know if ever we come to Erech,' said Aragorn. 'But the\par
oath that they broke was to fight against Sauron, and they must fight\par
therefore, if they are to fulfil it. For at Erech there stands yet a black\par
stone that was brought, it was said, from N\'famenor by Isildur; and it was set\par
upon a hill, and upon it the King of the Mountains swore allegiance to him in\par
the beginning of the realm of Gondor. But when Sauron returned and grew in\par
might again, Isildur summoned the Men of the Mountains to fulfil their oath,\par
and they would not: for they had worshipped Sauron in the Dark Years.\par
'Then Isildur said to their king: "Thou shalt be the last king. And if\par
the West prove mightier than thy Black Master, this curse I lay upon thee and\par
thy folk: to rest never until your oath is fulfilled. For this war will last\par
through years uncounted, and you shall be summoned once again ere the end."\par
And they fled before the wrath of Isildur, and did not dare to go forth to war\par
on Sauron's part; and they hid themselves in secret places in the mountains\par
and had no dealings with other men, but slowly dwindled in the barren hills.\par
And the terror of the Sleepless Dead lies about the Hill of Erech and all\par
places where that people lingered. But that way I must go, since there are\par
none living to help me.'\par
He stood up. 'Come!' he cried, and drew his sword, and it flashed in the\par
twilit hall of the Burg. 'To the Stone of Erech! I seek the Paths of the Dead.\par
Come with me who will!'\par
Legolas and Gimli made no answer, but they rose and followed Aragorn from\par
the hall. On the green there waited, still and silent, the hooded Rangers.\par
Legolas and Gimli mounted. Aragorn sprang upon Roheryn. Then Halbarad lifted a\par
great horn, and the blast of it echoed in Helm's Deep; and with that they\par
leapt away, riding down the Coomb like thunder, while all the men that were\par
left on Dike or Burg stared in amaze.\par
And while Th\'e9oden went by slow paths in the hills, the Grey Company\par
passed swiftly over the plain, and on the next day in the afternoon they came\par
to Edoras; and there they halted only briefly, ere they passed up the valley,\par
and so came to Dunharrow as darkness fell.\par
The Lady \'c9owyn greeted them and was glad of their coming; for no mightier\par
men had she seen than the D\'fanedain and the fair sons of Elrond; but on Aragorn\par
most of all her eyes rested. And when they sat at supper with her, they talked\par
together, and she heard of all that had passed since Th\'e9oden rode away,\par
concerning which only hasty tidings had yet reached her; and when she heard of\par
the battle in Helm's Deep and the great slaughter of their foes, and of the\par
charge of Th\'e9oden and his knights, then her eyes shone.\par
But at last she said: 'Lords, you are weary and shall now go to your beds\par
with such ease as can be contrived in haste. But tomorrow fairer housing shall\par
be found for you.'\par
But Aragorn said: 'Nay, lady, be not troubled for us! If we may lie here\par
tonight and break our fast tomorrow, it will be enough. For I ride on an\par
errand most urgent, and with the first light of morning we must go.'\par
She smiled on him and said: 'Then it was kindly done, lord, to ride so\par
many miles out of your way to bring tidings to \'c9owyn, and to speak with her in\par
her exile.'\par
'Indeed no man would count such a journey wasted,' said Aragorn; 'and\par
yet, lady, I could not have come hither, if it were not that the road which I\par
must take leads me to Dunharrow.'\par
And she answered as one that likes not what is said: "Then, lord, you are\par
astray; for out of Harrowdale no road runs east or south; and you had best\par
return as you came.'\par
'Nay, lady,' said he, 'I am not astray; for I walked in this land ere you\par
were born to grace it. There is a road out of this valley, and that road I\par
shall take. Tomorrow I shall ride by the Paths of the Dead.'\par
Then she stared at him as one that is stricken, and her face blanched,\par
and for long she spoke no more, while all sat silent. 'But, Aragorn,' she said\par
at last, 'is it then your errand to seek death? For that is all that you will\par
find on that road. They do not suffer the living to pass.'\par
'They may suffer me to pass,' said Aragorn; 'but at the least I will\par
adventure it. No other road will serve.'\par
'But this is madness,' she said. 'For here are men of renown and prowess,\par
whom you should not take into the shadows, but should lead to war, where men\par
are needed. I beg you to remain and ride with my brother; for then all our\par
hearts will be gladdened, and our hope be the brighter.'\par
'It is not madness, lady,' he answered; 'for I go on a path appointed.\par
But those who follow me do so of their free will; and if they wish now to\par
remain and ride with the Rohirrim, they may do so. But I shall take the Paths\par
of the Dead, alone, if needs be.'\par
Then they said no more, and they ate in silence; but her eyes were ever\par
upon Aragorn, and the others saw that she was in great torment of mind. At\par
length they arose, and took their leave of the Lady, and thanked her for her\par
care, and went to their rest.\par
But as Aragorn came to the booth where he was to lodge with Legolas and\par
Gimli, and his companions had gone in. there came the Lady \'c9owyn after him and\par
called to him. He turned and saw her as a glimmer in the night, for she was\par
clad in white; but her eyes were on fire.\par
'Aragorn,' she said, 'why will you go on this deadly road?'\par
'Because I must,' he said. 'Only so can I see any hope of doing my part\par
in the war against Sauron. I do not choose paths of peril, \'c9owyn. Were I to go\par
where my heart dwells, far in the North I would now be wandering in the fair\par
valley of Rivendell.'\par
For a while she was silent, as if pondering what this might mean. Then\par
suddenly she laid her hand on his arm. 'You are a stern lord and resolute,'\par
she said; 'and thus do men win renown.' She paused. 'Lord.' she said, 'if you\par
must go, then let me ride in your following. For I am weary of skulking in the\par
hills, and wish to face peril and battle.'\par
'Your duty is with your people,' he answered.\par
'Too often have I heard of duty,' she cried. 'But am I not of the House\par
of Eorl, a shieldmaiden and not a dry-nurse? I have waited on faltering feet\par
long enough. Since they falter no longer, it seems, may I not now spend my\par
life as I will?'\par
'Few may do that with honour,' he answered. 'But as for you, lady: did\par
you not accept the charge to govern the people until their lord's return? If\par
you had not been chosen, then some marshal or captain would have been set in\par
the same place, and he could not ride away from his charge, were he weary of\par
it or no.'\par
'Shall I always be chosen?' she said bitterly. 'Shall I always be left\par
behind when the Riders depart, to mind the house while they win renown, and\par
find food and beds when they return?'\par
'A time may come soon,' said he, 'when none will return. Then there will\par
be need of valour without renown, for none shall remember the deeds that are\par
done in the last defence of your homes. Yet the deeds will not be less valiant\par
because they are unpraised.'\par
And she answered: 'All your words are but to say: you are a woman, and\par
your part is in the house. But when the men have died in battle and honour,\par
you have leave to be burned in the house, for the men will need it no more.\par
But I am of the House of Eorl and not a serving-woman. I can ride and wield\par
blade, and I do not fear either pain or death.'\par
'What do you fear, lady?' he asked.\par
'A cage,' she said. 'To stay behind bars, until use and old age accept\par
them, and all chance of doing great deeds is gone beyond recall or desire.'\par
'And yet you counselled me not to adventure on the road that I had\par
chosen, because it is perilous?'\par
'So may one counsel another,' she said. 'Yet I do not bid you flee from\par
peril, but to ride to battle where your sword may win renown and victory. I\par
would not see a thing that is high and excellent cast away needlessly.'\par
'Nor would I,' he said. 'Therefore I say to you, lady: Stay! For you have\par
no errand to the South.'\par
'Neither have those others who go with thee. They go only because they\par
would not be parted from thee \endash  because they love thee.' Then she turned and\par
vanished into the night.\par
When the light of day was come into the sky but the sun was not yet risen\par
above the high ridges in the East, Aragorn made ready to depart. His company\par
was all mounted, and he was about to leap into the saddle, when the Lady \'c9owyn\par
came to bid them farewell. She was clad as a Rider and girt with a sword. In\par
her hand she bore a cup, and she set it to her lips and drank a little,\par
wishing them good speed; and then she gave the cup to Aragorn, and he drank,\par
and he said: 'Farewell, Lady of Rohan! I drink to the fortunes of your House,\par
and of you, and of all your people. Say to your brother: beyond the shadows we\par
may meet again!'\par
Then it seemed to Gimli and Legolas who were nearby that she wept, and in\par
one so stern and proud that seemed the more grievous. But she said: 'Aragorn,\par
wilt thou go?'\par
'I will,' he said.\par
'Then wilt thou not let me ride with this company, as I have asked?'\par
'I will not, lady,' he said. 'For that I could not grant without leave of\par
the king and of your brother; and they will not return until tomorrow. But I\par
count now every hour, indeed every minute. Farewell!'\par
Then she fell on her knees, saying: 'I beg thee!'\par
'Nay, lady,' he said, and taking her by the hand he raised her. Then he\par
kissed her hand, and sprang into the saddle, and rode away, and did not look\par
back; and only those who knew him well and were near to him saw the pain that\par
he bore.\par
But \'c9owyn stood still as a figure carven in stone, her hands clenched at\par
her sides, and she watched them until they passed into the shadows under the\par
black Dwimorberg, the Haunted Mountain, in which was the Gate of the Dead.\par
When they were lost to view, she turned, stumbling as one that is blind, and\par
went back to her lodging. But none of her folk saw this parting, for they hid\par
themselves in fear and would not come forth until the day was up, and the\par
reckless strangers were gone.\par
And some said: 'They are Elvish wights. Let them go where they belong,\par
into the dark places, and never return. The times are evil enough.'\par
The light was still grey as they rode, for the sun had not yet climbed\par
over the black ridges of the Haunted Mountain before them. A dread fell on\par
them, even as they passed between the lines of ancient stones and so came to\par
the Dimholt. There under the gloom of black trees that not even Legolas could\par
long endure they found a hollow place opening at the mountain's root, and\par
right in their path stood a single mighty stone like a finger of doom.\par
'My blood runs chill,' said Gimli, but the others were silent, and his\par
voice fell dead on the dank fir-needles at his feet. The horses would not pass\par
the threatening stone, until the riders dismounted and led them about. And so\par
they came at last deep into the glen; and there stood a sheer wall of rock,\par
and in the wall the Dark Door gaped before them like the mouth of night. Signs\par
and figures were carved above its wide arch too dim to read, and fear flowed\par
from it like a grey vapour.\par
The company halted, and there was not a heart among them that did not\par
quail, unless it were the heart of Legolas of the Elves, for whom the ghosts\par
of Men have no terror.\par
'This is an evil door,' said Halbarad, 'and my death lies beyond it. I\par
will dare to pass it nonetheless; but no horse will enter.'\par
'But we must go in, and therefore the horses must go too,' said Aragorn.\par
'For if ever we come through this darkness, many leagues lie beyond, and every\par
hour that is lost there will bring the triumph of Sauron nearer. Follow me!'\par
Then Aragorn led the way, and such was the strength of his will in that\par
hour that all the D\'fanedain and their horses followed him. And indeed the love\par
that the horses of the Rangers bore for their riders was so great that they\par
were willing to face even the terror of the Door, if their masters' hearts\par
were steady as they walked beside them. But Arod, the horse of Rohan, refused\par
the way, and he stood sweating and trembling in a fear that was grievous to\par
see. Then Legolas laid his hands on his eyes and sang some words that went\par
soft in the gloom, until he suffered himself to be led, and Legolas passed in.\par
And there stood Gimli the Dwarf left all alone.\par
His knees shook, and he was wroth with himself. 'Here is a thing unheard\par
of!' he said. 'An Elf will go underground and a Dwarf dare not!' With that he\par
plunged in. But it seemed to him that he dragged his feet like lead over the\par
threshold; and at once a blindness came upon him, even upon Gimli Gl\'f3in's son\par
who had walked unafraid in many deep places of the world.\par
Aragorn had brought torches from Dunharrow, and now he went ahead bearing\par
one aloft; and Elladan with another went at the rear, and Gimli, stumbling\par
behind, strove to overtake him. He could see nothing but the dim flame of the\par
torches; but if the company halted, there seemed an endless whisper of voices\par
all about him, a murmur of words in no tongue that he had ever heard before.\par
Nothing assailed the company nor withstood their passage, and yet\par
