Dead call.'\par
'Maybe he was called,' said Th\'e9oden; 'and my heart tells me that I shall\par
not see him again. Yet he is a kingly man of high destiny. And take comfort in\par
this, daughter, since comfort you seem to need in your grief for this guest.\par
It is said that when the Eorlingas came out of the North and passed at length\par
up the Snowbourn, seeking strong places of refuge in time of need, Brego and\par
his son Baldor climbed the Stair of the Hold and so came before the Door. On\par
the threshold sat an old man, aged beyond guess of years; tall and kingly he\par
had been, but now he was withered as an old stone. Indeed for stone they took\par
him, for he moved not, and he said no word, until they sought to pass him by\par
and enter. And then a voice came out of him, as it were out of the ground, and\par
to their amaze it spoke in the western tongue: _The way is shut_.\par
'Then they halted and looked at him and saw that he lived still; but he\par
did not look at them. _The way is shut_, his voice said again _It was made by\par
those who are Dead, and the Dead keep it, until the time comes. The way is\par
shut._\par
'_And when will that time be?_said Baldor. But no answer did he ever get.\par
For the old man died in that hour and fell upon his face; and no other tidings\par
of the ancient dwellers in the mountains have our folk ever learned. Yet maybe\par
at last the time foretold has come, and Aragorn may pass.'\par
'But how shall a man discover whether that time be come or no, save by\par
daring the Door?' said \'c9omer. 'And that way I would not go though all the\par
hosts of Mordor stood before me, and I were alone and had no other refuge.\par
Alas that a fey mood should fall on a man so greathearted in this hour of\par
need! Are there not evil things enough abroad without seeking them under the\par
earth? War is at hand.'\par
He paused, for at that moment there was a noise outside, a man's voice\par
crying the name of Th\'e9oden, and the challenge of the guard.\par
Presently the captain of the Guard thrust aside the curtain. 'A man is\par
here, lord,' he said, 'an errand-rider of Gondor. He wishes to come before you\par
at once.'\par
'Let him come!' said Th\'e9oden.\par
A tall man entered, and Merry choked back a cry; for a moment it seemed\par
to him that Boromir was alive again and had returned. Then he saw that it was\par
not so; the man was a stranger, though as like to Boromir as if he were one of\par
his kin, tall and grey-eyed and proud. He was clad as a rider with a cloak of\par
dark green over a coat of fine mail; on the front of his helm was wrought a\par
small silver star. In his hand he bore a single arrow, black-feathered and\par
barbed with steel, but the point was painted red.\par
He sank on one knee and presented the arrow to Th\'e9oden. 'Hail Lord of the\par
Rohirrim, friend of Gondor!' he said. 'Hirgon I am, errand-rider of Denethor,\par
who bring you this token of war. Gondor is in great need. Often the Rohirrim\par
have aided us, but now the Lord Denethor asks for all your strength and all\par
your speed; lest Gondor fall at last.'\par
'The Red Arrow!' said Th\'e9oden, holding it, as one who receives a summons\par
long expected and yet dreadful when it comes. His hand trembled. 'The Red\par
Arrow has not been seen in the Mark in all my years! Has it indeed come to\par
that? And what does the Lord Denethor reckon that all my strength and all my\par
speed may be?'\par
'That is best known to yourself, lord,' said Hirgon. 'But ere long it may\par
well come to pass that Minas Tirith is surrounded, and unless you have the\par
strength to break a siege of many powers, the Lord Denethor bids me say that\par
he judges that the strong arms of the Rohirrim would be better within his\par
walls than without.'\par
'But he knows that we are a people who fight rather upon horseback and in\par
the open, and that we are also a scattered people and time is needed for the\par
gathering of our Riders. Is it not true, Hirgon, that the Lord of Minas Tirith\par
knows more than he sets in his message? For we are already at war, as you may\par
have seen, and you do not find us all unprepared. Gandalf the Grey has been\par
among us, and even now we are mustering for battle in the East.'\par
'What the Lord Denethor may know or guess of all these things I cannot\par
say,' answered Hirgon. 'But indeed our case is desperate. My lord does not\par
issue any command to you, he begs you only to remember old friendship and\par
oaths long spoken, and for your own good to do all that you may. It is\par
reported to us that many kings have ridden in from the East to the service of\par
Mordor. From the North to the field of Dagorlad there is skirmish and rumour\par
of war. In the South the Haradrim are moving, and fear has fallen on all our\par
coastlands, so that little help will come to us thence. Make haste! For it is\par
before the walls of Minas Tirith that the doom of our time will be decided,\par
and if the tide be not stemmed there, then it will flow over all the fair\par
fields of Rohan, and even in this Hold among the hills there shall be no\par
refuge.'\par
'Dark tidings,' said Th\'e9oden, 'yet not all unguessed. But say to Denethor\par
that even if Rohan itself felt no peril, still we would come to his aid. But\par
we have suffered much loss in our battles with Saruman the traitor, and we\par
must still think of our frontier to the north and east, as his own tidings\par
make clear. So great a power as the Dark Lord seems now to wield might well\par
contain us in battle before the City and yet strike with great force across\par
the River away beyond the Gate of Kings.\par
'But we will speak no longer counsels of prudence. We will come. The\par
weapontake was set for the morrow. When all is ordered we will set out. Ten\par
thousand spears I might have sent riding over the plain to the dismay of your\par
foes. It will be less now, I fear; for I will not leave my strongholds all\par
unguarded. Yet six thousands at the least shall ride behind me. For say to\par
Denethor that in this hour the King of the Mark himself will come down to the\par
land of Gondor, though maybe he will not ride back. But it is a long road, and\par
man and beast must reach the end with strength to fight. A week it may be from\par
tomorrow's morn ere you hear the cry of the Sons of Eorl coming from the\par
North.\par
'A week!' said Hirgon. 'If it must be so, it must. But you are like to\par
find only ruined walls in seven days from now, unless other help unlooked-for\par
comes. Still, you may at the least disturb the Orcs and Swarthy Men from their\par
feasting in the White Tower.'\par
'At the least we will do that,' said Th\'e9oden. 'But I myself am new-come\par
from battle and long journey, and I will now go to rest. Tarry here this\par
night. Then you shall look on the muster of Rohan and ride away the gladder\par
for the sight, and the swifter for the rest. In the morning counsels are best,\par
and night changes many thoughts.\par
With that the king stood up, and they all rose. 'Go now each to your\par
rest.' he said, 'and sleep well. And you, Master Meriadoc, I need no more\par
tonight. But be ready to my call as soon as the Sun is risen.'\par
'I will be ready,' said Merry, 'even if you bid me ride with you on the\par
Paths of the Dead.'\par
'Speak not words of omen!' said the king. 'For there may be more roads\par
than one that could bear that name. But I did not say that I would bid you\par
ride with me on any road. Good night!'\par
'I won't be left behind, to be called for on return!' said Merry. 'I\par
won't be left, I won't.' And repeating this over and over again to himself he\par
fell asleep at last in his tent.\par
He was wakened by a man shaking him. 'Wake up, wake up. Master\par
Holbytla!' he cried; and at length Merry came out of deep dreams and sat up\par
with a start. It still seemed very dark, he thought.\par
'What is the matter?' he asked.\par
'The king calls for you.'\par
'But the Sun has not risen, yet,' said Merry.\par
'No, and will not rise today, Master Holbytla. Nor ever again, one would\par
think under this cloud. But time does not stand still, though the Sun be lost.\par
Make haste!'\par
Flinging on some clothes, Merry looked outside. The world was darkling.\par
The very air seemed brown, and all things about were black and grey and\par
shadowless; there was a great stillness. No shape of cloud could be seen,\par
unless it were far away westward, where the furthest groping fingers of the\par
great gloom still crawled onwards and a little light leaked through them.\par
Overhead there hung a heavy roof, sombre and featureless, and light seemed\par
rather to be failing than growing.\par
Merry saw many folk standing, looking up and muttering: all their faces\par
were grey and sad, and some were afraid. With a sinking heart he made his way\par
to the king. Hirgon the rider of Gondor was there before him, and beside him\par
stood now another man, like him and dressed alike, but shorter and broader. As\par
Merry entered he was speaking to the king.\par
'It comes from Mordor, lord,' he said. 'It began last night at sunset.\par
From the hills in the Eastfold of your realm I saw it rise and creep across\par
the sky, and all night as I rode it came behind eating up the stars. Now the\par
great cloud hangs over all the land between here and the Mountains of Shadow;\par
and it is deepening. War has already begun.'\par
For a while the king sat silent. At last he spoke. 'So we come to it in\par
the end,' he said: 'the great battle of our time, in which many things shall\par
pass away. But at least there is no longer need for hiding. We will ride the\par
straight way and the open road and with all our speed. The muster shall begin\par
at once, and wait for none that tarry. Have you good store in Minas Tirith?\par
For if we must ride now in all haste, then we must ride light, with but meal\par
and water enough to last us into battle.'\par
'We have very great store long prepared,' answered Hirgon. Ride now as\par
light and as swift as you may!'\par
'Then call the heralds, \'c9omer,' said Th\'e9oden. 'Let the Riders be\par
marshalled!'\par
\'c9omer went out, and presently the trumpets rang in the Hold and were\par
answered by many others from below; but their voices no longer sounded clear\par
and brave as they had seemed to Merry the night before. Dull they seemed and\par
harsh in the heavy air, braying ominously.\par
The king turned to Merry. 'I am going to war, Master Meriadoc,' he said.\par
'In a little while I shall take the road. I release you from my service, but\par
not from my friendship. You shall abide here, and if you will, you shall serve\par
the Lady \'c9owyn, who will govern the folk in my stead.'\par
'But, but, lord,' Merry stammered, 'I offered you my sword. I do not want\par
to be parted from you like this, Th\'e9oden King. And as all my friends have gone\par
to the battle' I should be ashamed to stay behind.'\par
'But we ride on horses tall and swift,' said Th\'e9oden; 'and great though\par
your heart be, you cannot ride on such beasts.'\par
'Then tie me on to the back of one, or let me hang on a stirrup, or\par
something,' said Merry. 'It is a long way to run; but run I shall, if I cannot\par
ride, even if I wear my feet off and arrive weeks too late.'\par
Th\'e9oden smiled. 'Rather than that I would bear you with me on Snowmane,'\par
he said. 'But at the least you shall ride with me to Edoras and look on\par
Meduseld; for that way I shall go. So far Stybba can bear you: the great race\par
will not begin till we reach the plains.'\par
Then \'c9owyn rose up. 'Come now, Meriadoc!' she said. 'I will show you the\par
gear that I have prepared fur you.' They went out together. 'This request only\par
did Aragorn make to me,' said \'c9owyn, as they passed among the tents, 'that you\par
should be armed for battle. I have granted it, as I could. For my heart tells\par
me that you will need such gear ere the end.'\par
Now she led Merry to a booth among the lodges of the king's guard and\par
there an armourer brought out to her a small helm, and a round shield, and\par
other gear.\par
'No mail have we to fit you,' said \'c9owyn, 'nor any time for the forging\par
of such a hauberk; but here is also a stout jerkin of leather, a belt, and a\par
knife. A sword you have.'\par
Merry bowed, and the lady showed him the shield, which was like the\par
shield that had been given to Gimli, and it bore on it the device of the white\par
horse. 'Take all these things,' she said, 'and bear them to good fortune!\par
Farewell now, Master Meriadoc! Yet maybe we shall meet again, you and I.'\par
So it was that amid a gathering gloom the King of the Mark made ready to\par
lead all his Riders on the eastward road. Hearts were heavy and many quailed\par
in the shadow. But they were a stern people, loyal to their lord, and little\par
weeping or murmuring was heard, even in the camp in the Hold where the exiles\par
from Edoras were housed, women and children and old men. Doom hung over them,\par
but they faced it silently.\par
Two swift hours passed, and now the king sat upon his white horse,\par
glimmering in the half light. Proud and tall he seemed, though the hair that\par
flowed beneath his high helm was like snow; and many marvelled at him and took\par
heart to see him unbent and unafraid.\par
There on the wide flats beside the noisy river were marshalled in many\par
companies well nigh five and fifty hundreds of Riders fully armed, and many\par
hundreds of other men with spare horses lightly burdened. A single trumpet\par
sounded. The king raised his hand, and then silently the host of the Mark\par
began to move. Foremost went twelve of the king's household-men, Riders of\par
renown. Then the king followed with \'c9omer on his right. He had said farewell\par
to \'c9owyn above in the Hold, and the memory was grievous; but now he turned his\par
mind to the road that lay ahead. Behind him Merry rode on Stybba with the\par
errand riders of Gondor, and behind them again twelve more of the king's\par
household. They passed down the long ranks of waiting men with stern and\par
unmoved faces. But when they had come almost to the end of the line one looked\par
up glancing keenly at the hobbit. A young man, Merry thought as he returned\par
the glance, less in height and girth than most. He caught the glint of clear\par
grey eyes; and then he shivered, for it came suddenly to him that it was the\par
face of one without hope who goes in search of death.\par
On down the grey road they went beside the Snowbourn rushing on its\par
stones; through the hamlets of Underharrow and Upbourn, where many sad faces\par
of women looked out from dark doors; and so without horn or harp or music of\par
men's voices the great ride into the East began with which the songs of Rohan\par
were busy for many long lives of men thereafter.\par
From dark Dunharrow in the dim morning\par
with thane and captain rode Thengel's son:\par
to Edoras he came, the ancient halls\par
of the Mark-wardens mist-enshrouded;\par
golden timbers were in gloom mantled.\par
Farewell he bade to his free people,\par
hearth and high-seat, and the hallowed places,\par
where long he had feasted ere the light faded.\par
Forth rode the king, fear behind him,\par
fate before him. Fealty kept he;\par
oaths he had taken, all fulfilled them.\par
Forth rode Th\'e9oden. Five nights and days\par
east and onward rode the Eorlingas\par
through Folde and Fenmarch and the Firienwood,\par
six thousand spears to Sunlending,\par
Mundburg the mighty under Mindolluin,\par
Sea-kings' city in the South-kingdom\par
foe-beleaguered, fire-encircled.\par
Doom drove them on. Darkness took them,\par
Horse and horseman; hoofbeats afar\par
sank into silence: so the songs tell us.\par
It was indeed in deepening gloom that the king came to Edoras, although\par
it was then but noon by the hour. There he halted only a short while and\par
strengthened his host by some three score of Riders that came late to the\par
weapontake. Now having eaten he made ready to set out again, and he wished his\par
esquire a kindly farewell. But Merry begged for the last time not to be parted\par
from him.\par
'This is no journey for such steeds as Stybba, as I have told you ' said\par
Th\'e9oden. 'And in such a battle as we think to make on the fields of Gondor\par
what would you do, Master Meriadoc, sword-thain though you be, and greater of\par
heart than of stature?'\par
'As for that, who can tell?' answered Merry. 'But why, lord, did you\par
receive me as sword-thain, if not to stay by your side? And I would not have\par
it said of me in song only that I was always left behind!'\par
'I received you for your safe-keeping,' answered Th\'e9oden; 'and also to do\par
as I might bid. None of my Riders can bear you as burden. If the battle were\par
before my gates, maybe your deeds would be remembered by the minstrels; but it\par
is a hundred leagues and two to Mundburg where Denethor is lord. I will say no\par
more.'\par
Merry bowed and went away unhappily, and stared at the lines of horsemen.\par
Already the companies were preparing to start: men were tightening girths,\par
looking to saddles, caressing their horses; some gazed uneasily at the\par
lowering sky. Unnoticed a Rider came up and spoke softly in the hobbit's ear.\par
'_Where will wants not, a way opens_, so we say,' he whispered; 'and so I\par
have found myself.' Merry looked up and saw that it was the young Rider whom\par
he had noticed in the morning. 'You wish to go whither the Lord of the Mark\par
goes: I see it in your face.'\par
'I do,' said Merry.\par
'Then you shall go with me,' said the Rider. 'I will bear you before me,\par
under my cloak until we are far afield, and this darkness is yet darker. Such\par
good will should not be denied. Say no more to any man, but come!'\par
'Thank you indeed!' said Merry. 'Thank you, sir, though I do not know\par
your name.'\par
'Do you not?' said the Rider softly. 'Then call me Dernhelm.'\par
Thus it came to pass that when the king set out, before Dernhelm sat\par
Meriadoc the hobbit, and the great grey steed Windfola made little of the\par
burden; for Dernhelm was less in weight than many men, though lithe and wellknit\par
in frame.\par
On into the shadow they rode. In the willow-thickets where Snowbourn\par
flowed into Entwash, twelve leagues east of Edoras, they camped that night.\par
And then on again through the Folde; and through the Fenmarch, where to their\par
right great oakwoods climbed on the skirts of the hills under the shades of\par
dark Halifirien by the borders of Gondor; but away to their left the mists lay\par
on the marshes fed by the mouths of Entwash. And as they rode rumour came of\par
war in the North. Lone men, riding wild, brought word of foes assailing their\par
east-borders, of orc-hosts marching in the Wold of Rohan.\par
'Ride on! Ride on!' cried \'c9omer. 'Too late now to turn aside. The fens of\par
Entwash must guard our flank. Haste now we need. Ride on!'\par
And so King Th\'e9oden departed from his own realm, and mile by mile the\par
long road wound away, and the beacon hills marched past: Calenhad, Min-Rimmon,\par
Erelas, Nardol. But their fires were quenched. All the lands were grey and\par
still; and ever the shadow deepened before them, and hope waned in every\par
heart.\par
_Chapter 4_\par
The Siege of Gondor\par
Pippin was roused by Gandalf. Candles were lit in their chamber, for only\par
a dim twilight came through the windows; the air was heavy as with approaching\par
thunder.\par
'What is the time?' said Pippin yawning.\par
'Past the second hour,' said Gandalf. 'Time to get up and make yourself\par
presentable. You are summoned to the Lord of the City to learn your new\par
duties.'\par
'And will he provide breakfast?'\par
'No! I have provided it: all that you will get till noon. Food is now\par
doled out by order.'\par
Pippin looked ruefully at the small loaf and (he thought) very inadequate\par
pat of butter which was set out for him, beside a cup of thin milk. 'Why did\par
you bring me here?' he said.\par
'You know quite well,' said Gandalf. 'To keep you out of mischief; and if\par
you do not like being here, you can remember that you brought it on\par
yourself.' Pippin said no more.\par
Before long he was walking with Gandalf once more down the cold corridor\par
to the door of the Tower Hall. There Denethor sat in a grey gloom, like an old\par
patient spider, Pippin thought: he did not seem to have moved since the day\par
before. He beckoned Gandalf to a seat, but Pippin was left for a while\par
standing unheeded. Presently the old man turned to him:\par
'Well, Master Peregrin, I hope that you used yesterday to your profit,\par
and to your liking? Though I fear that the board is barer in this city than\par
you could wish.'\par
Pippin had an uncomfortable feeling that most of what he had said or done\par
was somehow known to the Lord of the City, and much was guessed of what he\par
thought as well. He did not answer.\par
'What would you do in my service?'\par
'I thought, sir, that you would tell me my duties.'\par
'I will, when I learn what you are fit for,' said Denethor. 'But that I\par
shall learn soonest, maybe, if I keep you beside me. The esquire of my chamber\par
has begged leave to go to the out-garrison, so you shall take his place for a\par
while. You shall wait on me, bear errands, and talk to me, if war and council\par
leave me any leisure. Can you sing?'\par
'Yes,' said Pippin. 'Well, yes, well enough for my own people. But we\par
have no songs fit for great halls and evil times, lord. We seldom sing of\par
anything more terrible than wind or rain. And most of my songs are about\par
things that make us laugh; or about food and drink, of course.'\par
'And why should such songs be unfit for my halls, or for such hours as\par
these? We who have lived long under the Shadow may surely listen to echoes\par
from a land untroubled by it? Then we may feel that our vigil was not\par
fruitless, though it may have been thankless.'\par
Pippin's heart sank. He did not relish the idea of singing any song of\par
the Shire to the Lord of Minas Tirith, certainly not the comic ones that he\par
knew best; they were too, well, rustic for such an occasion. He was however\par
spared the ordeal for the present. He was not commanded to sing. Denethor\par
turned to Gandalf, asking questions about the Rohirrim and their policies, and\par
the position of \'c9omer, the king's nephew. Pippin marvelled at the amount that\par
the Lord seemed to know about a people that lived far away, though it must, he\par
thought, be many years since Denethor himself had ridden abroad.\par
Presently Denethor waved to Pippin and dismissed him again for a while.\par
'Go to the armouries of the Citadel,' he said, 'and get you there the livery\par
and gear of the Tower. It will be ready. It was commanded yesterday. Return\par
when you are clad!'\par
It was as he said; and Pippin soon found himself arrayed in strange\par
garments, all of black and silver. He had a small hauberk, its rings forged of\par
steel, maybe, yet black as jet; and a high-crowned helm with small raven-wings\par
on either side, set with a silver star in the centre of the circlet. Above the\par
mail was a short surcoat of black, but broidered on the breast in silver with\par
the token of the Tree. His old clothes were folded and put away, but he was\par
permitted to keep the grey cloak of L\'f3rien, though not to wear it when on\par
duty. He looked now, had he known it, verily _Ernil i Pheriannath_, the Prince\par
of the Halflings, that folk had called him; but he felt uncomfortable. And the\par
gloom began to weigh on his spirits.\par
It was dark and dim all day. From the sunless dawn until evening the\par
heavy shadow had deepened, and all hearts in the City were oppressed. Far\par
above a great cloud streamed slowly westward from the Black Land, devouring\par
light, borne upon a wind of war; but below the air was still and breathless,\par
as if all the Vale of Anduin waited for the onset of a ruinous storm.\par
About the eleventh hour, released at last for a while from service.\par
Pippin came out and went in search of food and drink to cheer his heavy heart\par
and make his task of waiting more supportable. In the messes he met Beregond\par
again, who had just come from an errand over the Pelennor out to the Guardtowers\par
upon the Causeway. Together they strolled out to the walls; for Pippin\par
felt imprisoned indoors, and stifled even in the lofty citadel. Now they sat\par
side by side again in the embrasure looking eastward, where they had eaten and\par
talked the day before.\par
It was the sunset-hour, but the great pall had now stretched far into the\par
West, and only as it sank at last into the Sea did the Sun escape to send out\par
a brief farewell gleam before the night, even as Frodo saw it at the Crossroads\par
touching the head of the fallen king. But to the fields of the Pelennor,\par
under the shadow of Mindolluin, there came no gleam: they were brown and\par
drear.\par
Already it seemed years to Pippin since he had sat there before, in some\par
half-forgotten time when he had still been a hobbit, a light-hearted wanderer\par
touched little by the perils he had passed through. Now he was one small\par
soldier in a city preparing for a great assault, clad in the proud but sombre\par
manner of the Tower of Guard.\par
In some other time and place Pippin might have been pleased with his new\par
array, but he knew now that he was taking part in no play; he was in deadly\par
earnest the servant of a grim master in the greatest peril. The hauberk was\par
burdensome, and the helm weighed upon his head. His cloak he had cast aside\par
upon the seat. He turned his tired gaze away from the darkling fields below\par
and yawned, and then he sighed.\par
'You are weary of this day?' said Beregond.\par
'Yes,' said Pippin, 'very: tired out with idleness and waiting. I have\par
kicked my heels at the door of my master's chamber for many slow hours, while\par
he has debated with Gandalf and the Prince and other great persons. And I'm\par
not used, Master Beregond, to waiting hungry on others while they eat. It is a\par
sore trial for a hobbit, that. No doubt you will think I should feel the\par
honour more deeply. But what is the good of such honour? Indeed what is the\par
good even of food and drink under this creeping shadow? What does it mean? The\par
very air seems thick and brown! Do you often have such glooms when the wind is\par
in the East?'\par
'Nay,' said Beregond, 'this is no weather of the world. This is some\par
device of his malice; some broil of fume from the Mountain of Fire that he\par
sends to darken hearts and counsel. And so it doth indeed. I wish the Lord\par
Faramir would return. He would not be dismayed. But now, who knows if he will\par
ever come back across the River out of the Darkness?'\par
'Yes,' said Pippin, 'Gandalf, too, is anxious. He was disappointed. I\par
think, not to find Faramir here. And where has he got to himself? He left the\par
Lord's council before the noon-meal, and in no good mood either, I thought.\par
Perhaps he has some foreboding of bad news.'\par
Suddenly as they talked they were stricken dumb, frozen as it were to\par
listening stones. Pippin cowered down with his hands pressed to his ears; but\par
Beregond, who had been looking out from the battlement as he spoke of Faramir,\par
remained there, stiffened, staring out with starting eyes. Pippin knew the\par
shuddering cry that he had heard: it was the same that he had heard long ago\par
in the Marish of the Shire, but now it was grown in power and hatred, piercing\par
the heart with a poisonous despair.\par
At last Beregond spoke with an effort. 'They have come!' he said. 'Take\par
courage and look! There are fell things below.'\par
Reluctantly Pippin climbed on to the seat and looked out over the wall.\par
The Pelennor lay dim beneath him, fading away to the scarce guessed line of\par
the Great River. But now wheeling swiftly across it, like shadows of untimely\par
night, he saw in the middle airs below him five birdlike forms, horrible as\par
carrion-fowl yet greater than eagles, cruel as death. Now they swooped near,\par
venturing almost within bowshot of the walls, now they circled away.\par
'Black Riders!' muttered Pippin. 'Black Riders of the air! But see,\par
Beregond!' he cried. 'They are looking for something, surely? See how they\par
wheel and swoop, always down to that point over there! And can you see\par
something moving on the ground? Dark little things. Yes, men on horses: four\par
or five. Ah! I cannot stand it! Gandalf! Gandalf save us!'\par
Another long screech rose and fell, and he threw himself back again from\par
the wall, panting like a hunted animal. Faint and seemingly remote through\par
that shuddering cry he heard winding up from below the sound of a trumpet\par
ending on a long high note.\par
'Faramir! The Lord Faramir! It is his call!' cried Beregond. 'Brave\par
heart! But how can he win to the Gate, if these foul hell-hawks have other\par
weapons than fear? But look! They hold on. They will make the Gate. No! the\par
horses are running mad. Look! the men are thrown; they are running on foot.\par
No, one is still up, but he rides back to the others. That will be the\par
Captain: he can master both beasts and men. Ah! there one of the foul things\par
is stooping on him. Help! help! Will no one go out to him? Faramir!'\par
With that Beregond sprang away and ran off into the gloom. Ashamed of his\par
terror, while Beregond of the Guard thought first of the captain whom he\par
loved, Pippin got up and peered out. At that moment he caught a flash of white\par
and silver coming from the North, like a small star down on the dusky fields.\par
It moved with the speed of an arrow and grew as it came, converging swiftly\par
with the flight of the four men towards the Gate. It seemed to Pippin that a\par
pale light was spread about it and the heavy shadows gave way before it; and\par
then as it drew near he thought that he heard, like an echo in the walls, a\par
great voice calling.\par
'Gandalf!' he cried. 'Gandalf! He always turns up when things are\par
darkest. Go on! Go on, White Rider! Gandalf, Gandalf!' he shouted wildly, like\par
an onlooker at a great race urging on a runner who is far beyond\par
encouragement.\par
But now the dark swooping shadows were aware of the newcomer. One wheeled\par
towards him; but it seemed to Pippin that he raised his hand, and from it a\par
shaft of white light stabbed upwards. The Nazg\'fbl gave a long wailing cry and\par
swerved away; and with that the four others wavered, and then rising in swift\par
spirals they passed away eastward vanishing into the lowering cloud above; and\par
down on the Pelennor it seemed for a while less dark.\par
Pippin watched, and he saw the horseman and the White Rider meet and\par
halt, waiting for those on foot. Men now hurried out to them from the City;\par
and soon they all passed from sight under the outer walls, and he knew that\par
they were entering the Gate. Guessing that they would come at once to the\par
Tower and the Steward, he hurried to the entrance of the citadel. There he was\par
joined by many others who had watched the race and the rescue from the high\par
walls.\par
It was not long before a clamour was heard in the streets leading up from\par
the outer circles, and there was much cheering and crying of the names of\par
Faramir and Mithrandir. Presently Pippin saw torches, and followed by a press\par
of people two horsemen riding slowly: one was in white but shining no longer,\par
pale in the twilight as if his fire was spent or veiled; the other was dark\par
and his head was bowed. They dismounted, and as grooms took Shadowfax and the\par
other horse, they walked forward to the sentinel at the gate: Gandalf\par
steadily, his grey cloak flung back, and a fire still smouldering in his eyes;\par
the other, clad all in green, slowly, swaying a little as a weary or a wounded\par
man.\par
Pippin pressed forward as they passed under the lamp beneath the gatearch,\par
and when he saw the pale face of Faramir he caught his breath. It was\par
the face of one who has been assailed by a great fear or anguish, but has\par
mastered it and now is quiet. Proud and grave he stood for a moment as he\par
spoke to the guard, and Pippin gazing at him saw how closely he resembled his\par
brother Boromir \endash  whom Pippin had liked from the first, admiring the great\par
man's lordly but kindly manner. Yet suddenly for Faramir his heart was\par
strangely moved with a feeling that he had not known before. Here was one with\par
an air of high nobility such as Aragorn at times revealed, less high perhaps,\par
yet also less incalculable and remote: one of the Kings of Men born into a\par
later time, but touched with the wisdom and sadness of the Elder Race. He knew\par
now why Beregond spoke his name with love. He was a captain that men would\par
follow, that he would follow, even under the shadow of the black wings.\par
'Faramir!' he cried aloud with the others. 'Faramir!' And Faramir\par
catching his strange voice among the clamour of the men of the City, turned\par
and looked down at him and was amazed.\par
'Whence come you?' he said. 'A halfling, and in the livery of the Tower!\par
Whence...?'\par
But with that Gandalf stepped to his side and spoke. 'He came with me\par
from the land of the Halflings,' he said. 'He came with me. But let us not\par
tarry here. There is much to say and to do, and you are weary. He shall come\par
with us. Indeed he must, for if he does not forget his new duties more easily\par
than I do, he must attend on his lord again within this hour. Come, Pippin,\par
follow us!'\par
So at length they came to the private chamber of the Lord of the City.\par
There deep seats were set about a brazier of charcoal; and wine was brought;\par
and there Pippin, hardly noticed, stood behind the chair of Denethor and felt\par
his weariness little, so eagerly did he listen to all that was said.\par
When Faramir had taken white bread and drunk a draught of wine, he sat\par
upon a low chair at his father's left hand. Removed a little upon the other\par
side sat Gandalf in a chair of carven wood; and he seemed at first to be\par
asleep. For at the beginning Faramir spoke only of the errand upon which he\par
had been sent out ten days before, and he brought tidings of Ithilien and of\par
movements of the Enemy and his allies; and he told of the fight on the road\par
when the men of Harad and their great beast were overthrown: a captain\par
reporting to his master such matters as had often been heard before, small\par
things of border-war that now seemed useless and petty, shorn of their renown.\par
Then suddenly Faramir looked at Pippin. 'But now we come to strange\par
matters,' he said. 'For this is not the first halfling that I have seen\par
walking out of northern legends into the Southlands.'\par
At that Gandalf sat up and gripped the arms of his chair; but he said\par
nothing, and with a look stopped the exclamation on Pippin's lips. Denethor\par
looked at their faces and nodded his head, as though in sign that he had read\par
much there before it was spoken. Slowly, while the others sat silent and\par
still, Faramir told his tale, with his eyes for the most part on Gandalf,\par
though now and again his glance strayed to Pippin, as if to refresh his memory\par
of others that he had seen.\par
As his story was unfolded of his meeting with Frodo and his servant and\par
of the events at Henneth Ann\'fbn, Pippin became aware that Gandalf's hands were\par
trembling as they clutched the carven wood. White they seemed now and very\par
old, and as he looked at them, suddenly with a thrill of fear Pippin knew that\par
Gandalf, Gandalf himself, was troubled, even afraid. The air of the room was\par
close and still. At last when Faramir spoke of his parting with the\par
travellers, and of their resolve to go to Cirith Ungol, his voice fell, and he\par
shook his head and sighed. Then Gandalf sprang up.\par
'Cirith Ungol? Morgul Vale?' he said. 'The time, Faramir, the time? When\par
did you part with them? When would they reach that accursed valley?'\par
'I parted with them in the morning two days ago,' said Faramir. 'It is\par
fifteen leagues thence to the vale of the Morgulduin, if they went straight\par
south; and then they would be still five leagues westward of the accursed\par
Tower. At swiftest they could not come there before today, and maybe they have\par
not come there yet. Indeed I see what you fear. But the darkness is not due to\par
their venture. It began yestereve, and all Ithilien was under shadow last\par
night. It is clear to me that the Enemy has long planned an assault on us, and\par
its hour had already been determined before ever the travellers left my\par
keeping.'\par
Gandalf paced the floor. 'The morning of two days ago, nigh on three days\par
of journey! How far is the place where you parted?'\par
'Some twenty-five leagues as a bird flies,' answered Faramir. 'But I\par
could not come more swiftly. Yestereve I lay at Cair Andros, the long isle in\par
the River northward which we hold in defence; and horses are kept on the\par
hither bank. As the dark drew on I knew that haste was needed, so I rode\par
thence with three others that could also be horsed. The rest of my company I\par
sent south to strengthen the garrison at the fords of Osgiliath. I hope that I\par
have not done ill?' He looked at his father.\par
'Ill?' cried Denethor, and his eyes flashed suddenly. 'Why do you ask?\par
The men were under your command. Or do you ask for my judgement on all your\par
deeds? Your bearing is lowly in my presence, yet it is long now since you\par
turned from your own way at my counsel. See, you have spoken skilfully, as\par
ever; but I, have I not seen your eye fixed on Mithrandir, seeking whether you\par
said well or too much? He has long had your heart in his keeping.\par
'My son, your father is old but not yet dotard. I can see and hear, as\par
was my wont; and little of what you have half said or left unsaid is now\par
hidden from me. I know the answer to many riddles. Alas, alas for Boromir!'\par
'If what I have done displeases you, my father,' said Faramir quietly, 'I\par
wish I had known your counsel before the burden of so weighty a judgement was\par
thrust on me.'\par
'Would that have availed to change your judgement?' said Denethor. 'You\par
would still have done just so, I deem. I know you well. Ever your desire is to\par
appear lordly and generous as a king of old, gracious, gentle. That may well\par
befit one of high race, if he sits in power and peace. But in desperate hours\par
gentleness may be repaid with death.'\par
'So be it,' said Faramir.\par
'So be it!' cried Denethor. 'But not with your death only, Lord Faramir:\par
with the death also of your father, and of all your people, whom it is your\par
part to protect now that Boromir is gone.'\par
'Do you wish then,' said Faramir, 'that our places had been exchanged?'\par
'Yes, I wish that indeed,' said Denethor. 'For Boromir was loyal to me\par
and no wizard's pupil. He would have remembered his father's need, and would\par
not have squandered what fortune gave. He would have brought me a mighty\par
gift.'\par
For a moment Faramir's restraint gave way. 'I would ask you, my father,\par
to remember why it was that I, not he, was in Ithilien. On one occasion at\par
least your counsel has prevailed, not long ago. It was the Lord of the City\par
that gave the errand to him.'\par
'Stir not the bitterness in the cup that I mixed for myself,' said\par
Denethor. 'Have I not tasted it now many nights upon my tongue foreboding that\par
worse yet lay in the dregs? As now indeed I find. Would it were not so! Would\par
that this thing had come to me!'\par
'Comfort yourself!' said Gandalf. 'In no case would Boromir have brought\par
it to you. He is dead, and died well; may he sleep in peace! Yet you deceive\par
yourself. He would have stretched out his hand to this thing, and taking it he\par
would have fallen. He would have kept it for his own, and when he returned you\par
would not have known your son.'\par
The face of Denethor set hard and cold. 'You found Boromir less apt to\par
your hand, did you not?' he said softly. 'But I who was his father say that he\par
would have brought it to me. You are wise, maybe, Mithrandir, yet with all\par
your subtleties you have not all wisdom. Counsels may be found that are\par
neither the webs of wizards nor the haste of fools. I have in this matter more\par
lore and wisdom than you deem. '\par
'What then is your wisdom?' said Gandalf.\par
'Enough to perceive that there are two follies to avoid. To use this\par
thing is perilous. At this hour, to send it in the hands of a witless halfling\par
into the land of the Enemy himself, as you have done, and this son of mine,\par
that is madness.'\par
'And the Lord Denethor what would he have done?'\par
'Neither. But most surely not for any argument would he have set this\par
thing at a hazard beyond all but a fool's hope, risking our utter ruin, if the\par
Enemy should recover what he lost. Nay, it should have been kept, hidden,\par
hidden dark and deep. Not used, I say, unless at the uttermost end of need,\par
but set beyond his grasp, save by a victory so final that what then befell\par
would not trouble us, being dead.'\par
'You think, as is your wont, my lord, of Gondor only,' said Gandalf. 'Yet\par
there are other men and other lives, and time still to be. And for me, I pity\par
even his slaves.'\par
'And where will other men look for help, if Gondor falls?' answered\par
Denethor. 'If I had this thing now in the deep vaults of this citadel, we\par
should not then shake with dread under this gloom, fearing the worst, and our\par
counsels would be undisturbed. If you do not trust me to endure the test, you\par
do not know me yet.'\par
'Nonetheless I do not trust you,' said Gandalf. 'Had I done so, I could\par
have sent this thing hither to your keeping and spared myself and others much\par
anguish. And now hearing you speak I trust you less, no more than Boromir.\par
Nay, stay your wrath! I do not trust myself in this, and I refused this thing,\par
even as a freely given gift. You are strong and can still in some matters\par
govern yourself, Denethor; yet if you had received this thing, it would have\par
overthrown you. Were it buried beneath the roots of Mindolluin, still it would\par
burn your mind away, as the darkness grows, and the yet worse things follow\par
that soon shall come upon us.'\par
For a moment the eyes of Denethor glowed again as he faced Gandalf, and\par
Pippin felt once more the strain between their wills; but now almost it seemed\par
as if their glances were like blades from eye to eye, flickering as they\par
fenced. Pippin trembled fearing some dreadful stroke. But suddenly Denethor\par
relaxed and grew cold again. He shrugged his shoulders.\par
'If I had! If you had!' he said. 'Such words and ifs are vain. It has\par
gone into the Shadow, and only time will show what doom awaits it and us. The\par
time will not be long. In what is left, let all who fight the Enemy in their\par
fashion be at one, and keep hope while they may, and after hope still the\par
hardihood to die free.' He turned to Faramir. 'What think you of the garrison\par
at Osgiliath?'\par
'It is not strong,' said Faramir. 'I have sent the company of Ithilien to\par
strengthen it, as I have said.'\par
'Not enough, I deem,' said Denethor. 'It is there that the first blow\par
will fall. They will have need of some stout captain there.'\par
'There and elsewhere in many places,' said Faramir, and sighed. 'Alas for\par
my brother, whom I too loved!' He rose. 'May I have your leave, father?' And\par
then he swayed and leaned upon his father's chair.\par
'You are weary, I see,' said Denethor. 'You have ridden fast and far, and\par
under shadows of evil in the air, I am told.'\par
'Let us not speak of that!' said Faramir.\par
'Then we will not,' said Denethor. 'Go now and rest as you may.\par
Tomorrow's need will be sterner.'\par
All now took leave of the Lord of the City and went to rest while they\par
still could. Outside there was a starless blackness as Gandalf with Pippin\par
beside him bearing a small torch, made his way to their lodging. They did not\par
speak until they were behind closed doors. Then at last Pippin took Gandalf's\par
hand.\par
'Tell me,' he said, 'is there any hope? For Frodo, I mean; or at least\par
mostly for Frodo.'\par
Gandalf put his hand on Pippin's head. 'There never was much hope,' he\par
answered. 'Just a fool's hope, as I have been told. And when I heard of Cirith\par
Ungol\endash\endash\endash ' He broke off and strode to the window as if his eyes could pierce\par
the night in the East. 'Cirith Ungol!' he muttered. 'Why that way, I wonder?'\par
He turned. 'Just now, Pippin, my heart almost failed me, hearing that name.\par
And yet in truth I believe that the news that Faramir brings has some hope in\par
it. For it seems clear that our Enemy has opened his war at last and made the\par
first move while Frodo was still free. So now for many days he will have his\par
eye turned this way and that, away from his own land. And yet, Pippin, I feel\par
from afar his haste and fear. He has begun sooner than he would. Something has\par
happened to stir him.'\par
Gandalf stood for a moment in thought. 'Maybe,' he muttered. 'Maybe even\par
your foolishness helped, my lad. Let me see: some five days ago now he would\par
discover that we had thrown down Saruman and had taken the Stone. Still what\par
of that? We could not use it to much purpose, or without his knowing. Ah! I\par
wonder. Aragorn? His time draws near. And he is strong and stern underneath,\par
Pippin; bold, determined, able to take his own counsel and dare great risks at\par
need. That may be it. He may have used the Stone and shown himself to the\par
Enemy, challenging him, for this very purpose. I wonder. Well, we shall not\par
know the answer till the Riders of Rohan come, if they do not come too late.\par
There are evil days ahead. To sleep while we may!'\par
'But,' said Pippin.\par
'But what?' said Gandalf. 'Only one _but_ will I allow tonight.'\par
'Gollum,' said Pippin. 'How on earth could they be going about _with_\par
him, even following him? And I could see that Faramir did not like the place\par
he was taking them to any more than you do. What is wrong?'\par
'I cannot answer that now,' said Gandalf. 'Yet my heart guessed that\par
Frodo and Gollum would meet before the end. For good, or for evil. But of\par
Cirith Ungol I will not speak tonight. Treachery, treachery I fear; treachery\par
of that miserable creature. But so it must be. Let us remember that a traitor\par
may betray himself and do good that he does not intend. It can be so,\par
sometimes. Good night! '\par
The next day came with a morning like a brown dusk, and the hearts of\par
men, lifted for a while by the return of Faramir, sank low again. The winged\par
Shadows were not seen again that day, yet ever and anon, high above the city,\par
a faint cry would come, and many who heard it would stand stricken with a\par
passing dread, while the less stout-hearted quailed and wept.\par
And now Faramir was gone again. 'They give him no rest,' some murmured.\par
'The Lord drives his son too hard, and now he must do the duty of two, for\par
himself and for the one that will not return.' And ever men looked northward,\par
asking: 'Where are the Riders of Rohan?'\par
In truth Faramir did not go by his own choosing. But the Lord of the City\par
was master of his Council, and he was in no mood that day to bow to others.\par
Early in the morning the Council had been summoned. There all the captains\par
judged that because of the threat in the South their force was too weak to\par
make any stroke of war on their own part, unless perchance the Riders of Rohan\par
yet should come. Meanwhile they must man the walls and wait.\par
'Yet,' said Denethor, 'we should not lightly abandon the outer defences,\par
the Rammas made with so great a labour. And the Enemy must pay dearly for the\par
crossing of the River. That he cannot do, in force to assail the City, either\par
north of Cair Andros because of the marshes, or southwards towards Lebennin\par
because of the breadth of the River, that needs many boats. It is at Osgiliath\par
that he will put his weight, as before when Boromir denied him the passage.'\par
'That was but a trial,' said Faramir. 'Today we may make the Enemy pay\par
ten times our loss at the passage and yet rue the exchange. For he can afford\par
to lose a host better than we to lose a company. And the retreat of those that\par
we put out far afield will be perilous, if he wins across in force.'\par
'And what of Cair Andros?' said the Prince. 'That, too, must be held, if\par
Osgiliath is defended. Let us not forget the danger on our left. The Rohirrim\par
may come, and they may not. But Faramir has told us of great strength drawing\par
ever to the Black Gate. More than one host may issue from it, and strike for\par
more than one passage.'\par
'Much must be risked in war,' said Denethor. 'Cair Andros is manned and\par
no more can be sent so far. But I will not yield the River and the Pelennor\par
unfought \endash  not if there is a captain here who has still the courage to do his\par
lord's will.'\par
Then all were silent, but at length Faramir said: 'I do not oppose your\par
will, sire. Since you are robbed of Boromir, I will go and do what I can in\par
his stead \endash  if you command it.'\par
'I do so,' said Denethor.\par
'Then farewell!' said Faramir. 'But if I should return, think better of\par
me!'\par
'That depends on the manner of your return,' said Denethor.\par
Gandalf it was that last spoke to Faramir ere he rode east. 'Do not throw\par
your live away rashly or in bitterness,' he said. 'You will be needed here,\par
for other things than war. Your father loves you, Faramir, and will remember\par
it ere the end. Farewell!'\par
So now the Lord Faramir had gone forth again, and had taken with him such\par
strength of men as were willing to go or could be spared. On the walls some\par
gazed through the gloom towards the ruined city, and they wondered what\par
chanced there, for nothing could be seen. And others, as ever, looked north\par
and counted the leagues to Th\'e9oden in Rohan. 'Will he come? Will he remember\par
our old alliance?' they said.\par
'Yes, he will come,' said Gandalf, 'even if he comes too late. But think!\par
At best the Red Arrow cannot have reached him more than two days ago, and the\par
miles are long from Edoras.'\par
It was night again ere news came. A man rode in haste from the fords,\par
saying that a host had issued from Minas Morgul and was already drawing nigh\par
to Osgiliath; and it had been joined by regiments from the South, Haradrim,\par
cruel and tall. 'And we have learned ' said the messenger, 'that the Black\par
Captain leads them once again, and the fear of him has passed before him over\par
the River.'\par
With those ill-boding words the third day closed since Pippin came to\par
Minas Tirith. Few went to rest, for small hope had any now that even Faramir\par
could hold the fords for long.\par
The next day, though the darkness had reached its full and grew no\par
deeper, it weighed heavier on men's hearts, and a great dread was on them. Ill\par
news came soon again. The passage of Anduin was won by the Enemy. Faramir was\par
retreating to the wall of the Pelennor, rallying his men to the Causeway\par
Forts; but he was ten times outnumbered.\par
'If he wins back at all across the Pelennor, his enemies will be on his\par
heels,' said the messenger. 'They have paid dear for the crossing but less\par
dearly than we hoped. The plan has been well laid. It is now seen that in\par
secret they have long been building floats and barges in great numbers in East\par
Osgiliath. They swarmed across like beetles. But it is the Black Captain that\par
defeats us. Few will stand and abide even the rumour of his coming. His own\par
folk quail at him, and they would slay themselves at his bidding.'\par
'Then I am needed there more than here,' said Gandalf, and rode off at\par
once, and the glimmer of him faded soon from sight. And all that night Pippin\par
alone and sleepless stood upon the wall and gazed eastward.\par
The bells of day had scarcely rung out again, a mockery in the\par
unlightened dark, when far away he saw fires spring up, across in the dim\par
spaces where the walls of the Pelennor stood. The watchmen cried aloud, and\par
all men in the City stood to arms. Now ever and anon there was a red flash,\par
and slowly through the heavy air dull rumbles could be heard.\par
'They have taken the wall!' men cried. 'They are blasting breaches in it.\par
They are coming!'\par
'Where is Faramir?' cried Beregond in dismay. 'Say not that he has\par
fallen!'\par
It was Gandalf that brought the first tidings. With a handful of horsemen\par
he came in the middle morning, riding as escort to a line of wains. They were\par
filled with wounded men, all that could be saved from the wreck of the\par
Causeway Forts. At once he went to Denethor. The Lord of the City sat now in a\par
high chamber above the Hall of the White Tower with Pippin at his side; and\par
through the dim windows, north and south and east, he bent his dark eyes, as\par
if to pierce the shadows of doom that ringed him round. Most to the north he\par
looked, and would pause at whiles to listen as if by some ancient art his ears\par
might hear the thunder of hoofs on the plains far away.\par
'Is Faramir come?' he asked.\par
'No,' said Gandalf. 'But he still lived when I left him. Yet he is\par
resolved to stay with the rearguard, lest the retreat over the Pelennor become\par
a rout. He may, perhaps, hold his men together long enough, but I doubt it. He\par
is pitted against a foe too great. For one has come that I feared.'\par
'Not \endash  the Dark Lord?' cried Pippin, forgetting his place in his terror.\par
Denethor laughed bitterly. 'Nay, not yet, Master Peregrin! He will not\par
come save only to triumph over me when all is won. He uses others as his\par
weapons. So do all great lords, if they are wise, Master Halfling. Or why\par
should I sit here in my tower and think, and watch, and wait, spending even my\par
sons? For I can still wield a brand.'\par
He stood up and cast open his long black cloak, and behold! he was clad\par
in mail beneath, and girt with a long sword, great-hilted in a sheath of black\par
and silver. 'Thus have I walked, and thus now for many years have I slept,' he\par
said, 'lest with age the body should grow soft and timid.'\par
'Yet now under the Lord of Barad-d\'fbr the most fell of all his captains is\par
already master of your outer walls,' said Gandalf. 'King of Angmar long ago,\par
Sorcerer, Ringwraith, Lord of the Nazg\'fbl, a spear of terror in the hand of\par
Sauron, shadow of despair.'\par
'Then, Mithrandir, you had a foe to match you,' said Denethor. 'For\par
myself, I have long known who is the chief captain of the hosts of the Dark\par
Tower. Is this all that you have returned to say? Or can it be that you have\par
withdrawn because you are overmatched?'\par
Pippin trembled, fearing that Gandalf would be stung to sudden wrath, but\par
his fear was needless. 'It might be so,' Gandalf answered softly. 'But our\par
trial of strength is not yet come. And if words spoken of old be true, not by\par
the hand of man shall he fall, and hidden from the Wise is the doom that\par
awaits him. However that may be, the Captain of Despair does not press\par
forward, yet. He rules rather according to the wisdom that you have just\par
spoken, from the rear, driving his slaves in madness on before.\par
'Nay, I came rather to guard the hurt men that can yet be healed; for the\par
Rammas is breached far and wide, and soon the host of Morgul will enter in at\par
many points. And I came chiefly to say this. Soon there will be battle on the\par
fields. A sortie must be made ready. Let it be of mounted men. In them lies\par
our brief hope, for in one thing only is the enemy still poorly provided: he\par
has few horsemen.'\par
'And we also have few. Now would the coming of Rohan be in the nick of\par
time,' said Denethor.\par
'We are likely to see other newcomers first,' said Gandalf. 'Fugitives\par
from Cair Andros have already reached us. The isle has fallen. Another army is\par
come from the Black Gate, crossing from the north-east.'\par
'Some have accused you, Mithrandir, of delighting to bear ill news,' said\par
Denethor, 'but to me this is no longer news: it was known to me ere nightfall\par
yesterday. As for the sortie, I had already given thought to it. Let us go\par
down.'\par
Time passed. At length watchers on the walls could see the retreat of the\par
out-companies. Small bands of weary and often wounded men came first with\par
little order; some were running wildly as if pursued. Away to the eastward the\par
distant fires flickered; and now it seemed that here and there they crept\par
across the plain. Houses and barns were burning. Then from many points little\par
rivers of red flame came hurrying on, winding through the gloom, converging\par
towards the line of the broad road that led from the City-gate to Osgiliath.\par
'The enemy,' men murmured. 'The dike is down. Here they come pouring\par
through the breaches! And they carry torches, it seems. Where are our own\par
folk?'\par
It drew now to evening by the hour, and the light was so dim that even\par
far-sighted men upon the Citadel could discern little clearly out upon the\par
fields, save only the burnings that ever multiplied, and the lines of fire\par
that grew in length and speed. At last, less than a mile from the City, a more\par
ordered mass of men came into view, marching not running, still holding\par
together.\par
The watchers held their breath. 'Faramir must be there,' they said. 'He\par
can govern man and beast. He will make it yet.'\par
Now the main retreat was scarcely two furlongs distant. Out of the gloom\par
behind a small company of horsemen galloped, all that was left of the\par
rearguard. Once again they turned at bay, facing the oncoming lines of fire.\par
Then suddenly there was a tumult of fierce cries. Horsemen of the enemy swept\par
up. The lines of fire became flowing torrents, file upon file of Orcs bearing\par
flames, and wild Southron men with red banners, shouting with harsh tongues,\par
surging up, overtaking the retreat. And with a piercing cry out of the dim sky\par
fell the winged shadows, the Nazg\'fbl stooping to the kill.\par
The retreat became a rout. Already men were breaking away, flying wild\par
and witless here and there, flinging away their weapons, crying out in fear,\par
falling to the ground.\par
And then a trumpet rang from the Citadel, and Denethor at last released\par
the sortie. Drawn up within the shadow of the Gate and under the looming walls\par
outside they had waited for his signal: all the mounted men that were left in\par
the City. Now they sprang forward, formed, quickened to a gallop, and charged\par
with a great shout. And from the walls an answering shout went up; for\par
foremost on the field rode the swan-knights of Dol Amroth with their Prince\par
and his blue banner at their head.\par
'Amroth for Gondor!' they cried. 'Amroth to Faramir!'\par
Like thunder they broke upon the enemy on either flank of the retreat;\par
but one rider outran them all, swift as the wind in the grass: Shadowfax bore\par
him, shining, unveiled once more, a light starting from his upraised hand.\par
The Nazg\'fbl screeched and swept away, for their Captain was not yet come\par
to challenge the white fire of his foe. The hosts of Morgul intent on their\par
prey, taken at unawares in wild career, broke, scattering like sparks in a\par
gale. The out-companies with a great cheer turned and smote their pursuers.\par
Hunters became the hunted. The retreat became an onslaught. The field was\par
strewn with stricken orcs and men, and a reek arose of torches cast away,\par
sputtering out in swirling smoke. The cavalry rode on.\par
But Denethor did not permit them to go far. Though the enemy was checked,\par
and for the moment driven back, great forces were flowing in from the East.\par
Again the trumpet rang, sounding the retreat. The cavalry of Gondor halted.\par
Behind their screen the out-companies re-formed. Now steadily they came\par
marching back. They reached the Gate of the City and entered, stepping\par
proudly: and proudly the people of the City looked on them and cried their\par
praise, and yet they were troubled in heart. For the companies were grievously\par
reduced. Faramir had lost a third of his men. And where was he?\par
Last of all he came. His men passed in. The mounted knights returned, and\par
at their rear the banner of Dol Amroth, and the Prince. And in his arms before\par
him on his horse he bore the body of his kinsman, Faramir son of Denethor,\par
found upon the stricken field.\par
'Faramir! Faramir!' men cried, weeping in the streets. But he did not\par
answer, and they bore him away up the winding road to the Citadel and his\par
father. Even as the Nazg\'fbl had swerved aside from the onset of the White\par
Rider, there came flying a deadly dart, and Faramir, as he held at bay a\par
mounted champion of Harad, had fallen to the earth. Only the charge of Dol\par
Amroth had saved him from the red southland swords that would have hewed him\par
as he lay.\par
The Prince Imrahil brought Faramir to the White Tower, and he said: Your\par
son has returned, lord, after great deeds, and he told all that he had seen.\par
But Denethor rose and looked on the face of his son and was silent. Then he\par
bade them make a bed in the chamber and lay Faramir upon it and depart. But he\par
himself went up alone into the secret room under the summit of the Tower; and\par
many who looked up thither at that time saw a pale light that gleamed and\par
flickered from the narrow windows for a while, and then flashed and went out.\par
And when Denethor descended again he went to Faramir and sat beside him\par
without speaking, but the face of the Lord was grey, more deathlike than his\par
son's.\par
So now at last the City was besieged, enclosed in a ring of foes. The\par
Rammas was broken, and all the Pelennor abandoned to the Enemy. The last word\par
to come from outside the walls was brought by men flying down the northward\par
road ere the Gate was shut. They were the remnant of the guard that was kept\par
at that point where the way from An\'f3rien and Rohan ran into the townlands:\par
Ingold led them, the same who had admitted Gandalf and Pippin less than five\par
days before, while the sun still rose and there was hope in the morning.\par
'There is no news of the Rohirrim,' he said. 'Rohan will not come now. Or\par
if they come, it will not avail us. The new host that we had tidings of has\par
come first, from over the River by way of Andros, it is said. They are strong:\par
battalions of Orcs of the Eye, and countless companies of Men of a new sort\par
that we have not met before. Not tall, but broad and grim, bearded like\par
dwarves, wielding great axes. Out of some savage land in the wide East they\par
come, we deem. They hold the northward road; and many have passed on into\par
An\'f3rien. The Rohirrim cannot come.'\par
The Gate was shut. All night watchmen on the walls heard the rumour of\par
the enemy that roamed outside, burning field and tree, and hewing any man that\par
they found abroad, living or dead. The numbers that had already passed over\par
the River could not be guessed in the darkness, but when morning, or its dim\par
shadow, stole over the plain, it was seen that even fear by night had scarcely\par
over-counted them. The plain was dark with their marching companies, and as\par
far as eyes could strain in the mirk there sprouted, like a foul fungusgrowth,\par
all about the beleaguered city great camps of tents, black or sombre\par
red.\par
Busy as ants hurrying orcs were digging, digging lines of deep trenches\par
in a huge ring, just out of bowshot from the walls; and as the trenches were\par
made each was filled with fire, though how it was kindled or fed, by art or\par
devilry, none could see. All day the labour went forward, while the men of\par
Minas Tirith looked on, unable to hinder it. And as each length of trench was\par
completed, they could see great wains approaching; and soon yet more companies\par
of the enemy were swiftly setting up, each behind the cover of a trench, great\par
engines for the casting of missiles. There were none upon the City walls large\par
enough to reach so far or to stay the work.\par
At first men laughed and did not greatly fear such devices. For the main\par
wall of the City was of great height and marvellous thickness, built ere the\par
power and craft of N\'famenor waned in exile; and its outward face was like to\par
the Tower of Orthanc, hard and dark and smooth, unconquerable by steel or\par
fire, unbreakable except by some convulsion that would rend the very earth on\par
which it stood.\par
'Nay,' they said, 'not if the Nameless One himself should come, not even\par
he could enter here while we yet live.' But some answered: 'While we yet live?\par
How long? He has a weapon that has brought low many strong places since the\par
world began. Hunger. The roads are cut. Rohan will not come.'\par
But the engines did not waste shot upon the indomitable wall. It was no\par
brigand or orc-chieftain that ordered the assault upon the Lord of Mordor's\par
greatest foe. A power and mind of malice guided it. As soon as the great\par
catapults were set, with many yells and the creaking of rope and winch, they\par
began to throw missiles marvellously high, so that they passed right above the\par
battlement and fell thudding within the first circle of the City; and many of\par
them by some secret art burst into flame as they came toppling down.\par
Soon there was great peril of fire behind the wall, and all who could be\par
spared were busy quelling the flames that sprang up in many places. Then among\par
the greater casts there fell another hail, less ruinous but more horrible. All\par
about the streets and lanes behind the Gate it tumbled down, small round shot\par
that did not burn. But when men ran to learn what it might be, they cried\par
aloud or wept. For the enemy was flinging into the City all the heads of those\par
who had fallen fighting at Osgiliath, or on the Rammas, or in the fields. They\par
were grim to look on; for though some were crushed and shapeless, and some had\par
been cruelly hewn, yet many had features that could be told, and it seemed\par
that they had died in pain; and all were branded with the foul token of the\par
Lidless Eye. But marred and dishonoured as they were, it often chanced that\par
thus a man would see again the face of someone that he had known, who had\par
walked proudly once in arms, or tilled the fields, or ridden in upon a holiday\par
from the green vales in the hills.\par
In vain men shook their fists at the pitiless foes that swarmed before\par
the Gate. Curses they heeded not, nor understood the tongues of western men;\par
crying with harsh voices like beasts and carrion-birds. But soon there were\par
few left in Minas Tirith who had the heart to stand up and defy the hosts of\par
Mordor. For yet another weapon, swifter than hunger, the Lord of the Dark\par
Tower had: dread and despair.\par
The Nazg\'fbl came again, and as their Dark Lord now grew and put forth his\par
strength, so their voices, which uttered only his will and his malice, were\par
filled with evil and horror. Ever they circled above the City, like vultures\par
that expect their fill of doomed men's flesh. Out of sight and shot they flew,\par
and yet were ever present, and their deadly voices rent the air. More\par
unbearable they became, not less, at each new cry. At length even the stouthearted\par
would fling themselves to the ground as the hidden menace passed over\par
them, or they would stand, letting their weapons fall from nerveless hands\par
while into their minds a blackness came, and they thought no more of war, but\par
only of hiding and of crawling, and of death.\par
During all this black day Faramir lay upon his bed in the chamber of the\par
White Tower, wandering in a desperate fever; dying someone said, and soon\par
'dying' all men were saying upon the walls and in the streets. And by him his\par
father sat, and said nothing, but watched, and gave no longer any heed to the\par
defence.\par
No hours so dark had Pippin known, not even in the clutches of the Urukhai.\par
It was his duty to wait upon the Lord, and wait he did, forgotten it\par
seemed, standing by the door of the unlit chamber, mastering his own fears as\par
best he could. And as he watched, it seemed to him that Denethor grew old\par
before his eyes, as if something had snapped in his proud will, and his stern\par
mind was overthrown. Grief maybe had wrought it, and remorse. He saw tears on\par
that once tearless face, more unbearable than wrath.\par
'Do not weep, lord,' he stammered. 'Perhaps he will get well. Have you\par
asked Gandalf?'\par
'Comfort me not with wizards!' said Denethor. 'The fool's hope has\par
failed. The Enemy has found it, and now his power waxes; he sees our very\par
thoughts, and all we do is ruinous.\par
'I sent my son forth, unthanked, unblessed, out into needless peril, and\par
here he lies with poison in his veins. Nay, nay, whatever may now betide in\par
war, my line too is ending, even the House of the Stewards has failed. Mean\par
folk shall rule the last remnant of the Kings of Men, lurking in the hills\par
until all are hounded out.'\par
Men came to the door crying for the Lord of the City. 'Nay, I will not\par
come down,' he said. 'I must stay beside my son. He might still speak before\par
the end. But that is near. Follow whom you will, even the Grey Fool, though\par
his hope has failed. Here I stay.'\par
So it was that Gandalf took command of the last defence of the City of\par
Gondor. Wherever he came men's hearts would lift again, and the winged shadows\par
pass from memory. Tirelessly he strode from Citadel to Gate, from north to\par
south about the wall; and with him went the Prince of Dol Amroth in his\par
shining mail. For he and his knights still held themselves like lords in whom\par
the race of N\'famenor ran true. Men that saw them whispered saying: 'Belike the\par
old tales speak well; there is Elvish blood in the veins of that folk, for the\par
people of Nimrodel dwelt in that land once long ago.' And then one would sing\par
amid the gloom some staves of the Lay of Nimrodel, or other songs of the Vale\par
of Anduin out of vanished years.\par
And yet \endash  when they had gone, the shadows closed on men again, and their\par
hearts went cold, and the valour of Gondor withered into ash. And so slowly\par
they passed out of a dim day of fears into the darkness of a desperate night.\par
Fires now raged unchecked in the first circle of the City, and the garrison\par
upon the outer wall was already in many places cut off from retreat. But the\par
faithful who remained there at their posts were few; most had fled beyond the\par
second gate.\par
Far behind the battle the River had been swiftly bridged, and all day\par
more force and gear of war had poured across. Now at last in the middle night\par
the assault was loosed. The vanguard passed through the trenches of fire by\par
many devious paths that had been left between them. On they came, reckless of\par
their loss as they approached, still bunched and herded, within the range of\par
bowmen on the wall. But indeed there were too few now left there to do them\par
great damage, though the light of the fires showed up many a mark for archers\par
of such skill as Gondor once had boasted. Then perceiving that the valour of\par
the City was already beaten down, the hidden Captain put forth his strength.\par
Slowly the great siege-towers built in Osgiliath rolled forward through the\par
dark.\par
Messengers came again to the chamber in the White Tower, and Pippin let\par
them enter, for they were urgent. Denethor turned his head slowly from\par
Faramir's face, and looked at them silently.\par
'The first circle of the City is burning, lord,' they said. 'What are\par
your commands? You are still the Lord and Steward. Not all will follow\par
Mithrandir. Men are flying from the walls and leaving them unmanned.'\par
'Why? Why do the fools fly?' said Denethor. 'Better to burn sooner than\par
late, for burn we must. Go back to your bonfire! And I? I will go now to my\par
pyre. To my pyre! No tomb for Denethor and Faramir. No tomb! No long slow\par
sleep of death embalmed. We will burn like heathen kings before ever a ship\par
sailed hither from the West. The West has failed. Go back and burn!'\par
The messengers without bow or answer turned and fled.\par
Now Denethor stood up and released the fevered hand of Faramir that he\par
had held. 'He is burning, already burning,' he said sadly. 'The house of his\par
spirit crumbles.' Then stepping softly towards Pippin he looked down at him.\par
'Farewell!' he said. 'Farewell, Peregrin son of Paladin! Your service has\par
been short, and now it is drawing to an end. I release you from the little\par
that remains. Go now, and die in what way seems best to you. And with whom you\par
will, even that friend whose folly brought you to this death. Send for my\par
servants and then go. Farewell!'\par
'I will not say farewell, my lord,' said Pippin kneeling. And then\par
suddenly hobbit-like once more, he stood up and looked the old man in the\par
eyes. 'I will take your leave, sir,' he said; 'for I want to see Gandalf very\par
much indeed. But he is no fool; and I will not think of dying until he\par
despairs of life. But from my word and your service I do not wish to be\par
released while you live. And if they come at last to the Citadel, I hope to be\par
here and stand beside you and earn perhaps the arms that you have given me.'\par
'Do as you will, Master Halfling,' said Denethor. 'But my life is broken.\par
Send for my servants!' He turned back to Faramir.\par
Pippin left him and called for the servants, and they came: six men of\par
the household, strong and fair; yet they trembled at the summons. But in a\par
quiet voice Denethor bade them lay warm coverlets on Faramir's bed and take it\par
up. And they did so, and lifting up the bed they bore it from the chamber.\par
Slowly they paced to trouble the fevered man as little as might be, and\par
Denethor, now bending on a staff, followed them; and last came Pippin.\par
Out from the White Tower they walked, as if to a funeral, out into the\par
darkness, where the overhanging cloud was lit beneath with flickers of dull\par
red. Softly they paced the great courtyard, and at a word from Denethor halted\par
beside the Withered Tree.\par
All was silent, save for the rumour of war in the City down below, and\par
they heard the water dripping sadly from the dead branches into the dark pool.\par
Then they went on through the Citadel gate, where the sentinel stared at them\par
in wonder and dismay as they passed by. Turning westward they came at length\par
to a door in the rearward wall of the sixth circle. Fen Hollen it was called,\par
for it was kept ever shut save at times of funeral, and only the Lord of the\par
City might use that way, or those who bore the token of the tombs and tended\par
the houses of the dead. Beyond it went a winding road that descended in many\par
curves down to the narrow land under the shadow of Mindolluin's precipice\par
where stood the mansions of the dead Kings and of their Stewards.\par
A porter sat in a little house beside the way, and with fear in his eyes\par
he came forth bearing a lantern in his hand. At the Lord's command he unlocked\par
the door, and silently it swung back; and they passed through, taking the\par
lantern from his hand. It was dark on the climbing road between ancient walls\par
and many-pillared balusters looming in the swaying lantern-beam. Their slow\par
feet echoed as they walked down, down, until at last they came to the Silent\par
Street, Rath D\'ednen, between pale domes and empty halls and images of men long\par
dead; and they entered into the House of the Stewards and set down their\par
burden.\par
There Pippin, staring uneasily about him, saw that he was in a wide\par
vaulted chamber, draped as it were with the great shadows that the little\par
lantern threw upon its shrouded walls. And dimly to be seen were many rows of\par
tables, carved of marble; and upon each table lay a sleeping form, hands\par
folded, head pillowed upon stone. But one table near at hand stood broad and\par
bare. Upon it at a sign from Denethor they laid Faramir and his father side by\par
side, and covered them with one covering, and stood then with bowed heads as\par
mourners beside a bed of death. Then Denethor spoke in a low voice.\par
'Here we will wait,' he said. 'But send not for the embalmers. Bring us\par
wood quick to burn, and lay it all about us, and beneath; and pour oil upon\par
it. And when I bid you thrust in a torch. Do this and speak no more to me.\par
Farewell!'\par
'By your leave, lord!' said Pippin and turned and fled in terror from the\par
deathly house. 'Poor Faramir!' he thought. 'I must find Gandalf. Poor Faramir!\par
Quite likely he needs medicine more than tears. Oh, where can I find Gandalf?\par
In the thick of things, I suppose; and he will have no time to spare for dying\par
men or madmen.'\par
At the door he turned to one of the servants who had remained on guard\par
there. 'Your master is not himself,' he said. 'Go slow! Bring no fire to this\par
place while Faramir lives! Do nothing until Gandalf comes!'\par
'Who is the master of Minas Tirith?' the man answered. 'The Lord Denethor\par
or the Grey Wanderer?'\par
'The Grey Wanderer or no one, it would seem,' said Pippin, and he sped\par
back and up the winding way as swiftly as his feet would carry him, past the\par
astonished porter, out through the door, and on, till he came near the gate of\par
the Citadel. The sentinel hailed him as he went by, and he recognized the\par
voice of Beregond.\par
'Whither do you run, Master Peregrin?' he cried.\par
'To find Mithrandir,' Pippin answered.\par
'The Lord's errands are urgent and should not be hindered by me,' said\par
Beregond; 'but tell me quickly, if you may: what goes forward? Whither has my\par
Lord gone? I have just come on duty, but I heard that he passed towards the\par
Closed Door, and men were bearing Faramir before him.'\par
'Yes,' said Pippin, 'to the Silent Street.'\par
Beregond bowed his head to hide his tears. 'They said that he was\par
dying,' he sighed, 'and now he is dead.'\par
'No,' said Pippin, 'not yet. And even now his death might be prevented, I\par
think. But the Lord of the City, Beregond, has fallen before his city is\par
taken. He is fey and dangerous.' Quickly he told of Denethor's strange words\par
and deeds. 'I must find Gandalf at once.'\par
'Then you must go down to the battle.'\par
'I know. The Lord has given me leave. But, Beregond, if you can, do\par
something to stop any dreadful thing happening.'\par
'The Lord does not permit those who wear the black and silver to leave\par
their post for any cause, save at his own command.'\par
'Well, you must choose between orders and the life of Faramir,' said\par
Pippin. 'And as for orders, I think you have a madman to deal with, not a\par
lord. I must run. I will return if I can.'\par
He ran on, down, down towards the outer city. Men flying back from the\par
burning passed him, and some seeing his livery turned and shouted, but he paid\par
no heed. At last he was through the Second Gate, beyond which great fires\par
leaped up between the walls. Yet it seemed strangely silent. No noise or\par
shouts of battle or din of arms could be heard. Then suddenly there was a\par
dreadful cry and a great shock, and a deep echoing boom. Forcing himself on\par
against a gust of fear and horror that shook him almost to his knees. Pippin\par
turned a corner opening on the wide place behind the City Gate. He stopped\par
dead. He had found Gandalf; but he shrank back, cowering into a shadow.\par
Ever since the middle night the great assault had gone on. The drums\par
rolled. To the north and to the south company upon company of the enemy\par
pressed to the walls. There came great beasts, like moving houses in the red\par
and fitful light, the _m\'fbmakil_ of the Harad dragging through the lanes amid\par
the fires huge towers and engines. Yet their Captain cared not greatly what\par
they did or how many might be slain: their purpose was only to test the\par
strength of the defence and to keep the men of Gondor busy in many places. It\par
was against the Gate that he would throw his heaviest weight. Very strong it\par
might be, wrought of steel and iron, and guarded with towers and bastions of\par
indomitable stone, yet it was the key, the weakest point in all that high and\par
impenetrable wall.\par
The drums rolled louder. Fires leaped up. Great engines crawled across\par
the field; and in the midst was a huge ram, great as a forest-tree a hundred\par
feet in length, swinging on mighty chains. Long had it been forging in the\par
dark smithies of Mordor, and its hideous head, founded of black steel, was\par
shaped in the likeness of a ravening wolf; on it spells of ruin lay. Grond\par
they named it, in memory of the Hammer of the Underworld of old. Great beasts\par
drew it, Orcs surrounded it, and behind walked mountain-trolls to wield it.\par
But about the Gate resistance still was stout, and there the knights of\par
Dol Amroth and the hardiest of the garrison stood at bay. Shot and dart fell\par
thick; siege-towers crashed or blazed suddenly like torches. All before the\par
walls on either side of the Gate the ground was choked with wreck and with\par
bodies of the slain; yet still driven as by a madness more and more came up.\par
Grond crawled on. Upon its housing no fire would catch; and though now\par
and again some great beast that hauled it would go mad and spread stamping\par
ruin among the orcs innumerable that guarded it, their bodies were cast aside\par
from its path and others took their place.\par
Grond crawled on. The drums rolled wildly. Over the hills of slain a\par
hideous shape appeared: a horseman, tall, hooded, cloaked in black. Slowly,\par
trampling the fallen, he rode forth, heeding no longer any dart. He halted and\par
held up a long pale sword. And as he did so a great fear fell on all, defender\par
and foe alike; and the hands of men drooped to their sides, and no bow sang.\par
For a moment all was still.\par
The drums rolled and rattled. With a vast rush Grond was hurled forward\par
by huge hands. It reached the Gate. It swung. A deep boom rumbled through the\par
City like thunder running in the clouds. But the doors of iron and posts of\par
steel withstood the stroke.\par
Then the Black Captain rose in his stirrups and cried aloud in a dreadful\par
voice, speaking in some forgotten tongue words of power and terror to rend\par
both heart and stone.\par
Thrice he cried. Thrice the great ram boomed. And suddenly upon the last\par
stroke the Gate of Gondor broke. As if stricken by some blasting spell it\par
burst asunder: there was a flash of searing lightning, and the doors tumbled\par
in riven fragments to the ground.\par
In rode the Lord of the Nazg\'fbl. A great black shape against the fires\par
beyond he loomed up, grown to a vast menace of despair. In rode the Lord of\par
the Nazg\'fbl, under the archway that no enemy ever yet had passed, and all fled\par
before his face.\par
All save one. There waiting, silent and still in the space before the\par
Gate, sat Gandalf upon Shadowfax: Shadowfax who alone among the free horses of\par
the earth endured the terror, unmoving, steadfast as a graven image in Rath\par
D\'ednen.\par
'You cannot enter here,' said Gandalf, and the huge shadow halted. 'Go\par
back to the abyss prepared for you! Go back! Fall into the nothingness that\par
awaits you and your Master. Go!'\par
The Black Rider flung back his hood, and behold! he had a kingly crown;\par
and yet upon no head visible was it set. The red fires shone between it and\par
the mantled shoulders vast and dark. From a mouth unseen there came a deadly\par
laughter.\par
'Old fool!' he said. 'Old fool! This is my hour. Do you not know Death\par
when you see it? Die now and curse in vain!' And with that he lifted high his\par
sword and flames ran down the blade.\par
Gandalf did not move. And in that very moment, away behind in some\par
courtyard of the City, a cock crowed. Shrill and clear he crowed, recking\par
nothing of wizardry or war, welcoming only the morning that in the sky far\par
above the shadows of death was coming with the dawn.\par
And as if in answer there came from far away another note. Horns, horns,\par
horns. In dark Mindolluin's sides they dimly echoed. Great horns of the North\par
wildly blowing. Rohan had come at last.\par
_Chapter 5_\par
The Ride of the Rohirrim\par
It was dark and Merry could see nothing as he lay on the ground rolled in\par
a blanket; yet though the night was airless and windless, all about him hidden\par
trees were sighing softly. He lifted his head. Then he heard it again: a sound\par
like faint drums in the wooded hills and mountain-steps. The throb would cease\par
suddenly and then be taken up again at some other point, now nearer, now\par
further off. He wondered if the watchmen had heard it.\par
He could not see them, but he knew that all round him were the companies\par
of the Rohirrim. He could smell the horses in the dark, and could hear their\par
shiftings and their soft stamping on the needle-covered ground. The host was\par
bivouacked in the pine-woods that clustered about Eilenach Beacon, a tall hill\par
standing up from the long ridges of the Dr\'faadan Forest that lay beside the\par
great road in East An\'f3rien.\par
Tired as he was Merry could not sleep. He had ridden now for four days on\par
end, and the ever-deepening gloom had slowly weighed down his heart. He began\par
to wonder why he had been so eager to come, when he had been given every\par
excuse, even his lord's command, to stay behind. He wondered, too, if the old\par
King knew that he had been disobeyed and was angry. Perhaps not. There seemed\par
to be some understanding between Dernhelm and Elfhelm, the Marshal who\par
commanded the _\'e9ored_ in which they were riding. He and all his men ignored\par
Merry and pretended not to hear if he spoke. He might have been just another\par
bag that Dernhelm was carrying. Dernhelm was no comfort: he never spoke to\par
anyone. Merry felt small, unwanted, and lonely. Now the time was anxious, and\par
the host was in peril. They were less than a day's ride from the out-walls of\par
Minas Tirith that encircled the townlands. Scouts had been sent ahead. Some\par
had not returned. Others hastening back had reported that the road was held in\par
force against them. A host of the enemy was encamped upon it, three miles west\par
of Amon D\'een, and some strength of men was already thrusting along the road and\par
was no more than three leagues away. Orcs were roving in the hills and woods\par
along the roadside. The king and \'c9omer held council in the watches of the\par
night.\par
Merry wanted somebody to talk to, and he thought of Pippin. But that only\par
increased his restlessness. Poor Pippin, shut up in the great city of stone,\par
lonely and afraid. Merry wished he was a tall Rider like \'c9omer and could blow\par
a horn or something and go galloping to his rescue. He sat up, listening to\par
the drums that were beating again, now nearer at hand. Presently he heard\par
voices speaking low, and he saw dim half-shrouded lanterns passing through the\par
trees. Men nearby began to move uncertainly in the dark.\par
A tall figure loomed up and stumbled over him, cursing the tree-roots. He\par
recognized the voice of the Marshal, Elfhelm.\par
'I am not a tree-root, Sir,' he said, 'nor a bag, but a bruised hobbit.\par
The least you can do in amends is to tell me what is afoot.'\par
'Anything that can keep so in this devil's mirk,' answered Elfhelm. 'But\par
my lord sends word that we must set ourselves in readiness: orders may come\par
for a sudden move.'\par
'Is the enemy coming then?' asked Merry anxiously. 'Are those their\par
drums? I began to think I was imagining them, as no one else seemed to take\par
any notice of them.'\par
'Nay, nay,' said Elfhelm, 'the enemy is on the road not in the hills. You\par
hear the Woses, the Wild Men of the Woods: thus they talk together from afar.\par
They still haunt Dr\'faadan Forest, it is said. Remnants of an older time they\par
be, living few and secretly, wild and wary as the beasts. They go not to war\par
with Gondor or the Mark; but now they are troubled by the darkness and the\par
coming of the orcs: they fear lest the Dark Years be returning, as seems\par
likely enough. Let us be thankful that they are not hunting us: for they use\par
poisoned arrows, it is said, and they are woodcrafty beyond compare. But they\par
have offered their services to Th\'e9oden. Even now one of their headmen is being\par
taken to the king. Yonder go the lights. So much I have heard but no more. And\par
now I must busy myself with my lord's commands. Pack yourself up, Master\par
Bag!' He vanished into the shadows.\par
Merry did not like this talk of wild men and poisoned darts, but quite\par
apart from that a great weight of dread was on him. Waiting was unbearable. He\par
longed to know what was going to happen. He got up and soon was walking warily\par
in pursuit of the last lantern before it disappeared among the trees.\par
Presently he came to an open space where a small tent had been set up for\par
the king under a great tree. A large lantern, covered above, was hanging from\par
a bough and cast a pale circle of light below. There sat Th\'e9oden and \'c9omer,\par
and before them on the ground sat a strange squat shape of a man, gnarled as\par
an old stone, and the hairs of his scanty beard straggled on his lumpy chin\par
like dry moss. He was short-legged and fat-armed, thick and stumpy, and clad\par
only with grass about his waist. Merry felt that he had seen him before\par
somewhere, and suddenly he remembered the P\'fakel-men of Dunharrow. Here was one\par
of those old images brought to life, or maybe a creature descended in true\par
line through endless years from the models used by the forgotten craftsmen\par
long ago.\par
There was a silence as Merry crept nearer, and then the Wild Man began to\par
speak, in answer to some question, it seemed. His voice was deep and guttural,\par
yet to Merry's surprise he spoke the Common Speech, though in a halting\par
fashion, and uncouth words were mingled with it.\par
'No, father of Horse-men,' he said, 'we fight not. Hunt only. Kill\par
_gorg\'fbn_ in woods, hate orc-folk. You hate _gorg\'fbn_ too. We help as we can.\par
Wild Men have long ears and long eyes; know all paths. Wild Men live here\par
before Stone-houses; before Tall Men come up out of Water.'\par
'But our need is for aid in battle,' said \'c9omer. 'How will you and your\par
folk help us?'\par
'Bring news,' said the Wild Man. 'We look out from hills. We climb big\par
mountain and look down. Stone-city is shut. Fire burns there outside; now\par
inside too. You wish to come there? Then you must be quick. But _gorg\'fbn_ and\par
men out of far-away,' he waved a short gnarled arm eastward, 'sit on horseroad.\par
Very many, more than Horse-men.'\par
'How do you know that?' said \'c9omer.\par
The old man's flat face and dark eyes showed nothing, but his voice was\par
sullen with displeasure. 'Wild men are wild, free, but not children,' he\par
answered. 'I am great headman, Gh\'e2n-buri-Gh\'e2n. I count many things: stars in\par
sky, leaves on trees, men in the dark. You have a score of scores counted ten\par
times and five. They have more. Big fight, and who will win? And many more\par
walk round walls of Stone-houses.'\par
'Alas! he speaks all too shrewdly,' said Th\'e9oden. 'And our scouts say\par
that they have cast trenches and stakes across the road. We cannot sweep them\par
away in sudden onset.'\par
'And yet we need great haste,' said \'c9omer. 'Mundburg is on fire!'\par
'Let Gh\'e2n-buri-Gh\'e2n finish!' said the Wild Man. 'More than one road he\par
knows. He will lead you by road where no pits are, no _gorg\'fbn_ walk, only Wild\par
Men and beasts. Many paths were made when Stonehouse-folk were stronger. They\par
carved hills as hunters carve beast-flesh. Wild Men think they ate stone for\par
food. They went through Dr\'faadan to Rimmon with great wains. They go no longer.\par
Road is forgotten, but not by Wild Men. Over hill and behind hill it lies\par
still under grass and tree, there behind Rimmon and down to D\'een, and back at\par
the end to Horse-men's road. Wild Men will show you that road. Then you will\par
kill _gorg\'fbn_ and drive away bad dark with bright iron, and Wild Men can go\par
back to sleep in the wild woods.'\par
\'c9omer and the king spoke together in their own tongue. At length Th\'e9oden\par
turned to the Wild Man. 'We will receive your offer,' he said. 'For though we\par
leave a host of foes behind, what matter? If the Stone-city falls, then we\par
shall have no returning. If it is saved, then the orc-host itself will be cut\par
off. If you are faithful, Gh\'e2n-buri-Gh\'e2n, then we will give you rich reward,\par
and you shall have the friendship of the Mark for ever.'\par
'Dead men are not friends to living men, and give them no gifts,' said\par
the Wild Man. 'But if you live after the Darkness, then leave Wild Men alone\par
in the woods and do not hunt them like beasts any more. Gh\'e2n-buri-Gh\'e2n will\par
not lead you into trap. He will go himself with father of Horse-men, and if he\par
leads you wrong, you will kill him.'\par
'So be it!' said Th\'e9oden.\par
'How long will it take to pass by the enemy and come back to the road?'\par
asked \'c9omer. 'We must go at foot-pace, if you guide us; and I doubt not the\par
way is narrow.'\par
'Wild Men go quick on feet,' said Gh\'e2n. 'Way is wide for four horses in\par
Stonewain Valley yonder,' he waved his hand southwards; 'but narrow at\par
beginning and at end. Wild Man could walk from here to D\'een between sunrise and\par
noon.'\par
'Then we must allow at least seven hours for the leaders,' said \'c9omer;\par
'but we must reckon rather on some ten hours for all. Things unforeseen may\par
hinder us, and if our host is all strung out, it will be long ere it can be\par
set in order when we issue from the hills. What is the hour now?'\par
'Who knows?' said Th\'e9oden. 'All is night now.'\par
'It is all dark, but it is not all night.' said Gh\'e2n. 'When Sun comes we\par
feel her, even when she is hidden. Already she climbs over East-mountains. It\par
is the opening of day in the sky-fields.'\par
'Then we must set out as soon as may be,' said \'c9omer. 'Even so we cannot\par
hope to come to Gondor's aid today.'\par
Merry waited to hear no more, but slipped away to get ready for the\par
summons to the march. This was the last stage before the battle. It did not\par
seem likely to him that many of them would survive it. But he thought of\par
Pippin and the flames in Minas Tirith and thrust down his own dread.\par
All went well that day, and no sight or sound had they of the enemy\par
waiting to waylay them. The Wild Men had put out a screen of wary hunters, so\par
that no orc or roving spy should learn of the movements in the hills. The\par
light was more dim than ever as they drew nearer to the beleaguered city, and\par
the Riders passed in long files like dark shadows of men and horses. Each\par
company was guided by a wild woodman; but old Gh\'e2n walked beside the king. The\par
start had been slower than was hoped, for it had taken time for the Riders,\par
walking and leading their horses, to find paths over the thickly wooded ridges\par
behind their camp and down into the hidden Stonewain Valley. It was late in\par
the afternoon when the leaders came to wide grey thickets stretching beyond\par
the eastward side of Amon D\'een, and masking a great gap in the line of hills\par
that from Nardol to D\'een ran east and west. Through the gap the forgotten wainroad\par
long ago had run down, back into the main horse-way from the City through\par
An\'f3rien; but now for many lives of men trees had had their way with it, and it\par
had vanished, broken and buried under the leaves of uncounted years. But the\par
thickets offered to the Riders their last hope of cover before they went into\par
open battle; for beyond them lay the road and the plains of Anduin, while east\par
and southwards the slopes were bare and rocky, as the writhen hills gathered\par
themselves together and climbed up, bastion upon bastion, into the great mass\par
and shoulders of Mindolluin.\par
The leading company was halted, and as those behind filed up out of the\par
trough of the Stonewain Valley they spread out and passed to camping-places\par
under the grey trees. The king summoned the captains to council. \'c9omer sent\par
out scouts to spy upon the road; but old Gh\'e2n shook his head.\par
'No good to send Horse-men,' he said. 'Wild Men have already seen all\par
that can be seen in the bad air. They will come soon and speak to me here.'\par
The captains came; and then out of the trees crept warily other p\'fakelshapes\par
so like old Gh\'e2n that Merry could hardly tell them apart. They spoke to\par
Gh\'e2n in a strange throaty language.\par
Presently Gh\'e2n turned to the king. 'Wild Men say many things ' he said.\par
'First, be wary! Still many men in camp beyond D\'een, an hour's walk yonder,' he\par
waved his arm west towards the black beacon. 'But none to see between here and\par
Stone-folk's new walls. Many busy there. Walls stand up no longer: _gorg\'fbn_\par
knock them down with earth-thunder and with clubs of black iron. They are\par
unwary and do not look about them. They think their friends watch all roads!'\par
At that old Gh\'e2n made a curious gurgling noise, and it seemed that he was\par
laughing.\par
'Good tidings!' cried \'c9omer. 'Even in this gloom hope gleams again. Our\par
Enemy's devices oft serve us in his despite. The accursed darkness itself has\par
been a cloak to us. And now, lusting to destroy Gondor and throw it down stone\par
from stone, his orcs have taken away my greatest fear. The out-wall could have\par
been held long against us. Now we can sweep through \endash  if once we win so far.'\par
'Once again I thank you, Gh\'e2n-buri-Gh\'e2n of the woods,' said Th\'e9oden.\par
'Good fortune go with you for tidings and for guidance!'\par
'Kill _gorg\'fbn_! Kill orc-folk! No other words please Wild Men ' answered\par
Gh\'e2n. 'Drive away bad air and darkness with bright iron!'\par
'To do these things we have ridden far,' said the king, 'and we shall\par
attempt them. But what we shall achieve only tomorrow will show.'\par
Gh\'e2n-buri-Gh\'e2n squatted down and touched the earth with his horny brow in\par
token of farewell. Then he got up as if to depart. But suddenly he stood\par
looking up like some startled woodland animal snuffling a strange air. A light\par
came in his eyes.\par
'Wind is changing!' he cried, and with that, in a twinkling as it seemed,\par
he and his fellows had vanished into the glooms, never to be seen by any Rider\par
of Rohan again. Not long after far away eastward the faint drums throbbed\par
again. Yet to no heart in all the host came any fear that the Wild Men were\par
unfaithful, strange and unlovely though they might appear.\par
'We need no further guidance,' said Elfhelm; 'for there are riders in the\par
host who have ridden down to Mundburg in days of peace. I for one. When we\par
come to the road it will veer south, and there will lie before us still seven\par
leagues ere we reach the wall of the townlands. Along most of that way there\par
is much grass on either side of the road. On that stretch the errand-riders of\par
Gondor reckoned to make their greatest speed. We may ride it swiftly and\par
without great rumour.'\par
'Then since we must look for fell deeds and the need of all our\par
strength,' said \'c9omer, 'I counsel that we rest now, and set out hence by\par
night, and so time our going that we come upon the fields when tomorrow is as\par
light as it will be, or when our lord gives the signal.'\par
To this the king assented, and the captains departed. But soon Elfhelm\par
returned. 'The scouts have found naught to report beyond the grey wood,\par
lord,' he said, 'save two men only: two dead men and two dead horses.'\par
'Well?' said \'c9omer. 'What of it?'\par
'This, lord: they were errand-riders of Gondor; Hirgon was one maybe. At\par
least his hand still clasped the Red Arrow, but his head was hewn off. And\par
this also: it would seem by the signs that they were fleeing _westward_ when\par
they fell. As I read it, they found the enemy already on the out-wall, or\par
assailing it, when they returned \endash  and that would be two nights ago, if they\par
used fresh horses from the posts, as is their wont. They could not reach the\par
City and turned back.'\par
'Alas!' said Th\'e9oden. 'Then Denethor has heard no news of our riding and\par
will despair of our coming.'\par
'_Need brooks no delay, yet late is better than never_,' said \'c9omer. 'And\par
mayhap in this time shall the old saw be proved truer than ever before since\par
men spoke with mouth.'\par
It was night. On either side of the road the host of Rohan was moving\par
silently. Now the road passing about the skirts of Mindolluin turned\par
southward. Far away and almost straight ahead there was a red glow under the\par
black sky and the sides of the great mountain loomed dark against it. They\par
were drawing near the Rammas of the Pelennor; but the day was not yet come.\par
The king rode in the midst of the leading company, his household-men\par
about him. Elfhelm's _\'e9ored_ came next; and now Merry noticed that Dernhelm\par
had left his place and in the darkness was moving steadily forward, until at\par
last he was riding just in rear of the king's guard. There came a check. Merry\par
heard voices in front speaking softly. Out-riders had come back who had\par
ventured forward almost to the wall. They came to the king.\par
'There are great fires, lord,' said one. 'The City is all set about with\par
flame, and the field is full of foes. But all seem drawn off to the assault.\par
As well as we could guess, there are few left upon the out-wall, and they are\par
heedless, busy in destruction.'\par
'Do you remember the Wild Man's words, lord?' said another. 'I live upon\par
the open Wold in days of peace; W\'eddfara is my name, and to me also the air\par
brings messages. Already the wind is turning. There comes a breath out of the\par
South; there is a sea-tang in it, faint though it be. The morning will bring\par
new things. Above the reek it will be dawn when you pass the wall.'\par
'If you speak truly, W\'eddfara, then may you live beyond this day in years\par
of blessedness!' said Th\'e9oden. He turned to the men of his household who were\par
near, and he spoke now in a clear voice so that many also of the riders of the\par
first _\'e9ored_ heard him:\par
'Now is the hour come, Riders of the Mark, sons of Eorl! Foes and fire\par
are before you, and your homes far behind. Yet, though you fight upon an alien\par
field, the glory that you reap there shall be your own for ever. Oaths ye have\par
taken: now fulfil them all, to lord and land and league of friendship!'\par
Men clashed spear upon shield.\par
'\'c9omer, my son! You lead the first _\'e9ored_,' said Th\'e9oden; 'and it shall\par
go behind the king's banner in the centre. Elfhelm, lead your company to the\par
right when we pass the wall. And Grimbold shall lead his towards the left. Let\par
the other companies behind follow these three that lead, as they have chance.\par
Strike wherever the enemy gathers. Other plans we cannot make, for we know not\par
yet how things stand upon the field. Forth now, and fear no darkness!'\par
The leading company rode off as swiftly as they could, for it was still\par
deep dark, whatever change W\'eddfara might forebode. Merry was riding behind\par
Dernhelm, clutching with the left hand while with the other he tried to loosen\par
his sword in its sheath. He felt now bitterly the truth of the old king's\par
words: _in such a battle what would you do Meriadoc?_ Just this,' he thought:\par
'encumber a rider, and hope at best to stay in my seat and not be pounded to\par
death by galloping hoofs!'\par
It was no more than a league to where the out-walls had stood. They soon\par
reached them; too soon for Merry. Wild cries broke out, and there was some\par
clash of arms, but it was brief. The orcs busy about the walls were few and\par
amazed, and they were quickly slain or driven off. Before the ruin of the\par
north-gate in the Rammas the king halted again. The first _\'e9ored_ drew up\par
behind him and about him on either side. Dernhelm kept close to the king,\par
though Elfhelm's company was away on the right. Grimbold's men turned aside\par
and passed round to a great gap in the wall further eastward.\par
Merry peered from behind Dernhelm's back. Far away, maybe ten miles or\par
more, there was a great burning, but between it and the Riders lines of fire\par
blazed in a vast crescent, at the nearest point less than a league distant. He\par
could make out little more on the dark plain, and as yet he neither saw any\par
hope of morning, nor felt any wind, changed or unchanged.\par
Now silently the host of Rohan moved forward into the field of Gondor,\par
pouring in slowly but steadily, like the rising tide through breaches in a\par
dike that men have thought secure. But the mind and will of the Black Captain\par
were bent wholly on the falling city, and as yet no tidings came to him\par
warning that his designs held any flaw.\par
After a while the king led his men away somewhat eastward, to come\par
between the fires of the siege and the outer fields. Still they were\par
unchallenged, and still Th\'e9oden gave no signal. At last he halted once again.\par
The City was now nearer. A smell of burning was in the air and a very shadow\par
of death. The horses were uneasy. But the king sat upon Snowmane, motionless,\par
gazing upon the agony of Minas Tirith, as if stricken suddenly by anguish, or\par
by dread. He seemed to shrink down, cowed by age. Merry himself felt as if a\par
great weight of horror and doubt had settled on him. His heart beat slowly.\par
Time seemed poised in uncertainty. They were too late! Too late was worse than\par
never! Perhaps Th\'e9oden would quail, bow his old head, turn, slink away to hide\par
in the hills.\par
Then suddenly Merry felt it at last, beyond doubt: a change. Wind was in\par
his face! Light was glimmering. Far, far away, in the South the clouds could\par
be dimly seen as remote grey shapes, rolling up, drifting: morning lay beyond\par
them.\par
But at that same moment there was a flash, as if lightning had sprung\par
from the earth beneath the City. For a searing second it stood dazzling far\par
off in black and white, its topmost tower like a glittering needle: and then\par
as the darkness closed again there came rolling over the fields a great\par
_boom_.\par
At that sound the bent shape of the king sprang suddenly erect. Tall and\par
proud he seemed again; and rising in his stirrups he cried in a loud voice,\par
more clear than any there had ever heard a mortal man achieve before:\par
Arise, arise, Riders of Th\'e9oden!\par
Fell deeds awake: fire and slaughter!\par
spear shall be shaken, shield be splintered,\par
a sword-day, a red day, ere the sun rises!\par
Ride now, ride now! Ride to Gondor!\par
With that he seized a great horn from Guthl\'e1f his banner-bearer, and he\par
blew such a blast upon it that it burst asunder. And straightway all the horns\par
in the host were lifted up in music, and the blowing of the horns of Rohan in\par
that hour was like a storm upon the plain and a thunder in the mountains.\par
Ride now, ride now! Ride to Gondor!\par
Suddenly the king cried to Snowmane and the horse sprang away. Behind him\par
his banner blew in the wind, white horse upon a field of green, but he\par
outpaced it. After him thundered the knights of his house, but he was ever\par
before them. \'c9omer rode there, the white horsetail on his helm floating in his\par
speed, and the front of the first _\'e9ored_ roared like a breaker foaming to the\par
shore, but Th\'e9oden could not be overtaken. Fey he seemed, or the battle-fury\par
of his fathers ran like new tire in his veins, and he was borne up on Snowmane\par
like a god of old, even as Orom\'eb the Great in the battle of the Valar when the\par
world was young. His golden shield was uncovered, and lo! it shone like an\par
image of the Sun, and the grass flamed into green about the white feet of his\par
steed. For morning came, morning and a wind from the sea; and the darkness was\par
removed, and the hosts of Mordor wailed, and terror took them, and they fled,\par
and died, and the hoofs of wrath rode over them. And then all the host of\par
Rohan burst into song, and they sang as they slew, for the joy of battle was\par
on them, and the sound of their singing that was fair and terrible came even\par
to the City.\par
_Chapter 6_\par
The Battle of the Pelennor Fields\par
But it was no orc-chieftain or brigand that led the assault upon Gondor.\par
The darkness was breaking too soon, before the date that his Master had set\par
for it: fortune had betrayed him for the moment, and the world had turned\par
against him; victory was slipping from his grasp even as he stretched out his\par
hand to seize it. But his arm was long. He was still in command, wielding\par
great powers. King, Ringwraith, Lord of the Nazg\'fbl, he had many weapons. He\par
left the Gate and vanished.\par
Th\'e9oden King of the Mark had reached the road from the Gate to the River,\par
and he turned towards the City that was now less than a mile distant. He\par
slackened his speed a little, seeking new foes, and his knights came about\par
him, and Dernhelm was with them. Ahead nearer the walls Elfhelm's men were\par
among the siege-engines, hewing, slaying, driving their foes into the firepits.\par
Well nigh all the northern half of the Pelennor was overrun, and there\par
camps were blazing, orcs were flying towards the River like herds before the\par
hunters; and the Rohirrim went hither and thither at their will. But they had\par
not yet overthrown the siege, nor won the Gate. Many foes stood before it, and\par
on the further half of the plain were other hosts still unfought. Southward\par
beyond the road lay the main force of the Haradrim, and there their horsemen\par
were gathered about the standard of their chieftain. And he looked out, and in\par
the growing light he saw the banner of the king, and that it was far ahead of\par
the battle with few men about it. Then he was filled with a red wrath and\par
shouted aloud, and displaying his standard, black serpent upon scarlet, he\par
came against the white horse and the green with great press of men; and the\par
drawing of the scimitars of the Southrons was like a glitter of stars.\par
Then Th\'e9oden was aware of him, and would not wait for his onset, but\par
crying to Snowmane he charged headlong to greet him. Great was the clash of\par
their meeting. But the white fury of the Northmen burned the hotter, and more\par
skilled was their knighthood with long spears and bitter. Fewer were they but\par
they clove through the Southrons like a fire-bolt in a forest. Right through\par
the press drove Th\'e9oden Thengel's son, and his spear was shivered as he threw\par
down their chieftain. Out swept his sword, and he spurred to the standard,\par
hewed staff and bearer; and the black serpent foundered. Then all that was\par
left unslain of their cavalry turned and fled far away.\par
But lo! suddenly in the midst of the glory of the king his golden shield\par
was dimmed. The new morning was blotted from the sky. Dark fell about him.\par
Horses reared and screamed. Men cast from the saddle lay grovelling on the\par
ground.\par
'To me! To me!' cried Th\'e9oden. 'Up Eorlingas! Fear no darkness!' But\par
Snowmane wild with terror stood up on high, fighting with the air, and then\par
with a great scream he crashed upon his side: a black dart had pierced him.\par
The king fell beneath him.\par
The great shadow descended like a falling cloud. And behold! it was a\par
winged creature: if bird, then greater than all other birds, and it was naked,\par
and neither quill nor feather did it bear, and its vast pinions were as webs\par
of hide between horned fingers; and it stank. A creature of an older world\par
maybe it was, whose kind, fingering in forgotten mountains cold beneath the\par
Moon, outstayed their day, and in hideous eyrie bred this last untimely brood,\par
apt to evil. And the Dark Lord took it, and nursed it with fell meats, until\par
it grew beyond the measure of all other things that fly; and he gave it to his\par
servant to be his steed. Down, down it came, and then, folding its fingered\par
webs, it gave a croaking cry, and settled upon the body of Snowmane, digging\par
in its claws, stooping its long naked neck.\par
Upon it sat a shape, black-mantled, huge and threatening. A crown of\par
steel he bore, but between rim and robe naught was there to see, save only a\par
deadly gleam of eyes: the Lord of the Nazg\'fbl. To the air he had returned,\par
summoning his steed ere the darkness failed, and now he was come again,\par
bringing ruin, turning hope to despair, and victory to death. A great black\par
mace he wielded.\par
But Th\'e9oden was not utterly forsaken. The knights of his house lay slain\par
about him, or else mastered by the madness of their steeds were borne far\par
away. Yet one stood there still: Dernhelm the young, faithful beyond fear; and\par
he wept, for he had loved his lord as a father. Right through the charge Merry\par
had been borne unharmed behind him, until the Shadow came; and then Windfola\par
had thrown them in his terror, and now ran wild upon the plain. Merry crawled\par
on all fours like a dazed beast, and such a horror was on him that he was\par
blind and sick.\par
'King's man! King's man!' his heart cried within him. 'You must stay by\par
him. As a father you shall be to me, you said.' But his will made no answer,\par
and his body shook. He dared not open his eyes or look up.\par
Then out of the blackness in his mind he thought that he heard Dernhelm\par
speaking; yet now the voice seemed strange, recalling some other voice that he\par
had known.\par
'Begone, foul dwimmerlaik, lord of carrion! Leave the dead in peace!'\par
A cold voice answered: 'Come not between the Nazg\'fbl and his prey! Or he\par
will not slay thee in thy turn. He will bear thee away to the houses of\par
lamentation, beyond all darkness, where thy flesh shall be devoured, and thy\par
shrivelled mind be left naked to the Lidless Eye.'\par
A sword rang as it was drawn. 'Do what you will; but I will hinder it, if\par
I may.'\par
'Hinder me? Thou fool. No living man may hinder me!'\par
Then Merry heard of all sounds in that hour the strangest. It seemed that\par
Dernhelm laughed, and the clear voice was like the ring of steel. 'But no\par
living man am I! You look upon a woman. \'c9owyn I am, \'c9omund's daughter. You\par
stand between me and my lord and kin. Begone, if you be not deathless! For\par
living or dark undead, I will smite you, if you touch him.'\par
The winged creature screamed at her, but the Ringwraith made no answer,\par
and was silent, as if in sudden doubt. Very amazement for a moment conquered\par
Merry's fear. He opened his eyes and the blackness was lifted from them. There\par
some paces from him sat the great beast, and all seemed dark about it, and\par
above it loomed the Nazg\'fbl Lord like a shadow of despair. A little to the left\par
facing them stood she whom he had called Dernhelm. But the helm of her\par
secrecy, had fallen from her, and her bright hair, released from its bonds,\par
gleamed with pale gold upon her shoulders. Her eyes grey as the sea were hard\par
and fell, and yet tears were on her cheek. A sword was in her hand, and she\par
raised her shield against the horror of her enemy's eyes.\par
\'c9owyn it was, and Dernhelm also. For into Merry's mind flashed the memory\par
of the face that he saw at the riding from Dunharrow: the face of one that\par
goes seeking death, having no hope. Pity filled his heart and great wonder,\par
and suddenly the slow-kindled courage of his race awoke. He clenched his hand.\par
She should not die, so fair, so desperate At least she should not die alone,\par
unaided.\par
The face of their enemy was not turned towards him, but still he hardly\par
dared to move, dreading lest the deadly eyes should fall on him. Slowly,\par
slowly he began to crawl aside; but the Black Captain, in doubt and malice\par
intent upon the woman before him, heeded him no more than a worm in the mud.\par
Suddenly the great beast beat its hideous wings, and the wind of them was\par
foul. Again it leaped into the air, and then swiftly fell down upon \'c9owyn,\par
shrieking, striking with beak and claw.\par
Still she did not blench: maiden of the Rohirrim, child of kings, slender\par
but as a steel-blade, fair but terrible. A swift stroke she dealt, skilled and\par
deadly. The outstretched neck she clove asunder, and the hewn head fell like a\par
stone. Backward she sprang as the huge shape crashed to ruin, vast wings\par
outspread, crumpled on the earth; and with its fall the shadow passed away. A\par
light fell about her, and her hair shone in the sunrise.\par
Out of the wreck rose the Black Rider, tall and threatening, towering\par
above her. With a cry of hatred that stung the very ears like venom he let\par
fall his mace. Her shield was shivered in many pieces, and her arm was broken;\par
she stumbled to her knees. He bent over her like a cloud, and his eyes\par
glittered; he raised his mace to kill.\par
But suddenly he too stumbled forward with a cry of bitter pain, and his\par
stroke went wide, driving into the ground. Merry's sword had stabbed him from\par
behind, shearing through the black mantle, and passing up beneath the hauberk\par
had pierced the sinew behind his mighty knee.\par
'\'c9owyn! \'c9owyn!' cried Merry. Then tottering, struggling up, with her last\par
strength she drove her sword between crown and mantle, as the great shoulders\par
bowed before her. The sword broke sparkling into many shards. The crown rolled\par
away with a clang. \'c9owyn fell forward upon her fallen foe. But lo! the mantle\par
and hauberk were empty. Shapeless they lay now on the ground, torn and\par
tumbled; and a cry went up into the shuddering air, and faded to a shrill\par
wailing, passing with the wind, a voice bodiless and thin that died, and was\par
swallowed up, and was never heard again in that age of this world.\par
And there stood Meriadoc the hobbit in the midst of the slain, blinking\par
like an owl in the daylight, for tears blinded him; and through a mist he\par
looked on \'c9owyn's fair head, as she lay and did not move; and he looked on the\par
face of the king, fallen in the midst of his glory, For Snowmane in his agony\par
had rolled away from him again; yet he was the bane of his master.\par
Then Merry stooped and lifted his hand to kiss it, and lo! Th\'e9oden opened\par
his eyes, and they were clear, and he spoke in a quiet voice though laboured.\par
'Farewell, Master Holbytla!' he said. 'My body is broken. I go to my\par
fathers. And even in their mighty company I shall not now be ashamed. I felled\par
the black serpent. A grim morn, and a glad day, and a golden sunset!'\par
Merry could not speak, but wept anew. 'Forgive me, lord,' he said at\par
last, 'if I broke your command, and yet have done no more in your service than\par
to weep at our parting.'\par
The old king smiled. 'Grieve not! It is forgiven. Great heart will not be\par
denied. Live now in blessedness; and when you sit in peace with your pipe,\par
think of me! For never now shall I sit with you in Meduseld, as I promised, or\par
listen to your herb-lore.' He closed his eyes, and Merry bowed beside him.\par
Presently he spoke again. 'Where is \'c9omer? For my eyes darken, and I would see\par
him ere I go. He must be king after me. And I would send word to \'c9owyn. She,\par
she would not have me leave her, and now I shall not see her again, dearer\par
than daughter.'\par
'Lord, lord,' began Merry brokenly, 'she is-'; but at that moment there\par
was a great clamour, and all about them horns and trumpets were blowing. Merry\par
looked round: he had forgotten the war, and all the world beside, and many\par
hours it seemed since the king rode to his fall, though in truth it was only a\par
little while. But now he saw that they were in danger of being caught in the\par
very midst of the great battle that would soon be joined.\par
New forces of the enemy were hastening up the road from the River; and\par
from under the walls came the legions of Morgul; and from the southward fields\par
came footmen of Harad with horsemen before them, and behind them rose the huge\par
backs of the _m\'fbmakil_ with war-towers upon them. But northward the white\par
crest of \'c9omer led the great front of the Rohirrim which he had again gathered\par
and marshalled; and out of the City came all the strength of men that was in\par
it, and the silver swan of Dol Amroth was borne in the van, driving the enemy\par
from the Gate.\par
For a moment the thought flitted through Merry's mind: 'Where is Gandalf?\par
Is he not here? Could he not have saved the king and \'c9owyn?' But thereupon\par
\'c9omer rode up in haste, and with him came the knights of the household that\par
still lived and had now mastered their horses. They looked in wonder at the\par
carcase of the fell beast that lay there: and their steeds would not go near.\par
But \'c9omer leaped from the saddle, and grief and dismay fell upon him as he\par
came to the king's side and stood there in silence.\par
Then one of the knights took the king's banner from the hand of Guthl\'e1f\par
the banner-bearer who lay dead, and he lifted it up. Slowly Th\'e9oden opened his\par
eyes. Seeing the banner he made a sign that it should be given to \'c9omer.\par
'Hail, King of the Mark!' he said. 'Ride now to victory! Bid \'c9owyn\par
farewell!' And so he died, and knew not that \'c9owyn lay near him. And those who\par
stood by wept, crying: 'Th\'e9oden King! Th\'e9oden King!'\par
But \'c9omer said to them:\par
Mourn not overmuch! Mighty was the fallen,\par
meet was his ending. When his mound is raised,\par
women then shall weep. War now calls us!\par
Yet he himself wept as he spoke. 'Let his knights remain here,' he said;\par
'and bear his body in honour from the field, lest the battle ride over it!\par
Yea, and all these other of the king's men that lie here.' And he looked at\par
the slain, recalling their names. Then suddenly he beheld his sister \'c9owyn as\par
she lay, and he knew her. He stood a moment as a man who is pierced in the\par
midst of a cry by an arrow through the heart; and then his face went deathly\par
white; and a cold fury rose in him, so that all speech failed him for a while.\par
A fey mood took him.\par
'\'c9owyn, \'c9owyn!' he cried at last: '\'c9owyn, how come you here? What madness\par
or devilry is this? Death, death, death! Death take us all!'\par
Then without taking counsel or waiting for the approach of the men of the\par
City, he spurred headlong back to the front of the great host, and blew a\par
horn, and cried aloud for the onset. Over the field rang his clear voice\par
calling: 'Death! Ride, ride to ruin and the world's ending!'\par
And with that the host began to move. But the Rohirrim sang no more.\par
_Death_ they cried with one voice loud and terrible, and gathering speed like\par
a great tide their battle swept about their fallen king and passed, roaring\par
away southwards.\par
And still Meriadoc the hobbit stood there blinking through his tears and\par
no one spoke to him, indeed none seemed to heed him. He brushed away the\par
tears, and stooped to pick up the green shield that \'c9owyn had given him; and\par
he slung it at his back. Then he looked for his sword that he had let fall;\par
for even as he struck his blow his arm was numbed, and now he could only use\par
his left hand. And behold! there lay his weapon, but the blade was smoking\par
like a dry branch that has been thrust in a fire; and as he watched it, it\par
writhed and withered and was consumed.\par
So passed the sword of the Barrow-downs, work of Westernesse. But glad\par
would he have been to know its fate who wrought it slowly long ago in the\par
North-kingdom when the D\'fanedain were young, and chief among their foes was the\par
dread realm of Angmar and its sorcerer king. No other blade, not though\par
mightier hands had wielded it, would have dealt that foe a wound so bitter,\par
cleaving the undead flesh, breaking the spell that knit his unseen sinews to\par
his will.\par
Men now raised the king, and laying cloaks upon spear-truncheons they\par
made shift to bear him away towards the City; and others lifted \'c9owyn gently\par
up and bore her after him. But the men of the king's household they could not\par
yet bring from the field; for seven of the king's knights had fallen there,\par
and D\'e9orwine their chief was among them. So they laid them apart from their\par
foes and the fell beast and set spears about them. And afterwards when all was\par
over men returned and made a fire there and burned the carcase of the beast;\par
but for Snowmane they dug a grave and set up a stone upon which was carved in\par
the tongues of Gondor and the Mark:\par
Faithful servant yet master's bane\par
Lightfoot's foal, swift Snowmane.\par
Green and long grew the grass on Snowmane's Howe, but ever black and bare\par
was the ground where the beast was burned.\par
Now slowly and sadly Merry walked beside the bearers, and he gave no more\par
heed to the battle. He was weary and full of pain, and his limbs trembled as\par
with a chill. A great rain came out of the Sea, and it seemed that all things\par
wept for Th\'e9oden and \'c9owyn, quenching the fires in the City with grey tears.\par
It was through a mist that presently he saw the van of the men of Gondor\par
approaching. Imrahil, Prince of Dol Amroth, rode up and drew rein before them.\par
'What burden do you bear, Men of Rohan?' he cried.\par
'Th\'e9oden King,' they answered. 'He is dead. But \'c9omer King now rides in\par
the battle: he with the white crest in the wind.'\par
Then the prince went from his horse, and knelt by the bier in honour of\par
the king and his great onset; and he wept. And rising he looked then on \'c9owyn\par
and was amazed. 'Surely, here is a woman?' he said. 'Have even the women of\par
the Rohirrim come to war in our need?'\par
'Nay! One only,' they answered. 'The Lady \'c9owyn is she, sister of \'c9omer;\par
and we knew naught of her riding until this hour, and greatly we rue it.'\par
Then the prince seeing her beauty, though her face was pale and cold,\par
touched her hand as he bent to look more closely on her. 'Men of Rohan!' he\par
cried. 'Are there no leeches among you? She is hurt to the death maybe, but I\par
deem that she yet lives.' And he held the bright-burnished vambrace that was\par
upon his arm before her cold tips, and behold! a little mist was laid on it\par
hardly to be seen.\par
'Haste now is needed,' he said, and he sent one riding back swiftly to\par
the City to bring aid. But he bowing low to the fallen, bade them farewell,\par
and mounting rode away into battle.\par
And now the fighting waxed furious on the fields of the Pelennor; and the\par
din of arms rose upon high, with the crying of men and the neighing of horses.\par
Horns were blown and trumpets were braying, and the _m\'fbmakil_ were bellowing\par
as they were goaded to war. Under the south walls of the City the footmen of\par
Gondor now drove against the legions of Morgul that were still gathered there\par
in strength. But the horsemen rode eastward to the succour of \'c9omer: H\'farin the\par
Tall Warden of the Keys, and the Lord of Lossarnach, and Hirluin of the Green\par
Hills, and Prince Imrahil the fair with his knights all about him.\par
Not too soon came their aid to the Rohirrim; for fortune had turned\par
against \'c9omer, and his fury had betrayed him. The great wrath of his onset had\par
utterly overthrown the front of his enemies, and great wedges of his Riders\par
had passed clear through the ranks of the Southrons, discomfiting their\par
horsemen and riding their footmen to ruin. But wherever the _m\'fbmakil_ came\par
there the horses would not go, but blenched and swerved away; and the great\par
monsters were unfought, and stood like towers of defence, and the Haradrim\par
rallied about them. And if the Rohirrim at their onset were thrice outnumbered\par
by the Haradrim alone, soon their case became worse; for new strength came now\par
streaming to the field out of Osgiliath. There they had been mustered for the\par
sack of the City and the rape of Gondor, waiting on the call of their Captain.\par
He now was destroyed; but Gothmog the lieutenant of Morgul had flung them into\par
the fray; Easterlings with axes, and Variags of Khand. Southrons in scarlet,\par
and out of Far Harad black men like half-trolls with white eyes and red\par
tongues. Some now hastened up behind the Rohirrim, others held westward to\par
hold off the forces of Gondor and prevent their joining with Rohan.\par
It was even as the day thus began to turn against Gondor and their hope\par
wavered that a new cry went up in the City, it being then midmorning, and a\par
great wind blowing, and the rain flying north, and the sun shining. In that\par
clear air watchmen on the walls saw afar a new sight of fear, and their last\par
hope left them.\par
For Anduin, from the bend at the Harlond, so flowed that from the City\par
men could look down it lengthwise for some leagues, and the far-sighted could\par
see any ships that approached. And looking thither they cried in dismay; for\par
black against the glittering stream they beheld a fleet borne up on the wind:\par
dromunds, and ships of great draught with many oars, and with black sails\par
bellying in the breeze.\par
'The Corsairs of Umbar!' men shouted. 'The Corsairs of Umbar! Look! The\par
Corsairs of Umbar are coming! So Belfalas is taken, and the Ethir, and\par
Lebennin is gone. The Corsairs are upon us! It is the last stroke of doom!'\par
And some without order, for none could he found to command them in the\par
City, ran to the bells and tolled the alarm; and some blew the trumpets\par
sounding the retreat. 'Back to the walls!' they cried. 'Back to the walls!\par
Come back to the City before all are overwhelmed!' But the wind that sped the\par
ships blew all their clamour away.\par
The Rohirrim indeed had no need of news or alarm. All too well they could\par
see for themselves the black sails. For \'c9omer was now scarcely a mile from the\par
Harlond, and a great press of his first foes was between him and the haven\par
there, while new foes came swirling behind, cutting him off from the Prince.\par
Now he looked to the River, and hope died in his heart, and the wind that he\par
had blessed he now called accursed. But the hosts of Mordor were enheartened,\par
and filled with a new lust and fury they came yelling to the onset.\par
Stern now was \'c9omer's mood, and his mind clear again. He let blow the\par
horns to rally all men to his banner that could come thither; for he thought\par
to make a great shield-wall at the last, and stand, and fight there on foot\par
till all fell, and do deeds of song on the fields of Pelennor, though no man\par
should be left in the West to remember the last King of the Mark. So he rode\par
to a green hillock and there set his banner, and the White Horse ran rippling\par
in the wind.\par
Out of doubt, out of dark to the day's rising\par
I came singing in the sun, sword unsheathing.\par
To hope's end I rode and to heart's breaking:\par
Now for wrath, now for ruin and a red nightfall!\par
These staves he spoke, yet he laughed as he said them. For once more lust\par
of battle was on him; and he was still unscathed, and he was young, and he was\par
king: the lord of a fell people. And lo! even as he laughed at despair he\par
looked out again on the black ships, and he lifted up his sword to defy them.\par
And then wonder took him, and a great joy; and he cast his sword up in\par
the sunlight and sang as he caught it. And all eyes followed his gaze, and\par
behold! upon the foremost ship a great standard broke, and the wind displayed\par
it as she turned towards the Harlond. There flowered a White Tree, and that\par
was for Gondor; but Seven Stars were about it, and a high crown above it, the\par
signs of Elendil that no lord had borne for years beyond count. And the stars\par
flamed in the sunlight, for they were wrought of gems by Arwen daughter of\par
Elrond; and the crown was bright in the morning, for it was wrought of mithril\par
and gold.\par
Thus came Aragorn son of Arathorn, Elessar, Isildur's heir, out of the\par
Paths of the Dead, borne upon a wind from the Sea to the kingdom of Gondor;\par
and the mirth of the Rohirrim was a torrent of laughter and a flashing of\par
swords, and the joy and wonder of the City was a music of trumpets and a\par
ringing of bells. But the hosts of Mordor were seized with bewilderment, and a\par
great wizardry it seemed to them that their own ships should be filled with\par
their foes; and a black dread fell on them, knowing that the tides of fate had\par
turned against them and their doom was at hand.\par
East rode the knights of Dol Amroth driving the enemy before them: trollmen\par
and Variags and orcs that hated the sunlight. South strode \'c9omer and men\par
fled before his face, and they were caught between the hammer and the anvil.\par
For now men leaped from the ships to the quays of the Harlond and swept north\par
like a storm. There came Legolas, and Gimli wielding his axe, and Halbarad\par
with the standard, and Elladan and Elrohir with stars on their brow, and the\par
dour-handed D\'fanedain, Rangers of the North, leading a great valour of the folk\par
of Lebennin and Lamedon and the fiefs of the South. But before all went\par
Aragorn with the Flame of the West, And\'faril like a new fire kindled, Narsil\par
re-forged as deadly as of old: and upon his brow was the Star of Elendil.\par
And so at length \'c9omer and Aragorn met in the midst of the battle, and\par
they leaned on their swords and looked on one another and were glad.\par
'Thus we meet again, though all the hosts of Mordor lay between us,' said\par
Aragorn. 'Did I not say so at the Hornburg?'\par
'So you spoke,' said \'c9omer, 'but hope oft deceives, and I knew not then\par
that you were a man foresighted. Yet twice blessed is help unlooked for, and\par
never was a meeting of friends more joyful.' And they clasped hand in hand.\par
'Nor indeed more timely,' said \'c9omer. 'You come none too soon, my friend. Much\par
loss and sorrow has befallen us.'\par
'Then let us avenge it, ere we speak of it!' said Aragorn, and they rode\par
back to battle together.\par
Hard fighting and long labour they had still; for the Southrons were bold\par
men and grim, and fierce in despair; and the Easterlings were strong and warhardened\par
and asked for no quarter. And so in this place and that, by burned\par
homestead or barn, upon hillock or mound, under wall or on field, still they\par
gathered and rallied and fought until the day wore away.\par
Then the Sun went at last behind Mindolluin and filled all the sky with a\par
great burning, so that the hills and the mountains were dyed as with blood;\par
fire glowed in the River, and the grass of the Pelennor lay red in the\par
nightfall. And in that hour the great Battle of the field of Gondor was over;\par
and not one living foe was left within the circuit of the Rammas. All were\par
slain save those who fled to die, or to drown in the red foam of the River.\par
Few ever came eastward to Morgul or Mordor; and to the land of the Haradrim\par
came only a tale from far off: a rumour of the wrath and terror of Gondor.\par
Aragorn and \'c9omer and Imrahil rode back towards the Gate of the City, and\par
they were now weary beyond joy or sorrow. These three were unscathed, for such\par
was their fortune and the skill and might of their arms, and few indeed had\par
dared to abide them or look on their faces in the hour of their wrath. But\par
many others were hurt or maimed or dead upon the field. The axes hewed Forlong\par
as he fought alone and unhorsed; and both Duilin of Morthond and his brother\par
were trampled to death when they assailed the _m\'fbmakil_, leading their bowmen\par
close to shoot at the eyes of the monsters. Neither Hirluin the fair would\par
return to Pinnath Gelin, nor Grimbold to Grimslade, nor Halbarad to the\par
Northlands, dour-handed Ranger. No few had fallen, renowned or nameless,\par
captain or soldier; for it was a great battle and the full count of it no tale\par
has told. So long afterward a maker in Rohan said in his song of the Mounds of\par
Mundburg:\par
We heard of the horns in the hills ringing,\par
the swords shining in the South-kingdom.\par
Steeds went striding to the Stoningland\par
as wind in the morning. War was kindled.\par
There Th\'e9oden fell, Thengling mighty,\par
to his golden halls and green pastures\par
in the Northern fields never returning,\par
high lord of the host. Harding and Guthl\'e1f\par
D\'fanhere and D\'e9orwine, doughty Grimbold,\par
Herefara and Herubrand, Horn and Fastred,\par
fought and fell there in a far country:\par
in the Mounds of Mundburg under mould they lie\par
with their league-fellows, lords of Gondor.\par
Neither Hirluin the Fair to the hills by the sea,\par
nor Forlong the old to the flowering vales\par
ever, to Arnach, to his own country\par
returned in triumph; nor the tall bowmen,\par
Derufin and Duilin, to their dark waters,\par
meres of Morthond under mountain-shadows.\par
Death in the morning and at day's ending\par
lords took and lowly. Long now they sleep\par
under grass in Gondor by the Great River.\par
Grey now as tears, gleaming silver,\par
red then it rolled, roaring water:\par
