or have you not heard the strange tidings that have come to the City?'\par
'I have been too busy with this and that to heed all the crying and\par
shouting,' she answered. 'All I hope is that those murdering devils do not\par
come to this House and trouble the sick.'\par
Then Gandalf went out in haste, and already the fire in the sky was\par
burning out, and the smouldering hills were fading, while ash-grey evening\par
crept over the fields.\par
Now as the sun went down Aragorn and \'c9omer and Imrahil drew near the City\par
with their captains and knights; and when they came before the Gate Aragorn\par
said:\par
'Behold the Sun setting in a great fire! It is a sign of the end and fall\par
of many things, and a change in the tides of the world. But this City and\par
realm has rested in the charge of the Stewards for many long years, and I fear\par
that if I enter it unbidden, then doubt and debate may arise, which should not\par
be while this war is fought. I will not enter in, nor make any claim, until it\par
be seen whether we or Mordor shall prevail. Men shall pitch my tents upon the\par
field, and here I will await the welcome of the Lord of the City.'\par
But \'c9omer said: 'Already you have raised the banner of the Kings and\par
displayed the tokens of Elendil's House. Will you suffer these to be\par
challenged?'\par
'No,' said Aragorn. 'But I deem the time unripe; and I have no mind for\par
strife except with our Enemy and his servants.'\par
And the Prince Imrahil said. Your words, lord, are wise, if one who is a\par
kinsman of the Lord Denethor may counsel you in this matter. He is strongwilled\par
and proud, but old; and his mood has been strange since his son was\par
stricken down. Yet I would not have you remain like a beggar at the door.'\par
'Not a beggar,' said Aragorn. 'Say a captain of the Rangers, who are\par
unused to cities and houses of stone.' And he commanded that his banner should\par
