dealings with the Enemy.' And they agreed upon that.\par
Then Gandalf said: 'Let us not stay at the door, for the time is urgent.\par
Let us enter! For it is only in the coming of Aragorn that any hope remains\par
for the sick that lie in the House. Thus spake Ioreth, wise-woman of Gondor:\par
_The hands of the king are the hands of a healer, and so shall the rightful\par
king be known_.'\par
Then Aragorn entered first and the others followed. And there at the door\par
were two guards in the livery of the Citadel: one tall, but the other scarce\par
the height of a boy; and when he saw them he cried aloud in surprise and joy.\par
'Strider! How splendid! Do you know, I guessed it was you in the black\par
ships. But they were all shouting _corsairs_ and wouldn't listen to me. How\par
did you do it?'\par
Aragorn laughed, and took the hobbit by the hand. 'Well met indeed!' he\par
said. 'But there is not time yet for travellers' tales.'\par
But Imrahil said to \'c9omer: 'Is it thus that we speak to our kings? Yet\par
maybe he will wear his crown in some other name!'\par
And Aragorn hearing him, turned and said: 'Verily, for in the high tongue\par
of old I am _Elessar_, the _Elfstone_, and _Envinyatar_, the Renewer': and he\par
lifted from his breast the green stone that lay there. 'But Strider shall be\par
the name of my house, if that be ever established. In the high tongue it will\par
not sound so ill, and _Telcontar_ I will be and all the heirs of my body.'\par
And with that they passed into the House; and as they went towards the\par
rooms where the sick were tended Gandalf told of the deeds of \'c9owyn and\par
Meriadoc. 'For,' he said, 'long have I stood by them and at first they spoke\par
much in their dreaming, before they sank into the deadly darkness. Also it is\par
given to me to see many things far off.'\par
Aragorn went first to Faramir, and then to the Lady \'c9owyn, and last to\par
Merry. When he had looked on the faces of the sick and seen their hurts he\par
sighed. 'Here I must put forth all such power and skill as is given to me,' he\par
said. 'Would that Elrond were here, for he is the eldest of all our race, and\par
has the greater power.'\par
And \'c9omer seeing that he was sorrowful and weary said: 'First you must\par
rest, surely, and at the least eat a little?'\par
But Aragorn answered: 'Nay, for these three, and most soon for Faramir,\par
time is running out. All speed is needed.'\par
Then he called to Ioreth and he said: 'You have store in this House of\par
the herbs of healing?'\par
'Yes, lord,' she answered; 'but not enough, I reckon, for all that will\par
need them. But I am sure I do not know where we shall find more; for all\par
things are amiss in these dreadful days, what with fires and burnings, and the\par
lads that run errands so few, and all the roads blocked. Why, it is days out\par
of count since ever a carrier came in from Lossarnach to the market! But we do\par
our best in this House with what we have, as I am sure your lordship will\par
know.'\par
'I will judge that when I see,' said Aragorn. 'One thing also is short\par
time for speech. Have you _athelas_?'\par
'I do not know, I am sure, lord,' she answered, 'at least not by that\par
name. I will go and ask of the herb-master; he knows all the old names.'\par
'It is also called _kingsfoil_,' said Aragorn; 'and maybe you know it by\par
that name, for so the country-folk call it in these latter days.' 'Oh that!'\par
said Ioreth. 'Well, if your lordship had named it at first I could have told\par
you. No, we have none of it, I am sure. Why, I have never heard that it had\par
any great virtue; and indeed I have often said to my sisters when we came upon\par
it growing in the woods: "kingsfoil" I said, " 'tis a strange name, and I\par
wonder why 'tis called so; for if I were a king, I would have plants more\par
bright in my garden". Still it smells sweet when bruised, does it not? If\par
sweet is the right word: wholesome, maybe, is nearer.'\par
'Wholesome verily,' said Aragorn. 'And now, dame, if you love the Lord\par
Faramir, run as quick as your tongue and get me kingsfoil, if there is a leaf\par
in the City.'\par
'And if not,' said Gandalf, 'I will ride to Lossarnach with Ioreth behind\par
me, and she shall take me to the woods, but not to her sisters. And Shadowfax\par
shall show her the meaning of haste.'\par
When Ioreth was gone, Aragorn bade the other women to make water hot.\par
Then he took Faramir's hand in his, and laid the other hand upon the sick\par
man's brow. It was drenched with sweat; but Faramir did not move or make any\par
sign, and seemed hardly to breathe.\par
'He is nearly spent,' said Aragorn turning to Gandalf. 'But this comes\par
not from the wound. See! that is healing. Had he been smitten by some dart of\par
the Nazg\'fbl, as you thought, he would have died that night. This hurt was given\par
by some Southron arrow, I would guess. Who drew it forth? Was it kept?'\par
'I drew it forth,' said Imrahil, 'and staunched the wound. But I did not\par
keep the arrow, for we had much to do. It was, as I remember, just such a dart\par
as the Southrons use. Yet I believed that it came from the Shadows above, for\par
else his fever and sickness were not to be understood; since the wound was not\par
deep or vital. How then do you read the matter?'\par
'Weariness, grief for his father's mood, a wound, and over all the Black\par
Breath,' said Aragorn. 'He is a man of staunch will, for already he had come\par
close under the Shadow before ever he rode to battle on the out-walls. Slowly\par
the dark must have crept on him, even as he fought and strove to hold his\par
outpost. Would that I could have been here sooner!'\par
Thereupon the herb-master entered. 'Your lordship asked for kingsfoil, as\par
the rustics name it, he said; or _athelas_ in the noble tongue, or to those\par
who know somewhat of the Valinorean. . .'\par
'I do so,' said Aragorn, 'and I care not whether you say now _as\'eba\par
aranion_ or _kingsfoil_, so long as you have some.'\par
'Your pardon lord!' said the man. 'I see you are a lore-master, not\par
merely a captain of war. But alas! sir, we do not keep this thing in the\par
Houses of Healing, where only the gravely hurt or sick are tended. For it has\par
no virtue that we know of, save perhaps to sweeten a fouled air, or to drive\par
away some passing heaviness. Unless, of course, you give heed to rhymes of old\par
days which women such as our good Ioreth still repeat without understanding.\par
When the black breath blows\par
and death's shadow grows\par
and all lights pass,\par
come athelas! come athelas!\par
Life to the dying\par
In the king's hand lying!\par
It is but a doggrel, I fear, garbled in the memory of old wives. Its\par
meaning I leave to your judgement, if indeed it has any. But old folk still\par
use an infusion of the herb for headaches.'\par
'Then in the name of the king, go and find some old man of less lore and\par
more wisdom who keeps some in his house!' cried Gandalf.\par
Now Aragorn knelt beside Faramir, and held a hand upon his brow. And\par
those that watched felt that some great struggle was going on. For Aragorn's\par
face grew grey with weariness; and ever and anon he called the name of\par
Faramir, but each time more faintly to their hearing, as if Aragorn himself\par
was removed from them, and walked afar in some dark vale, calling for one that\par
was lost.\par
And at last Bergil came running in, and he bore six leaves in a cloth.\par
'It is kingsfoil, Sir,' he said; 'but not fresh, I fear. It must have been\par
culled two weeks ago at the least. I hope it will serve, Sir?' Then looking at\par
Faramir he burst into tears.\par
But Aragorn smiled. 'It will serve,' he said. 'The worst is now over.\par
Stay and be comforted!' Then taking two leaves, he laid them on his hands and\par
breathed on them, and then he crushed them, and straightway a living freshness\par
filled the room, as if the air itself awoke and tingled, sparkling with joy.\par
And then he cast the leaves into the bowls of steaming water that were brought\par
to him, and at once all hearts were lightened. For the fragrance that came to\par
each was like a memory of dewy mornings of unshadowed sun in some land of\par
which the fair world in Spring is itself but a fleeting memory. But Aragorn\par
stood up as one refreshed, and his eyes smiled as he held a bowl before\par
Faramir's dreaming face.\par
'Well now! Who would have believed it?' said Ioreth to a woman that stood\par
beside her. 'The weed is better than I thought. It reminds me of the roses of\par
Imloth Melui when I was a lass, and no king could ask for better.'\par
Suddenly Faramir stirred, and he opened his eyes, and he looked on\par
Aragorn who bent over him; and a light of knowledge and love was kindled in\par
his eyes, and he spoke softly. 'My lord, you called me. I come. What does the\par
king command?'\par
'Walk no more in the shadows, but awake!' said Aragorn. 'You are weary.\par
Rest a while, and take food, and be ready when I return.'\par
'I will, lord,' said Faramir. 'For who would lie idle when the king has\par
returned?'\par
'Farewell then for a while!' said Aragorn. 'I must go to others who need\par
me.' And he left the chamber with Gandalf and Imrahil; but Beregond and his\par
son remained behind, unable to contain their joy. As he followed Gandalf and\par
shut the door Pippin heard Ioreth exclaim:\par
'King! Did you hear that? What did I say? The hands of a healer, I\par
said.' And soon the word had gone out from the House that the king was indeed\par
come among them, and after war he brought healing; and the news ran through\par
the City.\par
But Aragorn came to \'c9owyn, and he said: 'Here there is a grievous hurt\par
and a heavy blow. The arm that was broken has been tended with due skill, and\par
it will mend in time, if she has the strength to live: It is the shield-arm\par
that is maimed; but the chief evil comes through the sword-arm. In that there\par
now seems no life, although it is unbroken.\par
'Alas! For she was pitted against a foe beyond the strength of her mind\par
or body. And those who will take a weapon to such an enemy must be sterner\par
than steel, if the very shock shall not destroy them. It was an evil doom that\par
set her in his path. For she is a fair maiden, fairest lady of a house of\par
queens. And yet I know not how I should speak of her. When I first looked on\par
her and perceived her unhappiness, it seemed to me that I saw a white flower\par
standing straight and proud, shapely as a lily, and yet knew that it was hard,\par
as if wrought by elf-wrights out of steel. Or was it, maybe, a frost that had\par
turned its sap to ice, and so it stood, bitter-sweet, still fair to see, but\par
stricken, soon to fall and die? Her malady begins far back before this day,\par
does it not, \'c9omer?'\par
'I marvel that you should ask me, lord,' he answered. 'For I hold you\par
blameless in this matter, as in all else; yet I knew not that \'c9owyn, my\par
sister, was touched by any frost, until she first looked on you. Care and\par
dread she had, and shared with me, in the days of Wormtongue and the king's\par
bewitchment; and she tended the king in growing fear. But that did not bring\par
her to this pass!'\par
'My friend,' said Gandalf, 'you had horses, and deeds of arms, and the\par
free fields; but she, born in the body of a maid, had a spirit and courage at\par
least the match of yours. Yet she was doomed to wait upon an old man, whom she\par
loved as a father, and watch him falling into a mean dishonoured dotage; and\par
her part seemed to her more ignoble than that of the staff he leaned on.\par
'Think you that Wormtongue had poison only for Th\'e9oden's ears? _Dotard!\par
What is the house of Eorl but a thatched barn where brigands drink in the\par
reek, and their brats roll on the floor among their dogs?_Have you not heard\par
those words before? Saruman spoke them, the teacher of Wormtongue. Though I do\par
not doubt that Wormtongue at home wrapped their meaning in terms more cunning.\par
My lord, if your sister's love for you, and her will still bent to her duty,\par
had not restrained her lips; you might have heard even such things as these\par
escape them. But who knows what she spoke to the darkness, alone, in the\par
bitter watches of the night, when all her life seemed shrinking, and the walls\par
of her bower closing in about her, a hutch to trammel some wild thing in?'\par
Then \'c9omer was silent, and looked on his sister, as if pondering anew all\par
the days of their past life together. But Aragorn said: 'I saw also what you\par
saw, \'c9omer. Few other griefs amid the ill chances of this world have more\par
bitterness and shame for a man's heart than to behold the love of a lady so\par
fair and brave that cannot be returned Sorrow and pity have followed me ever\par
since I left her desperate in Dunharrow and rode to the Paths of the Dead; and\par
no fear upon that way was so present as the fear for what might befall her.\par
And yet, \'c9omer, I say to you that she loves you more truly than me; for you\par
she loves and knows; but in me she loves only a shadow and a thought: a hope\par
of glory and great deeds, and lands far from the fields of Rohan.\par
'I have, maybe, the power to heal her body, and to recall her from the\par
dark valley. But to what she will awake: hope, or forgetfulness, or despair, I\par
do not know. And if to despair, then she will die, unless other healing comes\par
which I cannot bring. Alas! for her deeds have set her among the queens of\par
great renown.'\par
Then Aragorn stooped and looked in her face, and it was indeed white as a\par
lily, cold as frost, and hard as graven stone. But he bent and kissed her on\par
the brow, and called her softly, saying:\par
'\'c9owyn \'c9omund's daughter, awake! For your enemy has passed away!'\par
She did not stir, but now she began again to breathe deeply, so that her\par
breast rose and fell beneath the white linen of the sheet. Once more Aragorn\par
bruised two leaves of _athelas_ and cast them into steaming water; and he\par
laved her brow with it, and her right arm lying cold and nerveless on the\par
coverlet.\par
Then, whether Aragorn had indeed some forgotten power of Westernesse, or\par
whether it was but his words of the Lady \'c9owyn that wrought on them, as the\par
sweet influence of the herb stole about the chamber it seemed to those who\par
stood by that a keen wind blew through the window, and it bore no scent, but\par
was an air wholly fresh and clean and young, as if it had not before been\par
breathed by any living thing and came new-made from snowy mountains high\par
beneath a dome of stars, or from shores of silver far away washed by seas of\par
foam.\par
'Awake, \'c9owyn, Lady of Rohan!' said Aragorn again, and he took her right\par
hand in his and felt it warm with life returning. 'Awake! The shadow is gone\par
and all darkness is washed clean!' Then he laid her hand in \'c9omer's and\par
stepped away. 'Call her!' he said, and he passed silently from the chamber.\par
'\'c9owyn, \'c9owyn!' cried \'c9omer amid his tears. But she opened her eyes and\par
said: '\'c9omer! What joy is this? For they said that you were slain. Nay, but\par
that was only the dark voices in my dream. How long have I been dreaming?'\par
'Not long, my sister,' said \'c9omer. 'But think no more on it!'\par
' I am strangely weary,' she said. 'I must rest a little. But tell me,\par
what of the Lord of the Mark? Alas! Do not tell me that that was a dream for I\par
know that it was not. He is dead as he foresaw.'\par
'He is dead,' said \'c9omer, 'but he bade me say farewell to \'c9owyn dearer\par
than daughter. He lies now in great honour in the Citadel of Gondor.'\par
'That is grievous,' she said. 'And yet it is good beyond all that I dared\par
hope in the dark days, when it seemed that the House of Eorl was sunk in\par
honour less than any shepherd's cot. And what of the king's esquire, the\par
Halfling? \'c9omer, you shall make him a knight of the Riddermark, for he is\par
valiant!'\par
'He lies nearby in this House, and I will go to him,' said Gandalf.\par
'\'c9omer shall stay here for a while. But do not speak yet of war or woe, until\par
you are made whole again. Great gladness it is to see you wake again to health\par
and hope, so valiant a lady!'\par
'To health?' said \'c9owyn. 'It may be so. At least while there is an empty\par
saddle of some fallen Rider that I can fill, and there are deeds to do. But to\par
hope? I do not know.'\par
Gandalf and Pippin came to Merry's room, and there they found Aragorn\par
standing by the bed. 'Poor old Merry!' cried Pippin, and he ran to the\par
bedside, for it seemed to him that his friend looked worse, and a greyness was\par
in his face, as if a weight of years of sorrow lay on him; and suddenly a fear\par
seized Pippin that Merry would die.\par
'Do not be afraid,' said Aragorn. 'I came in time, and I have called him\par
back. He is weary now, and grieved, and he has taken a hurt like the Lady\par
\'c9owyn, daring to smite that deadly thing. But these evils can be amended, so\par
strong and gay a spirit is in him. His grief he will not forget; but it will\par
not darken his heart, it will teach him wisdom.'\par
Then Aragorn laid his hand on Merry's head, and passing his hand gently\par
through the brown curls, he touched the eyelids, and called him by name. And\par
when the fragrance of _athelas_ stole through the room, like the scent of\par
orchards, and of heather in the sunshine full of bees, suddenly Merry awoke,\par
and he said:\par
'I am hungry. What is the time?'\par
'Past supper-time now,' said Pippin; 'though I daresay I could bring you\par
something, if they will let me.'\par
'They will indeed,' said Gandalf. 'And anything else that this Rider of\par
Rohan may desire, if it can be found in Minas Tirith, where his name is in\par
honour.'\par
