pipe.' At that his face clouded. 'No, not a pipe. I don't think I'll smoke\par
again.'\par
'Why not?' said Pippin.\par
'Well,' answered Merry slowly. 'He is dead. It has brought it all back to\par
me. He said he was sorry he had never had a chance of talking herb-lore with\par
me. Almost the last thing he ever said. I shan't ever be able to smoke again\par
without thinking of him, and that day, Pippin, when he rode up to Isengard and\par
was so polite.'\par
'Smoke then, and think of him!' said Aragorn. 'For he was a gentle heart\par
and a great king and kept his oaths; and he rose out of the shadows to a last\par
fair morning. Though your service to him was brief, it should be a memory glad\par
and honourable to the end of your days.'\par
Merry smiled. 'Well then,' he said, 'if Strider will provide what is\par
needed, I will smoke and think. I had some of Saruman's best in my pack, but\par
what became of it in the battle, I am sure I don't know.'\par
'Master Meriadoc,' said Aragorn, 'if you think that I have passed through\par
the mountains and the realm of Gondor with fire and sword to bring herbs to a\par
careless soldier who throws away his gear, you are mistaken. If your pack has\par
not been found, then you must send for the herb-master of this House. And he\par
will tell you that he did not know that the herb you desire had any virtues,\par
but that it is called _westmansweed_ by the vulgar, and _galenas_ by the\par
noble, and other names in other tongues more learned, and after adding a few\par
half-forgotten rhymes that he does not understand, he will regretfully inform\par
you that there is none in the House, and he will leave you to reflect on the\par
history of tongues. And so now must I. For I have not slept in such a bed as\par
this, since I rode from Dunharrow, nor eaten since the dark before dawn.'\par
Merry seized his hand and kissed it. 'I am frightfully sorry,' he said.\par
'Go at once! Ever since that night at Bree we have been a nuisance to you. But\par
it is the way of my people to use light words at such times and say less than\par
they mean. We fear to say too much. It robs us of the right words when a jest\par
