scouts before them on the road, and others on foot upon either side,\par
especially on the eastward flank; for there lay dark thickets, and a tumbled\par
land of rocky ghylls and crags, behind which the long grim slopes of the Ephel\par
D\'faath clambered up. The weather of the world remained fair and the wind held\par
in the west, but nothing could waft away the glooms and the sad mists that\par
clung about the Mountains of Shadow; and behind them at whiles great smokes\par
would arise and hover in the upper winds.\par
Ever and anon Gandalf let blow the trumpets, and the heralds would cry:\par
"The Lords of Gondor are come! Let all leave this land or yield them up!' But\par
Imrahil said: 'Say not _The Lords of Gondor_. Say _The King Elessar_. For that\par
is true, even though he has not yet sat upon the throne; and it will give the\par
Enemy more thought, if the heralds use that name.' And thereafter thrice a day\par
the heralds proclaimed the coming of the King Elessar. But none answered the\par
