Nonetheless, though they marched in seeming peace, the hearts of all the\par
army, from the highest to the lowest, were downcast, and with every mile that\par
they went north foreboding of evil grew heavier on them. It was near the end\par
of the second day of their march from the Cross-roads that they first met any\par
offer of battle. For a strong force of Orcs and Easterlings attempted to take\par
their leading companies in an ambush; and that was in the very place where\par
Faramir had waylaid the men of Harad, and the road went in a deep cutting\par
through an out-thrust of the eastward hills. But the Captains of the West were\par
well warned by their scouts, skilled men from Henneth Ann\'fbn led by Mablung;\par
and so the ambush was itself trapped. For horsemen went wide about westward\par
and came up on the flank of the enemy and from behind, and they were destroyed\par
or driven east into the hills.\par
But the victory did little to enhearten the captains. 'It is but a\par
feint,' said Aragorn; 'and its chief purpose, I deem, was rather to draw us on\par
by a false guess of our Enemy's weakness than to do us much hurt, yet.' And\par
from that evening onward the Nazg\'fbl came and followed every move of the army.\par
They still flew high and out of sight of all save Legolas, and yet their\par
presence could be felt, as a deepening of shadow and a dimming of the sun; and\par
though the Ringwraiths did not yet stoop low upon their foes and were silent,\par
uttering no cry, the dread of them could not be shaken off.\par
So time and the hopeless journey wore away. Upon the fourth day from the\par
Cross-roads and the sixth from Minas Tirith they came at last to the end of\par
the living lands, and began to pass into the desolation that lay before the\par
gates of the Pass of Cirith Gorgor; and they could descry the marshes and the\par
desert that stretched north and west to the Emyn Muil. So desolate were those\par
places and so deep the horror that lay on them that some of the host were\par
unmanned, and they could neither walk nor ride further north.\par
Aragorn looked at them, and there was pity in his eyes rather than wrath;\par
for these were young men from Rohan, from Westfold far away, or husbandmen\par
from Lossarnach, and to them Mordor had been from childhood a name of evil,\par
and yet unreal, a legend that had no part in their simple life; and now they\par
walked like men in a hideous dream made true, and they understood not this war\par
nor why fate should lead them to such a pass.\par
'Go!' said Aragorn. 'But keep what honour you may, and do not run! And\par
there is a task which you may attempt and so be not wholly shamed. Take your\par
way south-west till you come to Cair Andros, and if that is still held by\par
enemies, as I think, then re-take it, if you can; and hold it to the last in\par
defence of Gondor and Rohan!'\par
Then some being shamed by his mercy overcame their fear and went on, and\par
the others took new hope, hearing of a manful deed within their measure that\par
they could turn to, and they departed. And so, since many men had already been\par
left at the Cross-roads, it was with less than six thousands that the Captains\par
of the West came at last to challenge the Black Gate and the might of Mordor.\par
They advanced now slowly, expecting at every hour some answer to their\par
challenge, and they drew together, since it was but waste of men to send out\par
scouts or small parties from the main host. At nightfall of the fifth day of\par
the march from Morgul Vale they made their last camp, and set fires about it\par
