The two vast iron doors of the Black Gate under its frowning arch were\par
fast closed. Upon the battlement nothing could be seen. All was silent but\par
watchful. They were come to the last end of their folly, and stood forlorn and\par
chill in the grey light of early day before towers and walls which their army\par
could not assault with hope, not even if it had brought thither engines of\par
great power, and the Enemy had no more force than would suffice for the\par
manning of the gate and wall alone. Yet they knew that all the hills and rocks\par
about the Morannon were filled with hidden foes, and the shadowy defile beyond\par
was bored and tunnelled by teeming broods of evil things. And as they stood\par
they saw all the Nazg\'fbl gathered together, hovering above the Towers of the\par
Teeth like vultures; and they knew that they were watched. But still the Enemy\par
made no sign.\par
No choice was left them but to play their part to its end. Therefore\par
Aragorn now set the host in such array as could best be contrived; and they\par
were drawn up on two great hills of blasted stone and earth that orcs had\par
