once, harsh, brutal, cold. It was Shagrat speaking, Captain of the Tower.\par
`You won't go again, you say? Curse you, Snaga, you little maggot! If you\par
think I'm so damaged that it's safe to flout me, you're mistaken Come here,\par
and I'll squeeze your eyes out, like I did to Radbug just now. And when some\par
new lads come, I'll deal with you: I'll send you to Shelob.'\par
`They won't come, not before you're dead anyway,' answered Snaga surlily.\par
'I've told you twice that Gorbag's swine got to the gate first, and none of\par
ours got out. Lagduf and Muzgash ran through, but they were shot. I saw it\par
from a window, I tell you. And they were the last.'\par
'Then you must go. I must stay here anyway. But I'm hurt. The Black Pits\par
take that filthy rebel Gorbag!' Shagrat's voice trailed off into a string of\par
foul names and curses. `I gave him better than I got, but he knifed me, the\par
dung, before I throttled him. You must go, or I'll eat you. News must get\par
through to Lugb\'farz, or we'll both be for the Black Pits. Yes, you too. You\par
won't escape by skulking here.'\par
`I'm not going down those stairs again,' growled Snaga, `be you captain\par
or no. Nar! Keep your hands off your knife, or I'll put an arrow in your guts.\par
You won't be a captain long when They hear about all these goings-on. I've\par
fought for the Tower against those stinking Morgul-rats, but a nice mess you\par
two precious captains have made of things, fighting over the swag.'\par
'That's enough from you,' snarled Shagrat. `I had my orders. It was\par
Gorbag started it, trying to pinch that pretty shirt.'\par
`Well, you put his back up, being so high and mighty. And he had more\par
sense than you anyway. He told you more than once that the most dangerous of\par
these spies was still loose, and you wouldn't listen. And you won't listen\par
now. Gorbag was right, I tell you. There's a great fighter about, one of those\par
bloody-handed Elves, or one of the filthy _tarks_.*1 He's coming here, I tell\par
you. You heard the bell. He's got past the Watchers, and that's _tark's_ work.\par
He's on the stairs. And until he's off them, I'm not going down. Not if you\par
were a Nazg\'fbl, I wouldn't.'\par
`So that's it, is it?' yelled Shagrat. 'You'll do this, and you'll not do\par
that? And when he does come, you'll bolt and leave me? No, you won't! I'll put\par
red maggot-holes in your belly first.'\par
Out of the turret-door the smaller orc came flying. Behind him came\par
Shagrat, a large orc with long arms that, as he ran crouching, reached to the\par
ground. But one arm hung limp and seemed to be bleeding; the other hugged a\par
large black bundle. In the red glare Sam, cowering behind the stair-door,\par
caught a glimpse of his evil face as it passed: it was scored as if by rending\par
claws and smeared with blood; slaver dripped from its protruding fangs; the\par
mouth snarled like an animal.\par
As far as Sam could see, Shagrat hunted Snaga round the roof, until\par
ducking and eluding him the smaller orc with a yelp darted back into the\par
turret and disappeared. Then Shagrat halted. Out of the eastward door Sam\par
could see him now by the parapet, panting, his left claw clenching and\par
unclenching feebly. He put the bundle on the floor and with his right claw\par
drew out a long red knife and spat on it. Going to the parapet he leaned over,\par
looking down into the outer court far below. Twice he shouted but no answer\par
came.\par
Suddenly, as Shagrat was stooped over the battlement, his back to the\par
roof-top, Sam to his amazement saw that one of the sprawling bodies was\par
moving. It was crawling. It put out a claw and clutched the bundle. It\par
staggered up. In its other hand it held a broad-headed spear with a short\par
broken haft. It was poised for a stabbing thrust. But at that very moment a\par
hiss escaped its teeth, a gasp of pain or hate. Quick as a snake Shagrat\par
slipped aside, twisted round, and drove his knife into his enemy's throat.\par
`Got you, Gorbag!' he cried. 'Not quite dead, eh? Well, I'll finish my\par
job now.' He sprang on to the fallen body, and stamped and trampled it in his\par
fury, stooping now and again to stab and slash it with his knife. Satisfied at\par
last, he threw back his head and let out a horrible gurgling yell of triumph.\par
Then he licked his knife, and put it between his teeth, and catching up the\par
bundle he came loping towards the near door of the stairs.\par
Sam had no time to think. He might have slipped out of the other door,\par
but hardly without being seen; and he could not have played hide-and-seek with\par
this hideous orc for long. He did what was probably the best thing he could\par
have done. He sprang out to meet Shagrat with a shout. He was no longer\par
holding the Ring, but it was there, a hidden power, a cowing menace to the\par
slaves of Mordor; and in his hand was Sting, and its light smote the eyes of\par
the orc like the glitter of cruel stars in the terrible elf-countries, the\par
dream of which was a cold fear to all his kind. And Shagrat could not both\par
fight and keep hold of his treasure. He stopped, growling, baring his fangs.\par
Then once more, orc-fashion, he leapt aside, and as Sam sprang at him, using\par
the heavy bundle as both shield and weapon, he thrust it hard into his enemy's\par
face. Sam staggered, and before he could recover, Shagrat darted past and down\par
the stairs.\par
Sam ran after him, cursing, but he did not go far. Soon the thought of\par
Frodo returned to him, and he remembered that the other orc had gone back into\par
the turret. Here was another dreadful choice, and he had no time to ponder it.\par
If Shagrat got away, he would soon get help and come back. But if Sam pursued\par
him, the other orc might do some horrible deed up there. And anyway Sam might\par
miss Shagrat or be killed by him. He turned quickly and ran back up the\par
stairs. `Wrong again, I expect,' he sighed. `But it's my job to go right up to\par
the top first, whatever happens afterwards.'\par
Away below Shagrat went leaping down the stairs and out over the court\par
and through the gate, bearing his precious burden. If Sam could have seen him\par
and known the grief that his escape would bring, he might have quailed. But\par
now his mind was set on the last stage of his search. He came cautiously to\par
the turret-door and stepped inside. It opened into darkness. But soon his\par
staring eyes were aware of a dim light at his right hand. It came from an\par
opening that led to another stairway, dark and narrow: it appeared to go\par
winding up the turret along the inside of its round outer wall. A torch was\par
glimmering from somewhere up above.\par
Softly Sam began to climb. He came to the guttering torch, fixed above a\par
door on his left that faced a window-slit looking out westward: one of the red\par
eyes that he and Frodo had seen from down below by the tunnel's mouth. Quickly\par
Sam passed the door and hurried on to the second storey, dreading at any\par
moment to he attacked and to feel throttling fingers seize his throat from\par
behind. He came next to a window looking east and another torch above the door\par
to a passage through the middle of the turret. The door was open, the passage\par
dark save for the glimmer of the torch and the red glare from outside\par
filtering through the window-slit. But here the stair stopped and climbed no\par
further. Sam crept into the passage. On either side there was a low door; both\par
were closed and locked. There was no sound at all.\par
`A dead end,' muttered Sam; `and after all my climb! This can't be the\par
top of the tower. But what can I do now?'\par
He ran back to the lower storey and tried the door. It would not move. He\par
ran up again, and sweat began to trickle down his face. He felt that even\par
minutes were precious, but one by one they escaped; and he could do nothing.\par
He cared no longer for Shagrat or Snaga or any other orc that was ever\par
spawned. He longed only for his master, for one sight of his face or one touch\par
of his hand.\par
At last, weary and feeling finally defeated, he sat on a step below the\par
level of the passage-floor and bowed his head into his hands. It was quiet,\par
horribly quiet. The torch, that was already burning low when he arrived,\par
sputtered and went out; and he felt the darkness cover him like a tide. And\par
then softly, to his own surprise, there at the vain end of his long journey\par
and his grief, moved by what thought in his heart he could not tell, Sam began\par
to sing.\par
His voice sounded thin and quavering in the cold dark tower: the voice of\par
a forlorn and weary hobbit that no listening orc could possibly mistake for\par
the clear song of an Elven-lord. He murmured old childish tunes out of the\par
Shire, and snatches of Mr. Bilbo's rhymes that came into his mind like\par
fleeting glimpses of the country of his home. And then suddenly new strength\par
rose in him, and his voice rang out, while words of his own came unbidden to\par
fit the simple tune.\par
_In western lands beneath the Sun\par
the flowers may rise in Spring,\par
the trees may bud, the waters run,\par
the merry finches sing.\par
Or there maybe 'tis cloudless night\par
and swaying beeches bear\par
the Elven-stars as jewels white\par
amid their branching hair.\par
Though here at journey's end I lie\par
in darkness buried deep,\par
beyond all towers strong and high,\par
beyond all mountains steep,\par
above all shadows rides the Sun\par
and Stars for ever dwell:\par
I will not say the Day is done,\par
nor bid the Stars farewell._\par
`Beyond all towers strong and high,' he began again, and then he stopped\par
short. He thought that he had heard a faint voice answering him. But now he\par
could hear nothing. Yes, he could hear something, but not a voice. Footsteps\par
were approaching. Now a door was being opened quietly in the passage above;\par
the hinges creaked. Sam crouched down listening. The door closed with a dull\par
thud; and then a snarling orc-voice rang out.\par
'Ho la! You up there, you dunghill rat! Stop your squeaking, or I'll come\par
and deal with you. D'you hear?'\par
There was no answer.\par
'All right,' growled Snaga. `But I'll come and have a look at you all the\par
same, and see what you're up to.'\par
The hinges creaked again, and Sam, now peering over the corner of the\par
passage-threshold, saw a flicker of light in an open doorway, and the dim\par
shape of an orc coming out. He seemed to be carrying a ladder. Suddenly the\par
answer dawned on Sam: the topmost chamber was reached by a trap-door in the\par
roof of the passage. Snaga thrust the ladder upwards, steadied it, and then\par
clambered out of sight. Sam heard a bolt drawn back. Then he heard the hideous\par
voice speaking again.\par
`You lie quiet, or you'll pay for it! You've not got long to live in\par
peace, I guess; but if you don't want the fun to begin right now, keep your\par
trap shut, see? There's a reminder for you!' There was a sound like the crack\par
of a whip.\par
At that rage blazed in Sam's heart to a sudden fury. He sprang up, ran,\par
and went up the ladder like a cat. His head came out in the middle of the\par
floor of a large round chamber. A red lamp hung from its roof; the westward\par
window-slit was high and dark. Something was lying on the floor by the wall\par
under the window, but over it a black orc-shape was straddled. It raised a\par
whip a second time, but the blow never fell.\par
With a cry Sam leapt across the floor, Sting in hand. The orc wheeled\par
round, but before it could make a move Sam slashed its whip-hand from its arm.\par
Howling with pain and fear but desperate the orc charged head-down at him.\par
Sam's next blow went wide, and thrown off his balance he fell backwards,\par
clutching at the orc as it stumbled over him. Before he could scramble up he\par
heard a cry and a thud. The orc in its wild haste had tripped on the ladderhead\par
and fallen through the open trap-door. Sam gave no more thought to it. He\par
ran to the figure huddled on the floor. It was Frodo.\par
He was naked, lying as if in a swoon on a heap of filthy rags: his arm\par
was flung up, shielding his head, and across his side there ran an ugly whipweal.\par
`Frodo! Mr. Frodo, my dear!' cried Sam, tears almost blinding him. `It's\par
Sam, I've come!' He half lifted his master and hugged him to his breast. Frodo\par
opened his eyes.\par
`Am I still dreaming?' he muttered. `But the other dreams were horrible.'\par
`You're not dreaming at all, Master,' said Sam. `It's real. It's me. I've\par
come.'\par
`I can hardly believe it,' said Frodo, clutching him. `There was an orc\par
with a whip, and then it turns into Sam! Then I wasn't dreaming after all when\par
I heard that singing down below, and I tried to answer? Was it you?'\par
'It was indeed, Mr. Frodo. I'd given up hope, almost. I couldn't find\par
you.\par
Well, you have now, Sam, dear Sam, said Frodo, and he la back in Sam's\par
gentle arms, closing his eyes, like a child at rest when night-fears are\par
driven away by some loved voice or hand.\par
Sam felt that he could sit like that in endless happiness; but it was not\par
allowed. It was not enough for him to find his master, he had still to try and\par
save him. He kissed Frodo's forehead. `Come! Wake up Mr. Frodo!' he said,\par
trying to sound as cheerful as he had when he drew back the curtains at Bag\par
End on a summer's morning.\par
Frodo sighed and sat up. `Where are we? How did I get here?' he asked.\par
'There's no time for tales till we get somewhere else, Mr. Frodo,' said\par
Sam. `But you're in the top of that tower you and me saw from away down by the\par
tunnel before the orcs got you. How long ago that was I don't know. More than\par
a day, I guess.'\par
`Only that?' said Frodo. `It seems weeks. You must tell me all about it,\par
if we get a chance. Something hit me, didn't it? And I fell into darkness and\par
foul dreams, and woke and found that waking was worse. Orcs were all round me.\par
I think they had just been pouring some horrible burning drink down my throat.\par
My head grew clear, but I was aching and weary. They stripped me of\par
everything; and then two great brutes came and questioned me, questioned me\par
until I thought I should go mad, standing over me, gloating, fingering their\par
knives. I'll never forget their claws and eyes.'\par
`You won't, if you talk about them, Mr. Frodo,' said Sam. 'And if we\par
don't want to see them again, the sooner we get going the better. Can you\par
walk?'\par
`Yes, I can walk,' said Frodo, getting up slowly. 'I am not hurt Sam.\par
Only I feel very tired, and I've a pain here.' He put his hand to the back of\par
his neck above his left shoulder. He stood up, and it looked to Sam as if he\par
was clothed in flame: his naked skin was scarlet in the light of the lamp\par
above. Twice he paced across the floor.\par
`That's better!' he said, his spirits rising a little. `I didn't dare to\par
move when I was left alone, or one of the guards came. Until the yelling and\par
fighting began. The two big brutes: they quarrelled, I think. Over me and my\par
things. I lay here terrified. And then all went deadly quiet, and that was\par
worse.'\par
`Yes, they quarrelled, seemingly,' said Sam. There must have been a\par
couple of hundred of the dirty creatures in this place. A bit of a tall order\par
for Sam Gamgee, as you might say. But they've done all the killing of\par
themselves. That's lucky, but it's too long to make a song about, till we're\par
out of here. Now what's to be done? You can't go walking in the Black Land in\par
naught but your skin, Mr. Frodo.'\par
`They've taken everything, Sam,' said Frodo. `Everything I had. Do you\par
understand? _Everything!_' He cowered on the floor again with bowed head, as\par
his own words brought home to him the fullness of the disaster, and despair\par
overwhelmed him. 'The quest has failed Sam. Even if we get out of here, we\par
can't escape. Only Elves can escape. Away, away out of Middle-earth, far away\par
over the Sea. If even that is wide enough to keep the Shadow out.'\par
`No, _not_ everything, Mr. Frodo. And it hasn't failed, not yet. I took\par
it, Mr. Frodo, begging your pardon. And I've kept it safe. It's round my neck\par
now, and a terrible burden it is, too.' Sam fumbled for the Ring and its\par
chain. `But I suppose you must take it back.' Now it had come to it, Sam felt\par
reluctant to give up the Ring and burden his master with it again.\par
`You've got it?' gasped Frodo. `You've got it here? Sam, you're a\par
marvel!' Then quickly and strangely his tone changed. `Give it to me!' he\par
cried, standing up, holding out a trembling hand. `Give it me at once! You\par
can't have it!'\par
'All right, Mr. Frodo,' said Sam, rather startled. 'Here it is!' Slowly\par
he drew the Ring out and passed the chain over his head. `But you're in the\par
land of Mordor now, sir; and when you get out, you'll see the Fiery Mountain\par
and all. You'll find the Ring very dangerous now, and very hard to bear. If\par
it's too hard a job, I could share it with you, maybe?'\par
`No, no!' cried Frodo, snatching the Ring and chain from Sam's hands. `No\par
you won't, you thief!' He panted, staring at Sam with eyes wide with fear and\par
enmity. Then suddenly, clasping the Ring in one clenched fist, he stood\par
aghast. A mist seemed to clear from his eyes, and he passed a hand over his\par
aching brow. The hideous vision had seemed so real to him, half bemused as he\par
was still with wound and fear. Sam had changed before his very eyes into an\par
orc again, leering and pawing at his treasure, a foul little creature with\par
greedy eyes and slobbering mouth. But now the vision had passed. There was Sam\par
kneeling before him, his face wrung with pain, as if he had been stabbed in\par
the heart; tears welled from his eyes.\par
'O Sam!' cried Frodo. `What have I said? What have I done? Forgive me!\par
After all you have done. It is the horrible power of the Ring. I wish it had\par
never, never, been found. But don't mind me, Sam. I must carry the burden to\par
the end. It can't be altered. You can't come between me and this doom.'\par
'That's all right, Mr. Frodo,' said Sam, rubbing his sleeve across his\par
eyes. `I understand. But I can still help, can't I? I've got to get you out of\par
here. At once, see! But first you want some clothes and gear and then some\par
food. The clothes will be the easiest part. As we're in Mordor, we'd, best\par
dress up Mordor-fashion; and anyway there isn't no choice. It'll have to be\par
orc-stuff for you, Mr. Frodo, I'm afraid. And for me too. If we go together,\par
we'd best match. Now put this round you!'\par
Sam unclasped his grey cloak and cast it about Frodo's shoulders. Then\par
unslinging his pack he laid it on the floor. He drew Sting from its sheath.\par
Hardly a flicker was to be seen upon its blade. `I was forgetting this, Mr.\par
Frodo,' he said. `No, they didn't get everything! You lent me Sting, if you\par
remember, and the Lady's glass. I've got them both still. But lend them to me\par
a little longer, Mr. Frodo. I must go and see what I can find. You stay here.\par
Walk about a bit and ease your legs. I shan't be long. I shan't have to go\par
far.'\par
`Take care, Sam!' said Frodo. `And be quick! There may be orcs still\par
alive, lurking in wait.'\par
'I've got to chance it,' said Sam. He stepped to the trap-door and\par
slipped down the ladder. In a minute his head reappeared. He threw a long\par
knife on the floor.\par
`There's something that might be useful,' he said. 'He's dead: the one\par
that whipped you. Broke his neck, it seems, in his hurry. Now you draw up the\par
ladder, if you can, Mr. Frodo; and don't you let it down till you hear me call\par
the password. _Elbereth_ I'll call. What the Elves say. No orc would say\par
that.'\par
Frodo sat for a while and shivered, dreadful fears chasing one another\par
through his mind. Then he got up, drew the grey elven-cloak about him, and to\par
keep his mind occupied, began to walk to and fro, prying and peering into\par
every corner of his prison.\par
It was not very long, though fear made it seem an hour at least, before\par
he heard Sam's voice calling softly from below: _Elbereth, Elbereth_. Frodo\par
let down the light ladder. Up came Sam, puffing, heaving a great bundle on his\par
head. He let it fall with a thud.\par
`Quick now. Mr. Frodo!' he said. `I've had a bit of a search to find\par
anything small enough for the likes of us. We'll have to make do. But we must\par
hurry. I've met nothing alive, and I've seen nothing but I'm not easy. I think\par
this place is being watched. I can't explain it, but well: it feels to me as\par
if one of those foul flying Riders was about, up in the blackness where he\par
can't be seen.'\par
He opened the bundle. Frodo looked in disgust at the contents, but there\par
was nothing for it: he had to put the things on, or go naked. There were long\par
hairy breeches of some unclean beast-fell, and a tunic of dirty leather. He\par
drew them on. Over the tunic went a coat of stout ring-mail, short for a fullsized\par
orc, too long for Frodo and heavy. About it he clasped a belt, at which\par
there hung a short sheath holding a broad-bladed stabbing-sword. Sam had\par
brought several orc-helmets. One of them fitted Frodo well enough, a black cap\par
with iron rim, and iron hoops covered with leather upon which the evil Eye was\par
painted in red above the beaklike nose-guard.\par
`The Morgul-stuff, Gorbag's gear, was a better fit and better made,' said\par
Sam; `but it wouldn't do, I guess, to go carrying his tokens into Mordor, not\par
after this business here. Well, there you are, Mr. Frodo. A perfect little\par
orc, if I may make so bold-at least you would be, if we could cover your face\par
with a mask, give you longer arms, and make you bow-legged. This will hide\par
some of the tell-tales.' He put a large black cloak round Frodo's shoulders.\par
`Now you're ready! You can pick up a shield as we go.'\par
'What about you, Sam?' said Frodo. `Aren't we going to match?'\par
`Well, Mr. Frodo, I've been thinking,' said Sam. 'I'd best not leave any\par
of my stuff behind, and we can't destroy it. And I can't wear orc-mail over\par
all my clothes, can I? I'll just have to cover up.'\par
He knelt down and carefully folded his elven-cloak. It went into a\par
surprisingly small roll. This he put into his pack that lay on the floor.\par
Standing up, he slung it behind his back, put an orc-helm on his head, and\par
cast another black cloak about his shoulders. `There!' he said. `Now we match,\par
near enough. And now we must be off!'\par
'I can't go all the way at a run, Sam,' said Frodo with a wry smile. 'I\par
hope you've made inquiries about inns along the road? Or have you forgotten\par
about food and drink?'\par
`Save me, but so I had!' said Sam. He whistled in dismay. 'Bless me, Mr.\par
Frodo, but you've gone and made me that hungry and thirsty! I don't know when\par
drop or morsel last passed my lips. I'd forgotten it, trying to find you. But\par
let me think! Last time I looked I'd got about enough of that waybread, and of\par
what Captain Faramir gave us, to keep me on my legs for a couple of weeks at a\par
pinch. But if there's a drop left in my bottle, there's no more. That's not\par
going to be enough for two, nohow. Don't ores eat, and don't they drink? Or do\par
they just live on foul air and poison?'\par
`No, they eat and drink, Sam. The Shadow that bred them can only mock, it\par
cannot make: not real new things of its own. I don't think it gave life to the\par
ores, it only ruined them and twisted them; and if they are to live at all,\par
they have to live like other living creatures. Foul waters and foul meats\par
they'll take, if they can get no better, but not poison. They've fed me, and\par
so I'm better off than you. There must be food and water somewhere in this\par
place.' `But there's no time to look for them,' said Sam.\par
`Well, things are a bit better than you think,' said Frodo. 'I have had a\par
bit of luck while you were away. Indeed they did not take everything. I've\par
found my food-bag among some rags on the floor. They've rummaged it, of\par
course. But I guess they disliked the very look and smell of the _lembas_,\par
worse than Gollum did. It's scattered about and some of it is trampled and\par
broken, but I've gathered it together. It's not far short of what you've got.\par
But they've taken Faramir's food, and they've slashed up my water-bottle.'\par
`Well, there's no more to be said,' said Sam. `We've got enough to start\par
on. But the water's going to be a bad business. But come Mr. Frodo! Off we go,\par
or a whole lake of it won't do us any good!'\par
'Not till you've had a mouthful, Sam,' said Frodo. `I won't budge. Here,\par
take this elven-cake, and drink that last drop in your bottle! The whole thing\par
is quite hopeless, so it's no good worrying about tomorrow. It probably won't\par
come.'\par
At last they started. Down the ladder they climbed, and then Sam took it\par
and laid it in the passage beside the huddled body of the fallen orc. The\par
stair was dark, but on the roof-top the glare of the Mountain could still be\par
seen, though it was dying down now to a sullen red. They picked up two shields\par
to complete their disguise and then went on.\par
Down the great stairway they plodded. The high chamber of the turret\par
behind, where they had met again, seemed almost homely: they were out in the\par
open again now, and terror ran along the walls. All might be dead in the Tower\par
of Cirith Ungol, but it was steeped in fear and evil still.\par
At length they came to the door upon the outer court, and they halted.\par
Even from where they stood they felt the malice of the Watchers beating on\par
them, black silent shapes on either side of the gate through which the glare\par
of Mordor dimly showed. As they threaded their way among the hideous bodies of\par
the ores each step became more difficult. Before they even reached the archway\par
they were brought to a stand. To move an inch further was a pain and weariness\par
to will and limb.\par
Frodo had no strength for such a battle. He sank to the ground. `I can't\par
go on, Sam,' he murmured. `I'm going to faint. I don't know what's come over\par
me.'\par
`I do, Mr. Frodo. Hold up now! It's the gate. There's some devilry there.\par
But I got through, and I'm going to get out. It can't be more dangerous than\par
before. Now for it!'\par
Sam drew out the elven-glass of Galadriel again. As if to do honour to\par
his hardihood, and to grace with splendour his faithful brown hobbit-hand that\par
had done such deeds, the phial blazed forth suddenly, so that all the shadowy\par
court was lit with a dazzling radiance like lightning; but it remained steady\par
and did not pass.\par
'_Gilthoniel, A Elbereth!_' Sam cried. For, why he did not know, his\par
thought sprang back suddenly to the Elves in the Shire, and the song that\par
drove away the Black Rider in the trees.\par
