left, so sharp and narrow that it looked as if the black cliff had been cloven\par
by some huge axe, water came dripping down: the last remains, maybe, of some\par
sweet rain gathered from sunlit seas, but ill-fated to fall at last upon the\par
walls of the Black Land and wander fruitless down into the dust. Here it came\par
out of the rock in a little falling streamlet, and flowed across the path, and\par
turning south ran away swiftly to be lost among the dead stones.\par
Sam sprang towards it. 'If ever I see the Lady again, I will tell her!'\par
he cried. 'Light and now water!' Then he stopped. 'Let me drink first Mr.\par
Frodo,' he said.\par
'All right, but there's room enough for two.'\par
'I didn't mean that,' said Sam. 'I mean: if it's poisonous, or something\par
that will show its badness quick, well, better me than you, master, if you\par
understand me.'\par
'I do. But I think we'll trust our luck together, Sam; or our blessing.\par
Still, be careful now, if it's very cold!'\par
The water was cool but not icy, and it had an unpleasant taste, at once\par
bitter and oily, or so they would have said at home. Here it seemed beyond all\par
praise, and beyond fear or prudence. They drank their fill, and Sam\par
replenished his water-bottle. After that Frodo felt easier, and they went on\par
for several miles, until the broadening of the road and the beginnings of a\par
rough wall along its edge warned them that they were drawing near to another\par
orc-hold.\par
'This is where we turn aside, Sam,' said Frodo. 'And we must turn east.'\par
He sighed as he looked at the gloomy ridges across the valley. 'I have just\par
about enough strength left to find some hole away up there. And then I must\par
rest a little.'\par
The river-bed was now some way below the path. They scrambled down to it,\par
and began to cross it. To their surprise they came upon dark pools fed by\par
threads of water trickling down from some source higher up the valley. Upon\par
its outer marges under the westward mountains Mordor was a dying land, but it\par
was not yet dead. And here things still grew, harsh, twisted, bitter,\par
struggling for life. In the glens of the Morgai on the other side of the\par
valley low scrubby trees lurked and clung, coarse grey grass-tussocks fought\par
with the stones, and withered mosses crawled on them; and everywhere great\par
writhing, tangled brambles sprawled. Some had long stabbing thorns, some\par
hooked barbs that rent like knives. The sullen shrivelled leaves of a past\par
year hung on them, grating and rattling in the sad airs, but their maggotridden\par
