ravine, but they still had a long way to go before they could even come in\par
sight of the last craggy ridge. 'I must rest now, Sam, and sleep if I can.'\par
said Frodo. He looked about, but there seemed nowhere even for an animal to\par
crawl into in this dismal country. At length, tired out, they slunk under a\par
curtain of brambles that hung down like a mat over a low rock-face.\par
There they sat and made such a meal as they could. Keeping back the\par
precious _lembas_ for the evil days ahead, they ate the half of what remained\par
in Sam's bag of Faramir's provision: some dried fruit, and a small slip of\par
cured meat; and they sipped some water. They had drunk again from the pools in\par
the valley, but they were very, thirsty again. There was a bitter tang in the\par
air of Mordor that dried the mouth. When Sam thought of water even his hopeful\par
spirit quailed. Beyond the Morgai there was the dreadful plain of Gorgoroth to\par
cross.\par
'Now you go to sleep first, Mr. Frodo,' he said. 'It's getting dark\par
again. I reckon this day is nearly over.'\par
Frodo sighed and was asleep almost before the words were spoken. Sam\par
struggled with his own weariness, and he took Frodo's hand; and there he sat\par
silent till deep night fell. Then at last, to keep himself awake, he crawled\par
from the hiding-place and looked out. The land seemed full of creaking and\par
cracking and sly noises, but there was no sound of voice or of foot. Far above\par
the Ephel D\'faath in the West the night-sky was still dim and pale. There,\par
peeping among the cloud-wrack above a dark tor high up in the mountains, Sam\par
saw a white star twinkle for a while. The beauty of it smote his heart, as he\par
looked up out of the forsaken land, and hope returned to him. For like a\par
shaft, clear and cold, the thought pierced him that in the end the Shadow was\par
only a small and passing thing: there was light and high beauty for ever\par
beyond its reach. His song in the Tower had been defiance rather than hope;\par
for then he was thinking of himself. Now, for a moment, his own fate, and even\par
his masters, ceased to trouble him. He crawled back into the brambles and laid\par
himself by Frodo's side, and putting away all fear he cast himself into a deep\par
untroubled sleep.\par
They woke together, hand in hand. Sam was almost fresh, ready for another\par
day; but Frodo sighed. His sleep had been uneasy, full of dreams of fire, and\par
waking brought him no comfort. Still his sleep had not been without all\par
healing virtue: he was stronger, more able to bear his burden one stage\par
further. They did not know the time, nor how long they had slept; but after a\par
morsel of food and a sip of water they went on up the ravine, until it ended\par
in a sharp slope of screes and sliding stones. There the last living things\par
gave up their struggle; the tops of the Morgai were grassless, bare, jagged,\par
barren as a slate.\par
After much wandering and search they found a way that they could climb,\par
and with a last hundred feet of clawing scramble they were up. They came to a\par
cleft between two dark crags, and passing through found themselves on the very\par
edge of the last fence of Mordor. Below them, at the bottom of a fall of some\par
fifteen hundred feet, lay the inner plain stretching away into a formless\par
gloom beyond their sight. The wind of the world blew now from the West, and\par
the great clouds were lifted high, floating away eastward; but still only a\par
grey light came to the dreary fields of Gorgoroth. There smokes trailed on the\par
ground and lurked in hollows, and fumes leaked from fissures in the earth.\par
Still far away, forty miles at least, they saw Mount Doom, its feet\par
founded in ashen ruin, its huge cone rising to a great height, where its\par
reeking head was swathed in cloud. Its fires were now dimmed, and it stood in\par
smouldering slumber, as threatening and dangerous as a sleeping beast. Behind\par
it there hung a vast shadow, ominous as a thunder-cloud, the veils of Baradd\'fbr\par
that was reared far way upon a long spur of the Ashen Mountains thrust\par
down from the North. The Dark Power was deep in thought, and the Eye turned\par
inward, pondering tidings of doubt and danger: a bright sword, and a stern and\par
