For a while the hobbits sat in silence. At length Sam stirred. 'Well I\par
call that neat as neat,' he said. 'If this nice friendliness would spread\par
about in Mordor, half our trouble would be over.'\par
'Quietly, Sam,' Frodo whispered. 'There may be others about. We have\par
evidently had a very narrow escape, and the hunt was hotter on our tracks than\par
we guessed. But that is the spirit of Mordor, Sam; and it has spread to every\par
corner of it. Orcs have always behaved like that, or so all tales say, when\par
they are on their own. But you can't get much hope out of it. They hate us far\par
more, altogether and all the time. If those two had seen us, they would have\par
dropped all their quarrel until we were dead.'\par
There was another long silence. Sam broke it again, but with a whisper\par
this time. 'Did you hear what they said about _that gobbler_, Mr. Frodo? I\par
told you Gollum wasn't dead yet, didn't I?'\par
'Yes, I remember. And I wondered how you knew,' said Frodo. 'Well come\par
now! I think we had better not move out from here again, until it has gone\par
quite dark. So you shall tell me how you know, and all about what happened. If\par
you can do it quietly.'\par
'I'll try,' said Sam, 'but when I think of that Stinker I get so hot I\par
could shout.'\par
There the hobbits sat under the cover of the thorny bush, while the drear\par
light of Mordor faded slowly into a deep and starless night; and Sam spoke\par
into Frodo's ear all that he could find words for of Gollum's treacherous\par
attack, the horror of Shelob, and his own adventures with the orcs. When he\par
had finished, Frodo said nothing but took Sam's hand and pressed it. At length\par
he stirred.\par
'Well, I suppose we must be going on again,' he said. 'I wonder how long\par
it will be before we really are caught and all the toiling and the slinking\par
will be over, and in vain.' He stood up. 'It's dark, and we cannot use the\par
Lady's glass. Keep it safe for me, Sam. I have nowhere to keep it now, except\par
in my hand, and I shall need both hands in the blind night. But Sting I give\par
to you. I have got an orc-blade, but I do not think it will be my part to\par
strike any blow again.'\par
It was difficult and dangerous moving in the night in the pathless land;\par
but slowly and with much stumbling the two hobbits toiled on hour by hour\par
northward along the eastern edge of the stony valley. When a grey light crept\par
back over the western heights, long after day had opened in the lands beyond,\par
they went into hiding again and slept a little, turn by turn. In his times of\par
waking Sam was busy with thoughts of food. At last when Frodo roused himself\par
and spoke of eating and making ready for yet another effort, he asked the\par
question that was troubling him most.\par
'Begging your pardon, Mr. Frodo,' he said, 'but have you any notion how\par
far there is still to go?'\par
'No, not any clear notion, Sam,' Frodo answered. 'In Rivendell before I\par
set out I was shown a map of Mordor that was made before the Enemy came back\par
here; but I only remember it vaguely. I remember clearest that there was a\par
place in the north where the western range and the northern range send out\par
spurs that nearly meet. That must be twenty leagues at least from the bridge\par
back by the Tower. It might be a good point at which to cross. But of course,\par
if we get there, we shall be further than we were from the Mountain, sixty\par
miles from it, I should think. I guess that we have gone about twelve leagues\par
north from the bridge now. Even if all goes well, I could hardly reach the\par
Mountain in a week. I am afraid, Sam, that the burden will get very heavy, and\par
I shall go still slower as we get nearer.'\par
Sam sighed. 'That's just as I feared,' he said. 'Well, to say nothing of\par
water, we've got to eat less, Mr. Frodo, or else move a bit quicker, at any\par
rate while we're still in this valley. One more bite and all the food's ended,\par
save the Elves' waybread.'\par
'I'll try and be a bit quicker, Sam,' said Frodo, drawing a deep breath.\par
'Come on then! Let's start another march!'\par
It was not yet quite dark again. They plodded along, on into the night.\par
The hours passed in a weary stumbling trudge with a few brief halts. At the\par
first hint of grey light under the skirts of the canopy of shadow they hid\par
themselves again in a dark hollow under an overhanging stone.\par
Slowly the light grew, until it was clearer than it yet had been. A\par
strong wind from the West was now driving the fumes of Mordor from the upper\par
airs. Before long the hobbits could make out the shape of the land for some\par
miles about them. The trough between the mountains and the Morgai had steadily\par
dwindled as it climbed upwards, and the inner ridge was now no more than a\par
shelf in the steep faces of the Ephel D\'faath; but to the east it fell as\par
sheerly as ever down into Gorgoroth. Ahead the water-course came to an end in\par
broken steps of rock; for out from the main range there sprang a high barren\par
spur, thrusting eastward like a wall. To meet it there stretched out from the\par
grey and misty northern range of Ered Lithui a long jutting arm; and between\par
the ends there was a narrow gap: Carach Angren, the Isenmouthe, beyond which\par
lay the deep dale of Ud\'fbn. In that dale behind the Morannon were the tunnels\par
and deep armouries that the servants of Mordor had made for the defence of the\par
Black Gate of their land; and there now their Lord was gathering in haste\par
great forces to meet the onslaught of the Captains of the West. Upon the outthrust\par
spurs forts and towers were built, and watch-fires burned; and all\par
across the gap an earth-wall had been raised, and a deep trench delved that\par
could be crossed only by a single bridge.\par
A few miles north, high up in the angle where the western spur branched\par
away from the main range, stood the old castle of Durthang, now one of the\par
many orc-holds that clustered about the dale of Ud\'fbn. A road, already visible\par
in the growing light, came winding down from it, until only a mile or two from\par
where the hobbits lay it turned east and ran along a shelf cut in the side of\par
the spur, and so went down into the plain, and on to the Isenmouthe.\par
To the hobbits as they looked out it seemed that all their journey north\par
had been useless. The plain to their right was dim and smoky, and they could\par
see there neither camps nor troops moving; but all that region was under the\par
vigilance of the forts of Carach Angren.\par
'We have come to a dead end, Sam,' said Frodo. 'If we go on, we shall\par
only come up to that orc-tower, but the only road to take is that road that\par
comes down from it \endash  unless we go back. We can't climb up westward, or climb\par
down eastward.'\par
'Then we must take the road, Mr. Frodo,' said Sam. 'We must take it and\par
chance our luck, if there is any luck in Mordor. We might as well give\par
ourselves up as wander about any more, or try to go back. Our food won't last.\par
We've got to make a dash for it!'\par
'All right, Sam,' said Frodo. 'Lead me! As long as you've got any hope\par
left. Mine is gone. But I can't dash, Sam. I'll just plod along after you.'\par
'Before you start any more plodding, you need sleep and food, Mr. Frodo.\par
Come and take what you can get of them!'\par
He gave Frodo water and an additional wafer of the waybread, and he made\par
a pillow of his cloak for his master's head. Frodo was too weary to debate the\par
matter, and Sam did not tell him that he had drunk the last drop of their\par
water, and eaten Sam's share of the food as well as his own. When Frodo was\par
asleep Sam bent over him and listened to his breathing and scanned his face.\par
It was lined and thin, and yet in sleep it looked content and unafraid. 'Well,\par
here goes, Master!' Sam muttered to himself. 'I'll have to leave you for a bit\par
and trust to luck. Water we must have, or we'll get no further.'\par
Sam crept out, and flitting from stone to stone with more than hobbitcare,\par
he went down to the water-course, and then followed it for some way as\par
it climbed north, until he came to the rock-steps where long ago, no doubt,\par
its spring had come gushing down in a little waterfall. All now seemed dry and\par
silent; but refusing to despair Sam stooped and listened, and to his delight\par
he caught the sound of trickling. Clambering a few steps up he found a tiny\par
stream of dark water that came out from the hill-side and filled a little bare\par
pool, from which again it spilled, and vanished then under the barren stones.\par
Sam tasted the water, and it seemed good enough. Then he drank deeply,\par
refilled the bottle, and turned to go back. At that moment he caught a glimpse\par
of a black form or shadow flitting among the rocks away near Frodo's hidingplace.\par
Biting back a cry, he leapt down from the spring and ran, jumping from\par
stone to stone. It was a wary creature, difficult to see, but Sam had little\par
doubt about it: he longed to get his hands on its neck. But it heard him\par
coming and slipped quickly away. Sam thought he saw a last fleeting glimpse of\par
it, peering back over the edge of the eastward precipice, before it ducked and\par
disappeared.\par
'Well, luck did not let me down,' muttered Sam, 'but that was a near\par
thing! Isn't it enough to have orcs by the thousand without that stinking\par
villain coming nosing round? I wish he had been shot!' He sat down by Frodo\par
and did not rouse him; but he did not dare to go to sleep himself. At last\par
when he felt his eyes closing and knew that his struggle to keep awake could\par
not go on much longer, he wakened Frodo gently.\par
'That Gollum's about again, I'm afraid, Mr. Frodo,' he said. 'Leastways,\par
if it wasn't him, then there's two of him. I went away to find some water and\par
spied him nosing round just as I turned back. I reckon it isn't safe for us\par
both to sleep together, and begging your pardon, but I can't hold up my lids\par
much longer.'\par
'Bless you, Sam!' said Frodo. 'Lie down and take your proper turn! But\par
I'd rather have Gollum than orcs. At any rate he won't give us away to them \endash\par
not unless he's caught himself.'\par
'But he might do a bit of robbery and murder on his own,' growled Sam.\par
'Keep your eyes open, Mr. Frodo! There's a bottle full of water. Drink up. We\par
can fill it again when we go on.' With that Sam plunged into sleep.\par
Light was fading when he woke. Frodo sat propped against the rock behind,\par
but he had fallen asleep. The water-bottle was empty. There was no sign of\par
Gollum.\par
Mordor-dark had returned, and the watch-fires on the heights burned\par
fierce and red, when the hobbits set out again on the most dangerous stage of\par
all their journey. They went first to the little spring, and then climbing\par
warily up they came to the road at the point where it swung east towards the\par
Isenmouthe twenty miles away. It was not a broad road, and it had no wall or\par
parapet along the edge and as it ran on the sheer drop from its brink became\par
deeper and deeper. The hobbits could hear no movements, and after listening\par
for a while they set off eastward at a steady pace.\par
After doing some twelve miles, they halted. A short way back the road had\par
bent a little northward and the stretch that they had passed over was now\par
screened from sight. This proved disastrous. They rested for some minutes and\par
then went on; but they had not taken many steps when suddenly in the stillness\par
of the night they heard the sound that all along they had secretly dreaded:\par
the noise of marching feet. It was still some way behind them, but looking\par
back they could see the twinkle of torches coming round the bend less than a\par
mile away, and they were moving fast: too fast for Frodo to escape by flight\par
along the road ahead.\par
'I feared it, Sam,' said Frodo. 'We've trusted to luck, and it has failed\par
us. We're trapped.' He looked wildly up at the frowning wall, where the roadbuilders\par
of old had cut the rock sheer for many fathoms above their heads. He\par
ran to the other side and looked over the brink into a dark pit of gloom.\par
'We're trapped at last!' he said He sank to the ground beneath the wall of\par
rock and bowed his head.\par
'Seems so,' said Sam. 'Well, we can but wait and see.' And with that he\par
sat down beside Frodo under the shadow of the cliff.\par
They did not have to wait long. The orcs were going at a great pace.\par
Those in the foremost files bore torches. On they came, red flames in the\par
dark, swiftly growing. Now Sam too bowed his head, hoping that it would hide\par
his face when the torches reached them; and he set their shields before their\par
knees to hide their feet.\par
'If only they are in a hurry and will let a couple of tired soldiers\par
alone and pass on!' he thought.\par
And so it seemed that they would. The leading orcs came loping along,\par
panting, holding their heads down. They were a gang of the smaller breeds\par
being driven unwilling to their Dark Lord's wars; all they cared for was to\par
get the march over and escape the whip. Beside them, running up and down the\par
line, went two of the large fierce _uruks_, cracking lashes and shouting. File\par
after file passed, and the tell-tale torchlight was already some way ahead.\par
Sam held his breath. Now more than half the line had gone by. Then suddenly\par
one of the slave-drivers spied the two figures by the road-side. He flicked a\par
whip at them and yelled: 'Hi, you! Get up!' They did not answer, and with a\par
shout he halted the whole company.\par
'Come on, you slugs!' he cried. 'This is no time for slouching.' He took\par
a step towards them, and even in the gloom he recognized the devices on their\par
shields. 'Deserting, eh?' he snarled. 'Or thinking of it? All your folk should\par
have been inside Ud\'fbn before yesterday evening. You know that. Up you get and\par
fall in, or I'll have your numbers and report you.'\par
They struggled to their feet, and keeping bent, limping like footsore\par
soldiers, they shuffled back towards the rear of the line. 'No, not at the\par
rear!' the slave-driver shouted. 'Three files up. And stay there, or you'll\par
know it, when I come down the line!' He sent his long whip-lash cracking over\par
their heads; then with another crack and a yell he started the company off\par
again at a brisk trot.\par
It was hard enough for poor Sam, tired as he was; but for Frodo it was a\par
torment, and soon a nightmare. He set his teeth and tried to stop his mind\par
from thinking, and he struggled on. The stench of the sweating orcs about him\par
was stifling, and he began to gasp with thirst. On, on they went, and he bent\par
all his will to draw his breath and to make his legs keep going; and yet to\par
what evil end he toiled and endured he did not dare to think. There was no\par
hope of falling out unseen: Now and again the orc-driver fell back and jeered\par
at them.\par
'There now!' he laughed, flicking at their legs. 'Where there's a whip\par
there's a will, my slugs. Hold up! I'd give you a nice freshener now, only\par
you'll get as much lash as your skins will carry when you come in late to your\par
camp. Do you good. Don't you know we're at war?'\par
They had gone some miles, and the road was at last running down a long\par
slope into the plain, when Frodo's strength began to give out and his will\par
wavered. He lurched and stumbled. Desperately Sam tried to help him and hold\par
him up, though he felt that he could himself hardly stay the pace much longer.\par
At any moment now he knew that the end would come: his master would faint or\par
fall, and all would be discovered, and their bitter efforts be in vain. 'I'll\par
have that big slave-driving devil anyway,' he thought.\par
Then just as he was putting his hand to the hilt of his sword, there came\par
an unexpected relief. They were out on the plain now and drawing near the\par
entrance to Ud\'fbn. Some way in front of it, before the gate at the bridge-end,\par
the road from the west converged with others coming from the south, and from\par
Barad-d\'fbr. Along all the roads troops were moving; for the Captains of the\par
West were advancing and the Dark Lord was speeding his forces north. So it\par
chanced that several companies came together at the road-meeting, in the dark\par
beyond the light of the watch-fires on the wall. At once there was great\par
jostling and cursing as each troop tried to get first to the gate and the\par
ending of their march. Though the drivers yelled and plied their whips,\par
scuffles broke out and some blades were drawn. A troop of heavy-armed _uruks_\par
from Barad-d\'fbr charged into the Durthang line and threw them into confusion.\par
Dazed as he was with pain and weariness, Sam woke up, grasped quickly at\par
his chance, and threw himself to the ground, dragging Frodo down with him.\par
Orcs fell over them, snarling and cursing. Slowly on hand and knee the hobbits\par
crawled away out of the turmoil, until at last unnoticed they dropped over the\par
further edge of the road. It had a high kerb by which troop-leaders could\par
guide themselves in black night or fog, and it was banked up some feet above\par
the level of the open land.\par
They lay still for a while. It was too dark to seek for cover, if indeed\par
there was any to find; but Sam felt that they ought at least to get further\par
away from the highways and out of the range of torch-light.\par
'Come on, Mr. Frodo!' he whispered. 'One more crawl, and then you can lie\par
still.'\par
With a last despairing effort Frodo raised himself on his hands, and\par
struggled on for maybe twenty yards. Then he pitched down into a shallow pit\par
that opened unexpectedly before them, and there he lay like a dead thing.\par
_Chapter 3_\par
Mount Doom\par
Sam put his ragged orc-cloak under his master's head, and covered them\par
both with the grey robe of L\'f3rien; and as he did so his thoughts went out to\par
that fair land, and to the Elves, and he hoped that the cloth woven by their\par
hands might have some virtue to keep them hidden beyond all hope in this\par
wilderness of fear. He heard the scuffling and cries die down as the troops\par
passed on through the Isenmouthe. It seemed that in the confusion and the\par
mingling of many companies of various kinds they had not been missed, not yet\par
at any rate.\par
Sam took a sip of water, but pressed Frodo to drink, and when his master\par
had recovered a little he gave him a whole wafer of their precious waybread\par
and made him eat it. Then, too worn out even to feel much fear, they stretched\par
themselves out. They slept a little in uneasy fits; for their sweat grew chill\par
on them, and the hard stones bit them, and they shivered. Out of the north\par
from the Black Gate through Cirith Gorgor there flowed whispering along the\par
ground a thin cold air.\par
In the morning a grey light came again, for in the high regions the West\par
Wind still blew, but down on the stones behind the fences of the Black Land\par
the air seemed almost dead, chill and yet stifling. Sam looked up out of the\par
hollow. The land all about was dreary, flat and drab-hued. On the roads nearby\par
nothing was moving now; but Sam feared the watchful eyes on the wall of the\par
Isenmouthe, no more than a furlong away northward. South-eastward, far off\par
like a dark standing shadow. loomed the Mountain. Smokes were pouring from it\par
and while those that rose into the upper air trailed away eastward, great\par
rolling clouds floated down its sides and spread over the land. A few miles to\par
the north-east the foothills of the Ashen Mountains stood like sombre grey\par
ghosts, behind which the misty northern heights rose like a line of distant\par
cloud hardly darker than the lowering sky.\par
Sam tried to guess the distances and to decide what way they ought to\par
take. It looks every step of fifty miles,' he muttered gloomily staring at the\par
threatening mountain, 'and that'll take a week, if it takes a day, with Mr.\par
Frodo as he is.' He shook his head, and as he worked things out, slowly a new\par
dark thought grew in his mind. Never for long had hope died in his staunch\par
heart, and always until now he had taken some thought for their return. But\par
the bitter truth came home to him at last: at best their provision would take\par
them to their goal; and when the task was done, there they would come to an\par
end, alone, houseless, foodless in the midst of a terrible desert. There could\par
be no return.\par
'So that was the job I felt I had to do when I started,' thought Sam: 'to\par
help Mr. Frodo to the last step and then die with him? Well, if that is the\par
job then I must do it. But I would dearly like to see Bywater again, and Rosie\par
Cotton and her brothers, and the Gaffer and Marigold and all. I can't think\par
somehow that Gandalf would have sent Mr. Frodo on this errand if there hadn't\par
a' been any hope of his ever coming back at all. Things all went wrong when he\par
went down in Moria. I wish he hadn't. He would have done something.'\par
But even as hope died in Sam, or seemed to die, it was turned to a new\par
strength. Sam's plain hobbit-face grew stern, almost grim, as the will\par
hardened in him, and he felt through all his limbs a thrill, as if he was\par
turning into some creature of stone and steel that neither despair nor\par
weariness nor endless barren miles could subdue.\par
With a new sense of responsibility he brought his eyes back to the ground\par
near at hand, studying the next move. As the light grew a little he saw to his\par
surprise that what from a distance had seemed wide and featureless flats were\par
in fact all broken and tumbled. Indeed the whole surface of the plains of\par
Gorgoroth was pocked with great holes, as if, while it was still a waste of\par
soft mud, it had been smitten with a shower of bolts and huge slingstones. The\par
largest of these holes were rimmed with ridges of broken rock, and broad\par
fissures ran out from them in all directions. It was a land in which it would\par
be possible to creep from hiding to hiding, unseen by all but the most\par
watchful eyes: possible at least for one who was strong and had no need for\par
speed. For the hungry and worn, who had far to go before life failed, it had\par
an evil look.\par
Thinking of all these things Sam went back to his master. He had no need\par
to rouse him. Frodo was lying on his back with eyes open, staring at the\par
cloudy sky. 'Well, Mr. Frodo,' said Sam, 'I've been having a look round and\par
thinking a bit. There's nothing on the roads, and we'd best be getting away\par
while there's a chance. Can you manage it?'\par
'I can manage it,' said Frodo. 'I must.'\par
Once more they started, crawling from hollow to hollow, flitting behind\par
such cover as they could find, but moving always in a slant towards the\par
foothills of the northern range. But as they went the most easterly of the\par
roads followed them, until it ran off, hugging the skirts of the mountains,\par
away into a wall of black shadow far ahead. Neither man nor orc now moved\par
along its flat grey stretches; for the Dark Lord had almost completed the\par
movement of his forces, and even in the fastness of his own realm he sought\par
the secrecy of night, fearing the winds of the world that had turned against\par
him, tearing aside his veils, and troubled with tidings of bold spies that had\par
passed through his fences.\par
The hobbits had gone a few weary miles when they halted. Frodo seemed\par
nearly spent. Sam saw that he could not go much further in this fashion,\par
crawling, stooping, now picking a doubtful way very slowly, now hurrying at a\par
stumbling run.\par
'I'm going back on to the road while the light lasts, Mr. Frodo,' he\par
said. 'Trust to luck again! It nearly failed us last time, but it didn't\par
quite. A steady pace for a few more miles, and then a rest.'\par
He was taking a far greater risk than he knew; but Frodo was too much\par
occupied with his burden and with the struggle in his mind to debate, and\par
almost too hopeless to care. They climbed on to the causeway and trudged\par
along, down the hard cruel road that led to the Dark Tower itself. But their\par
luck held, and for the rest of that day they met no living or moving thing;\par
and when night fell they vanished into the darkness of Mordor. All the land\par
now brooded as at the coming of a great storm: for the Captains of the West\par
had passed the Cross-roads and set flames in the deadly fields of Imlad\par
Morgul.\par
So the desperate journey went on, as the Ring went south and the banners\par
of the kings rode north. For the hobbits each day, each mile. was more bitter\par
than the one before, as their strength lessened and the land became more evil.\par
They met no enemies by day. At times by night, as they cowered or drowsed\par
uneasily in some hiding beside the road, they heard cries and the noise of\par
many feet or the swift passing of some cruelly ridden steed. But far worse\par
than all such perils was the ever-approaching threat that beat upon them as\par
they went: the dreadful menace of the Power that waited, brooding in deep\par
thought and sleepless malice behind the dark veil about its Throne. Nearer and\par
nearer it drew, looming blacker, like the oncoming of a wall of night at the\par
last end of the world.\par
There came at last a dreadful nightfall; and even as the Captains of the\par
West drew near to the end of the living lands, the two wanderers came to an\par
hour of blank despair. Four days had passed since they had escaped from the\par
orcs, but the time lay behind them like an ever-darkening dream. All this last\par
day Frodo had not spoken, but had walked half-bowed, often stumbling, as if\par
his eyes no longer saw the way before his feet. Sam guessed that among all\par
their pains he bore the worst, the growing weight of the Ring, a burden on the\par
body and a torment to his mind. Anxiously Sam had noted how his master's left\par
hand would often be raised as if to ward on a blow, or to screen his shrinking\par
eyes from a dreadful Eye that sought to look in them. And sometimes his right\par
hand would creep to his breast, clutching, and then slowly, as the will\par
recovered mastery, it would be withdrawn.\par
Now as the blackness of night returned Frodo sat, his head between his\par
knees, his arms hanging wearily to the ground where his hands lay feebly\par
twitching. Sam watched him, till night covered them both and hid them from one\par
another. He could no longer find any words to say; and he turned to his own\par
dark thoughts. As for himself, though weary and under a shadow of fear, he\par
still had some strength left. The _lembas_ had a virtue without which they\par
would long ago have lain down to die. It did not satisfy desire, and at times\par
Sam's mind was filled with the memories of food, and the longing for simple\par
bread and meats. And yet this waybread of the Elves had a potency that\par
increased as travellers relied on it alone and did not mingle it with other\par
foods. It fed the will, and it gave strength to endure, and to master sinew\par
and limb beyond the measure of mortal kind. But now a new decision must be\par
made. They could not follow this road any longer; for it went on eastward into\par
the great Shadow, but the Mountain now loomed upon their right, almost due\par
south, and they must turn towards it. Yet still before it there stretched a\par
wide region of fuming, barren, ash-ridden land.\par
'Water, water!' muttered Sam. He had stinted himself, and in his parched\par
mouth his tongue seemed thick and swollen; but for all his care they now had\par
very little left, perhaps half his bottle, and maybe there were still days to\par
go. All would long ago have been spent, if they had not dared to follow the\par
orc-road. For at long intervals on that highway cisterns had been built for\par
the use of troops sent in haste through the waterless regions. In one Sam had\par
found some water left, stale, muddied by the orcs, but still sufficient for\par
their desperate case. Yet that was now a day ago. There was no hope of any\par
more.\par
At last wearied with his cares Sam drowsed, leaving the morrow till it\par
came; he could do no more. Dream and waking mingled uneasily. He saw lights\par
like gloating yes, and dark creeping shapes, and he heard noises as of wild\par
beasts or the dreadful cries of tortured things; and he would start up to find\par
the world all dark and only empty blackness all about him. Once only, as he\par
stood and stared wildly round, did it seem that, though now awake, he could\par
still see pale lights like eyes; but soon they flickered and vanished.\par
The hateful night passed slowly and reluctantly. Such daylight as\par
followed was dim; for here as the Mountain drew near the air was ever mirky,\par
while out from the Dark Tower there crept the veils of Shadow that Sauron wove\par
about himself. Frodo was lying on his back not moving. Sam stood beside him,\par
reluctant to speak, and yet knowing that the word now lay with him: he must\par
set his master's will to work for another effort. At length, stooping and\par
caressing Frodo's brow, he spoke in his ear.\par
'Wake up, Master!' he said. 'Time for another start.'\par
As if roused by a sudden bell, Frodo rose quickly, and stood up and\par
looked away southwards; but when his eyes beheld the Mountain and the desert\par
he quailed again.\par
'I can't manage it, Sam,' he said. 'It is such a weight to carry, such a\par
weight.'\par
Sam knew before he spoke, that it was vain, and that such words might do\par
more harm than good, but in his pity he could not keep silent. 'Then let me\par
carry it a bit for you, Master,' he said. 'You know I would, and gladly, as\par
long as I have any strength.'\par
A wild light came into Frodo's eyes. 'Stand away! Don't touch me!' he\par
cried. 'It is mine, I say. Be off!' His hand strayed to his sword-hilt. But\par
then quickly his voice changed. 'No, no, Sam,' he said sadly. 'But you must\par
understand. It is my burden, and no one else can bear it. It is too late now,\par
Sam dear. You can't help me in that way again. I am almost in its power now. I\par
could not give it up, and if you tried to take it I should go mad.'\par
Sam nodded. 'I understand,' he said. 'But I've been thinking, Mr. Frodo,\par
there's other things we might do without. Why not lighten the load a bit?\par
We're going that way now, as straight as we can make it.' He pointed to the\par
Mountain. 'It's no good taking anything we're not sure to need.'\par
Frodo looked again towards the Mountain. 'No,' he said, 'we shan't need\par
much on that road. And at its end nothing.' Picking up his orc-shield he flung\par
it away and threw his helmet after it. Then pulling off the grey cloak he\par
undid the heavy belt and let it fall to the ground, and the sheathed sword\par
with it. The shreds of the black cloak he tore off and scattered.\par
'There, I'll be an orc no more,' he cried, 'and I'll bear no weapon fair\par
or foul. Let them take me, if they will!'\par
Sam did likewise, and put aside his orc-gear; and he took out all the\par
things in his pack. Somehow each of them had become dear to him, if only\par
because he had borne them so far with so much toil. Hardest of all it was to\par
part with his cooking-gear. Tears welled in his eyes at the thought of casting\par
it away.\par
'Do you remember that bit of rabbit, Mr. Frodo?' he said. 'And our place\par
under the warm bank in Captain Faramir's country, the day I saw an oliphaunt?'\par
'No, I am afraid not, Sam,' said Frodo. 'At least, I know that such\par
things happened, but I cannot see them. No taste of food, no feel of water, no\par
sound of wind, no memory of tree or grass or flower, no image of moon or star\par
are left to me. I am naked in the dark. Sam, and there is no veil between me\par
and the wheel of fire. I begin to see it even with my waking eyes, and all\par
else fades.'\par
Sam went to him and kissed his hand. 'Then the sooner we're rid of it,\par
the sooner to rest,' he said haltingly, finding no better words to say.\par
'Talking won't mend nothing,' he muttered to himself, as he gathered up all\par
the things that they had chosen to cast away. He was not willing to leave them\par
lying open in the wilderness for any eyes to see. 'Stinker picked up that orcshirt,\par
seemingly, and he isn't going to add a sword to it. His hands are bad\par
enough when empty. And he isn't going to mess with my pans!' With that he\par
carried all the gear away to one of the many gaping fissures that scored the\par
land and threw them in. The clatter of his precious pans as they fell down\par
into the dark was like a death-knell to his heart.\par
He came back to Frodo, and then of his elven-rope he cut a short piece to\par
serve his master as a girdle and bind the grey cloak close about his waist.\par
The rest he carefully coiled and put back in his pack. Beside that he kept\par
only the remnants of their waybread and the water-bottle, and Sting still\par
hanging by his belt; and hidden away in a pocket of his tunic next his breast\par
the phial of Galadriel and the little box that she gave him for his own.\par
Now at last they turned their faces to the Mountain and set out, thinking\par
no more of concealment, bending their weariness and failing wills only to the\par
one task of going on. In the dimness of its dreary day few things even in that\par
land of vigilance could have espied them, save from close at hand. Of all the\par
slaves of the Dark Lord, only the Nazg\'fbl could have warned him of the peril\par
that crept, small but indomitable, into the very heart of his guarded realm.\par
But the Nazg\'fbl and their black wings were abroad on another errand: they were\par
gathered far away, shadowing the march of the Captains of the West, and\par
thither the thought of the Dark Tower was turned.\par
That day it seemed to Sam that his master had found some new strength,\par
more than could be explained by the small lightening of the load that he had\par
to carry. In the first marches they went further and faster than he had hoped.\par
The land was rough and hostile, and yet they made much progress, and ever the\par
Mountain drew nearer. But as the day wore on and all too soon the dim light\par
began to fail, Frodo stooped again, and began to stagger, as if the renewed\par
effort had squandered his remaining strength.\par
At their last halt he sank down and said: 'I'm thirsty, Sam,' and did not\par
speak again. Sam gave him a mouthful of water; only one more mouthful\par
remained. He went without himself; and now as once more the night of Mordor\par
closed over them, through all his thoughts there came the memory of water; and\par
every brook or stream or fount that he had ever seen, under green willowshades\par
or twinkling in the sun, danced and rippled for his torment behind the\par
blindness of his eyes. He felt the cool mud about his toes as he paddled in\par
the Pool at Bywater with Jolly Cotton and Tom and Nibs, and their sister\par
Rosie. 'But that was years ago,' he sighed, 'and far away. The way back, if\par
there is one, goes past the Mountain.'\par
He could not sleep and he held a debate with himself. 'Well, come now,\par
we've done better than you hoped,' he said sturdily. 'Began well anyway. I\par
reckon we crossed half the distance before we stopped. One more day will do\par
it.' And then he paused.\par
'Don't be a fool, Sam Gamgee,' came an answer in his own voice. 'He won't\par
go another day like that, if he moves at all. And you can't go on much longer\par
giving him all the water and most of the food.'\par
'I can go on a good way though, and I will.'\par
'Where to?'\par
'To the Mountain, of course.'\par
'But what then, Sam Gamgee, what then? When you get there, what are you\par
going to do? He won't be able to do anything for himself.'\par
To his dismay Sam realized that he had not got an answer to this. He had\par
no clear idea at all. Frodo had not spoken much to him of his errand, and Sam\par
only knew vaguely that the Ring had somehow to be put into the fire. 'The\par
Cracks of Doom,' he muttered, the old name rising to his mind. 'Well, if\par
Master knows how to find them, I don't.'\par
'There you are!' came the answer. 'It's all quite useless. He said so\par
himself. You are the fool, going on hoping and toiling. You could have lain\par
down and gone to sleep together days ago, if you hadn't been so dogged. But\par
you'll die just the same, or worse. You might just as well lie down now and\par
give it up. You'll never get to the top anyway.'\par
'I'll get there, if I leave everything but my bones behind,' said Sam.\par
'And I'll carry Mr. Frodo up myself, if it breaks my back and heart. So stop\par
arguing!'\par
At that moment Sam felt a tremor in the ground beneath him, and he heard\par
or sensed a deep remote rumble as of thunder imprisoned under the earth. There\par
was a brief red flame that flickered under the clouds and died away. The\par
Mountain too slept uneasily.\par
The last stage of their journey to Orodruin came, and it was a torment\par
greater than Sam had ever thought that he could bear. He was in pain, and so\par
parched that he could no longer swallow even a mouthful of food. It remained\par
dark, not only because of the smokes of the Mountain: there seemed to be a\par
storm coming up, and away to the south-east there was a shimmer of lightnings\par
under the black skies. Worst of all, the air was full of fumes; breathing was\par
painful and difficult, and a dizziness came on them, so that they staggered\par
and often fell. And yet their wills did not yield, and they struggled on.\par
The Mountain crept up ever nearer, until, if they lifted their heavy\par
heads, it filled all their sight, looming vast before them: a huge mass of ash\par
and slag and burned stone, out of which a sheer-sided cone was raised into the\par
clouds. Before the daylong dusk ended and true night came again they had\par
crawled and stumbled to its very feet.\par
With a gasp Frodo cast himself on the ground. Sam sat by him. To his\par
surprise he felt tired but lighter, and his head seemed clear again. No more\par
debates disturbed his mind. He knew all the arguments of despair and would not\par
listen to them. His will was set, and only death would break it. He felt no\par
longer either desire or need of sleep, but rather of watchfulness. He knew\par
that all the hazards and perils were now drawing together to a point: the next\par
day would be a day of doom, the day of final effort or disaster, the last\par
gasp.\par
But when would it come? The night seemed endless and timeless, minute\par
after minute falling dead and adding up to no passing hour, bringing no\par
change. Sam began to wonder if a second darkness had begun and no day would\par
ever reappear. At last he groped for Frodo's hand. It was cold and trembling.\par
His master was shivering.\par
'I didn't ought to have left my blanket behind,' muttered Sam; and lying\par
down he tried to comfort Frodo with his arms and body. Then sleep took him,\par
and the dim light of the last day of their quest found them side by side. The\par
wind had fallen the day before as it shifted from the West, and now it came\par
from the North and began to rise; and slowly the light of the unseen Sun\par
filtered down into the shadows where the hobbits lay.\par
'Now for it! Now for the last gasp!' said Sam as he struggled to his\par
feet. He bent over Frodo, rousing him gently. Frodo groaned; but with a great\par
effort of will he staggered up; and then he fell upon his knees again. He\par
raised his eyes with difficulty to the dark slopes of Mount Doom towering\par
above him, and then pitifully he began to crawl forward on his hands.\par
Sam looked at him and wept in his heart, but no tears came to his dry and\par
stinging eyes. 'I said I'd carry him, if it broke my back,' he muttered, 'and\par
I will!'\par
'Come, Mr. Frodo!' he cried. 'I can't carry it for you, but I can carry\par
you and it as well. So up you get! Come on, Mr. Frodo dear! Sam will give you\par
a ride. Just tell him where to go, and he'll go.'\par
As Frodo clung upon his back, arms loosely about his neck, legs clasped\par
firmly under his arms, Sam staggered to his feet; and then to his amazement he\par
felt the burden light. He had feared that he would have barely strength to\par
lift his master alone, and beyond that he had expected to share in the\par
dreadful dragging weight of the accursed Ring. But it was not so. Whether\par
because Frodo was so worn by his long pains, wound of knife, and venomous\par
sting, and sorrow, fear, and homeless wandering, or because some gift of final\par
strength was given to him, Sam lifted Frodo with no more difficulty than if he\par
were carrying a hobbit-child pig-a-back in some romp on the lawns or hayfields\par
of the Shire. He took a deep breath and started off.\par
They had reached the Mountain's foot on its northern side, and a little\par
to the westward; there its long grey slopes, though broken, were not sheer.\par
Frodo did not speak, and so Sam struggled on as best he could, having no\par
guidance but the will to climb as high as might be before his strength gave\par
out and his will broke. On he toiled, up and up, turning this way and that to\par
lessen the slope, often stumbling forward, and at the last crawling like a\par
snail with a heavy burden on its back. When his will could drive him no\par
further, and his limbs gave way, he stopped and laid his master gently down.\par
Frodo opened his eyes and drew a breath. It was easier to breathe up here\par
above the reeks that coiled and drifted down below. 'Thank you, Sam,' he said\par
in a cracked whisper. 'How far is there to go?'\par
'I don't know,' said Sam, 'because I don't know where we're going.'\par
He looked back, and then he looked up; and he was amazed to see how far\par
his last effort had brought him. The Mountain standing ominous and alone had\par
looked taller than it was. Sam saw now that it was less lofty than the high\par
passes of the Ephel D\'faath which he and Frodo had scaled. The confused and\par
tumbled shoulders of its great base rose for maybe three thousand feet above\par
the plain, and above them was reared half as high again its tall central cone,\par
like a vast oast or chimney capped with a jagged crater. But already Sam was\par
more than half way up the base, and the plain of Gorgoroth was dim below him,\par
wrapped in fume and shadow. As he looked up he would have given a shout. if\par
his parched throat had allowed him; for amid the rugged humps and shoulders\par
above him he saw plainly a path or road. It climbed like a rising girdle from\par
the west and wound snakelike about the Mountain, until before it went round\par
out of view it reached the foot of the cone upon its eastern side.\par
Sam could not see the course immediately above him, where it was lowest,\par
for a steep slope went up from where he stood; but he guessed that if he could\par
only struggle on just a little way further up, they would strike this path. A\par
gleam of hope returned to him. They might conquer the Mountain yet. 'Why, it\par
might have been put there a-purpose!' he said to himself. 'If it wasn't there,\par
I'd have to say I was beaten in the end.'\par
The path was not put there for the purposes of Sam. He did not know it,\par
but he was looking at Sauron's Road from Barad-d\'fbr to the Sammath Naur, the\par
Chambers of Fire. Out from the Dark Tower's huge western gate it came over a\par
deep abyss by a vast bridge of iron, and then passing into the plain it ran\par
for a league between two smoking chasms, and so reached a long sloping\par
causeway that led up on to the Mountain's eastern side. Thence, turning and\par
encircling all its wide girth from south to north, it climbed at last, high in\par
the upper cone, but still far from the reeking summit, to a dark entrance that\par
gazed back east straight to the Window of the Eye in Sauron's shadow-mantled\par
fortress. Often blocked or destroyed by the tumults of the Mountain's\par
furnaces, always that road was repaired and cleaned again by the labours of\par
countless orcs.\par
Sam drew a deep breath. There was a path, but how he was to get up the\par
slope to it he did not know. First he must ease his aching back. He lay flat\par
beside Frodo for a while. Neither spoke. Slowly the light grew. Suddenly a\par
sense of urgency which he did not understand came to Sam. It was almost as if\par
he had been called: 'Now, now, or it will be too late!' He braced himself and\par
got up. Frodo also seemed to have felt the call. He struggled to his knees.\par
'I'll crawl, Sam,' he gasped.\par
So foot by foot, like small grey insects, they crept up the slope. They\par
came to the path and found that it was broad, paved with broken rubble and\par
beaten ash. Frodo clambered on to it, and then moved as if by some compulsion\par
he turned slowly to face the East. Far off the shadows of Sauron hung; but\par
torn by some gust of wind out of the world, or else moved by some great\par
disquiet within, the mantling clouds swirled, and for a moment drew aside; and\par
then he saw, rising black, blacker and darker than the vast shades amid which\par
it stood, the cruel pinnacles and iron crown of the topmost tower of Baradd\'fbr.\par
One moment only it stared out, but as from some great window immeasurably\par
high there stabbed northward a flame of red, the flicker of a piercing Eye;\par
and then the shadows were furled again and the terrible vision was removed.\par
The Eye was not turned to them: it was gazing north to where the Captains of\par
the West stood at bay, and thither all its malice was now bent, as the Power\par
moved to strike its deadly blow; but Frodo at that dreadful glimpse fell as\par
one stricken mortally. His hand sought the chain about his neck.\par
Sam knelt by him. Faint, almost inaudibly, he heard Frodo whispering:\par
'Help me, Sam! Help me, Sam! Hold my hand! I can't stop it.' Sam took his\par
master's hands and laid them together, palm to palm, and kissed them; and then\par
he held them gently between his own. The thought came suddenly to him: 'He's\par
spotted us! It's all up, or it soon will be. Now, Sam Gamgee, this is the end\par
of ends.'\par
Again he lifted Frodo and drew his hands down to his own breast. letting\par
his master's legs dangle. Then he bowed his head and struggled off along the\par
climbing road. It was not as easy a way to take as it had looked at first. By\par
fortune the fires that had poured forth in the great turmoils when Sam stood\par
upon Cirith Ungol had flowed down mainly on the southern and western slopes,\par
and the road on this side was not blocked. Yet in many places it had crumbled\par
away or was crossed by gaping rents. After climbing eastward for some time it\par
bent back upon itself at a sharp angle and went westward fox a space. There at\par
the bend it was cut deep through a crag of old weathered stone once long ago\par
vomited from the Mountain's furnaces. Panting under his load Sam turned the\par
bend; and even as he did so, out of the corner of his eye, he had a glimpse of\par
something falling from the crag, like a small piece of black stone that had\par
toppled off as he passed.\par
A sudden weight smote him and he crashed forward, tearing the backs of\par
his hands that still clasped his master's. Then he knew what had happened, for\par
above him as he lay he heard a hated voice.\par
'Wicked masster!' it hissed. 'Wicked masster cheats us; cheats Sm\'e9agol,\par
_gollum_. He musstn't go that way. He musstn't hurt Preciouss. Give it to\par
Sm\'e9agol, yess, give it to us! Give it to uss!'\par
With a violent heave Sam rose up. At once he drew his sword; but he could\par
do nothing. Gollum and Frodo were locked together. Gollum was tearing at his\par
master, trying to get at the chain and the Ring. This was probably the only\par
thing that could have roused the dying embers of Frodo's heart and will: an\par
attack, an attempt to wrest his treasure from him by force. He fought back\par
with a sudden fury that amazed Sam, and Gollum also. Even so things might have\par
gone far otherwise, if Gollum himself had remained unchanged; but whatever\par
dreadful paths, lonely and hungry and waterless, he had trodden, driven by a\par
devouring desire and a terrible fear, they had left grievous marks on him. He\par
was a lean, starved, haggard thing, all bones and tight-drawn sallow skin. A\par
wild light flamed in his eyes, but his malice was no longer matched by his old\par
griping strength. Frodo flung him off and rose up quivering.\par
'Down, down!' he gasped, clutching his hand to his breast, so that\par
beneath the cover of his leather shirt he clasped the Ring. 'Down you creeping\par
thing, and out of my path! Your time is at an end. You cannot betray me or\par
slay me now.'\par
Then suddenly, as before under the eaves of the Emyn Muil, Sam saw these\par
two rivals with other vision. A crouching shape, scarcely more than the shadow\par
of a living thing, a creature now wholly ruined and defeated, yet filled with\par
a hideous lust and rage; and before it stood stern, untouchable now by pity, a\par
figure robed in white, but at its breast it held a wheel of fire. Out of the\par
fire there spoke a commanding voice.\par
'Begone, and trouble me no more! If you touch me ever again, you shall be\par
cast yourself into the Fire of Doom.'\par
The crouching shape backed away, terror in its blinking eyes, and yet at\par
the same time insatiable desire.\par
Then the vision passed and Sam saw Frodo standing, hand on breast, his\par
breath coming in great gasps, and Gollum at his feet, resting on his knees\par
with his wide-splayed hands upon the ground.\par
'Look out!' cried Sam. 'He'll spring!' He stepped forward, brandishing\par
his sword. 'Quick, Master!' he gasped. 'Go on! Go on! No time to lose. I'll\par
deal with him. Go on!'\par
Frodo looked at him as if at one now far away. 'Yes, I must go on,' he\par
said. 'Farewell, Sam! This is the end at last. On Mount Doom doom shall fall.\par
Farewell!' He turned and went on, walking slowly but erect up the climbing\par
path.\par
'Now!' said Sam. 'At last I can deal with you!' He leaped forward with\par
drawn blade ready for battle. But Gollum did not spring. He fell flat upon the\par
ground and whimpered.\par
'Don't kill us,' he wept. 'Don't hurt us with nassty cruel steel! Let us\par
live, yes, live just a little longer. Lost lost! We're lost. And when Precious\par
goes we'll die, yes, die into the dust.' He clawed up the ashes of the path\par
with his long fleshless fingers. 'Dusst!' he hissed.\par
Sam's hand wavered. His mind was hot with wrath and the memory of evil.\par
It would be just to slay this treacherous, murderous creature, just and many\par
times deserved; and also it seemed the only safe thing to do. But deep in his\par
heart there was something that restrained him: he could not strike this thing\par
lying in the dust, forlorn, ruinous, utterly wretched. He himself, though only\par
for a little while, had borne the Ring, and now dimly he guessed the agony of\par
Gollum's shrivelled mind and body, enslaved to that Ring, unable to find peace\par
or relief ever in life again. But Sam had no words to express what he felt.\par
'Oh, curse you, you stinking thing!' he said. 'Go away! Be off! I don't\par
trust you, not as far as I could kick you; but be off. Or I _shall_ hurt you,\par
yes, with nasty cruel steel.'\par
Gollum got up on all fours, and backed away for several paces, and then\par
he turned, and as Sam aimed a kick at him he fled away down the path. Sam gave\par
no more heed to him. He suddenly remembered his master. He looked up the path\par
and could not see him. As fast as he could he trudged up the road. If he had\par
looked back, he might have seen not far below Gollum turn again, and then with\par
a wild light of madness glaring in his eyes come, swiftly but warily, creeping\par
on behind, a slinking shadow among the stones.\par
The path climbed on. Soon it bent again and. with a last eastward course\par
passed in a cutting along the face of the cone and came to the dark door in\par
the Mountain's side, the door of the Sammath Naur. Far away now rising towards\par
the South the sun, piercing the smokes and haze, burned ominous, a dull\par
bleared disc of red; but all Mordor lay about the Mountain like a dead land,\par
silent, shadow-folded, waiting for some dreadful stroke.\par
Sam came to the gaping mouth and peered in. It was dark and hot, and a\par
deep rumbling shook the air. 'Frodo! Master!' he called. There was no answer.\par
For a moment he stood, his heart beating with wild fears, and then he plunged\par
in. A shadow followed him.\par
At first he could see nothing. In his great need he drew out once more\par
the phial of Galadriel, but it was pale and cold in his trembling hand and\par
threw no light into that stifling dark. He was come to the heart of the realm\par
of Sauron and the forges of his ancient might, greatest in Middle-earth; all\par
other powers were here subdued. Fearfully he took a few uncertain steps in the\par
dark, and then all at once there came a flash of red that leaped upward, and\par
smote the high black roof. Then Sam saw that he was in a long cave or tunnel\par
that bored into the Mountain's smoking cone. But only a short way ahead its\par
floor and the walls on either side were cloven by a great fissure, out of\par
which the red glare came, now leaping up, now dying down into darkness; and\par
all the while far below there was a rumour and a trouble as of great engines\par
throbbing and labouring.\par
The light sprang up again, and there on the brink of the chasm, at the\par
very Crack of Doom, stood Frodo, black against the glare, tense, erect, but\par
still as if he had been turned to stone.\par
'Master!' cried Sam.\par
Then Frodo stirred and spoke with a clear voice, indeed with a voice\par
clearer and more powerful than Sam had ever heard him use, and it rose above\par
the throb and turmoil of Mount Doom, ringing in the roof and walls.\par
'I have come,' he said. 'But I do not choose now to do what I came to do.\par
I will not do this deed. The Ring is mine!' And suddenly, as he set it on his\par
finger, he vanished from Sam's sight. Sam gasped, but he had no chance to cry\par
out, for at that moment many things happened.\par
Something struck Sam violently in the back, his legs were knocked from\par
under him and he was flung aside, striking his head against the stony floor,\par
as a dark shape sprang over him. He lay still and for a moment all went black.\par
And far away, as Frodo put on the Ring and claimed it for his own, even\par
in Sammath Naur the very heart of his realm, the Power in Barad-d\'fbr was\par
shaken, and the Tower trembled from its foundations to its proud and bitter\par
crown. The Dark Lord was suddenly aware of him, and his Eye piercing all\par
shadows looked across the plain to the door that he had made; and the\par
magnitude of his own folly was revealed to him in a blinding flash, and all\par
the devices of his enemies were at last laid bare. Then his wrath blazed in\par
consuming flame, but his fear rose like a vast black smoke to choke him. For\par
he knew his deadly peril and the thread upon which his doom now hung.\par
From all his policies and webs of fear and treachery, from all his\par
