From Deeping-coomb they rode to Isengard, and saw how the Ents had busied\par
themselves. All the stone-circle had been thrown down and removed, and the\par
land within was made into a garden filled with orchards and trees, and a\par
stream ran through it; but in the midst of all there was a lake of clear\par
water, and out of it the Tower of Orthanc rose still, tall and impregnable,\par
and its black rock was mirrored in the pool.\par
For a while the travellers sat where once the old gates of Isengard had\par
stood, and there were now two tall trees like sentinels at the beginning of a\par
green-bordered path that ran towards Orthanc; and they looked in wonder at the\par
work that had been done, but no living thing could they see far or near. But\par
presently they heard a voice calling _hoom-hom_, _hoom-hom_; and there came\par
Treebeard striding down the path to greet them with Quickbeam at his side.\par
'Welcome to the Treegarth of Orthanc!' he said. 'I knew that you were\par
coming, but I was at work up the valley; there is much still to be done. But\par
