great need. A snake without fangs may crawl where he will.'\par
'You may be right,' said Gandalf; 'but this snake had still one tooth\par
left, I think. He had the poison of his voice, and I guess that he persuaded\par
you, even you Treebeard, knowing the soft spot in your heart. Well, he is\par
gone, and there is no more to be said. But the Tower of Orthanc now goes back\par
to the King, to whom it belongs. Though maybe he will not need it.'\par
'That will be seen later,' said Aragorn. 'But I will give to Ents all\par
this valley to do with as they will, so long as they keep a watch upon Orthanc\par
and see that none enter it without my leave.'\par
'It is locked,' said Treebeard. 'I made Saruman lock it and give me the\par
keys. Quickbeam has them.'\par
Quickbeam bowed like a tree bending in the wind and handed to Aragorn two\par
great black keys of intricate shape, joined by a ring of steel. 'Now I thank\par
you once more,' said Aragorn, 'and I bid you farewell. May your forest grow\par
again in peace. When this valley is filled there is room and to spare west of\par
the mountains, where once you walked long ago.'\par
Treebeard's face became sad. 'Forests may grow,' he said. 'Woods may\par
spread. But not Ents. There are no Entings.'\par
'Yet maybe there is now more hope in your search,' said Aragorn. 'Lands\par
will lie open to you eastward that have long been closed.'\par
But Treebeard shook his head and said: 'It is far to go. And there are\par
too many Men there in these days. But I am forgetting my manners! Will you\par
stay here and rest a while? And maybe there are some that would be pleased to\par
pass through Fangorn Forest and so shorten their road home?' He looked at\par
Celeborn and Galadriel.\par
But all save Legolas said that they must now take their leave and depart,\par
either south or west. 'Come, Gimli!' said Legolas. 'Now by Fangorn's leave I\par
will visit the deep places of the Entwood and see such trees as are nowhere\par
else to be found in Middle-earth. You shall come with me and keep your word;\par
and thus we will journey on together to our own lands in Mirkwood and\par
beyond.' To this Gimli agreed, though with no great delight, it seemed.\par
'Here then at last comes the ending of the Fellowship of the Ring,' said\par
Aragorn. 'Yet I hope that ere long you will return to my land with the help\par
that you promised.'\par
'We will come, if our own lords allow it,' said Gimli. 'Well, farewell.\par
my hobbits! You should come safe to your own homes now, and I shall not be\par
kept awake for fear of your peril. We will send word when we may, and some of\par
us may yet meet at times; but I fear that we shall not all be gathered\par
together ever again.'\par
Then Treebeard said farewell to each of them in turn, and he bowed three\par
times slowly and with great reverence to Celeborn and Galadriel. 'It is long,\par
long since we met by stock or by stone, _A vanimar_, _vanim\'e1lion nostari!_' he\par
said. 'It is sad that we should meet only thus at the ending. For the world is\par
changing: I feel it in the water, I feel it in the earth, and I smell it in\par
the air. I do not think we shall meet again.'\par
And Celeborn said: 'I do not know, Eldest.' But Galadriel said: 'Not in\par
Middle-earth, nor until the lands that lie under the wave are lifted up again.\par
Then in the willow-meads of Tasarinan we may meet in the Spring. Farewell!'\par
Last of all Merry and Pippin said good-bye to the old Ent, and he grew\par
gayer as he looked at them. 'Well, my merry folk,' he said, 'will you drink\par
another draught with me before you go?'\par
'Indeed we will,' they said, and he took them aside into the shade of one\par
of the trees, and there they saw that a great stone jar had been set. And\par
Treebeard filled three bowls, and they drank; and they saw his strange eyes\par
looking at them over the rim of his bowl. 'Take care take care!' he said. 'For\par
you have already grown since I saw you last.' And they laughed and drained\par
their bowls.\par
'Well, good-bye!' he said. 'And don't forget that if you hear any news of\par
the Entwives in your land, you will send word to me.' Then he waved his great\par
hands to all the company and went off into the trees.\par
The travellers now rode with more speed, and they made their way towards\par
the Gap of Rohan; and Aragorn took leave of them at last close to that very\par
place where Pippin had looked into the Stone of Orthanc. The Hobbits were\par
grieved at this parting; for Aragorn had never failed them and he had been\par
their guide through many perils.\par
'I wish we could have a Stone that we could see all our friends in,' said\par
Pippin, 'and that we could speak to them from far away!'\par
'Only one now remains that you could use,' answered Aragorn for you would\par
not wish to see what the Stone of Minas Tirith would show you. But the\par
Palant\'edr of Orthanc the King will keep, to see what is passing in his realm,\par
and what his servants are doing. For do not forget, Peregrin Took, that you\par
are a knight of Gondor, and I do not release you from your service. You are\par
going now on leave, but I may recall you. And remember, dear friends of the\par
Shire, that my realm lies also in the North, and I shall come there one day.'\par
Then Aragorn took leave of Celeborn and Galadriel; and the Lady said to\par
him: 'Elfstone, through darkness you have come to your hope, and have now all\par
your desire. Use well the days!'\par
But Celeborn said: 'Kinsman, farewell! May your doom be other than mine,\par
and your treasure remain with you to the end!'\par
With that they parted, and it was then the time of sunset; and when after\par
a while they turned and looked back, they saw the King of the West sitting\par
upon his horse with his knights about him; and the falling Sun shone upon them\par
and made all their harness to gleam like red gold, and the white mantle of\par
Aragorn was turned to a flame. Then Aragorn took the green stone and held it\par
up, and there came a green fire from his hand.\par
Soon the dwindling company, following the Isen, turned west and rode\par
through the Gap into the waste lands beyond, and then they turned northwards,\par
and passed over the borders of Dunland. The Dunlendings fled and hid\par
themselves, for they were afraid of Elvish Folk, though few indeed ever came\par
to their country; but the travellers did not heed them, for they were still a\par
great company and were well provided with all that they needed; and they went\par
on their way at their leisure, setting up their tents when they would.\par
On the sixth day since their parting from the King they journeyed through\par
a wood climbing down from the hills at the feet of the Misty Mountains that\par
now marched on their right hand. As they came out again into the open country\par
