you had waited at Orthanc, you would have seen him, and he would have shown\par
you wisdom and mercy.'\par
'Then all the more reason to have left sooner,' said Saruman; 'for I\par
desire neither of him. Indeed if you wish for an answer to your first\par
question, I am seeking a way out of his realm.'\par
'Then once more you are going the wrong way,' said Gandalf, 'and I see no\par
hope in your journey. But will you scorn our help? For we offer it to you.'\par
'To me?' said Saruman. 'Nay, pray do not smile at me! I prefer your\par
frowns. And as for the Lady here, I do not trust her: she always hated me, and\par
schemed for your part. I do not doubt that she has brought you this way to\par
have the pleasure of gloating over my poverty. Had I been warned of your\par
pursuit, I would have denied you the pleasure.'\par
'Saruman,' said Galadriel, 'we have other errands and other cares that\par
seem to us more urgent than hunting for you. Say rather that you are overtaken\par
by good fortune; for now you have a last chance.'\par
'If it be truly the last, I am glad,' said Saruman; 'for I shall be\par
spared the trouble of refusing it again. All my hopes are ruined, but I would\par
not share yours. If you have any.'\par
For a moment his eyes kindled. 'Go!' he said. 'I did not spend long study\par
on these matters for naught. You have doomed yourselves, and you know it. And\par
it will afford me some comfort as I wander to think that you pulled down your\par
own house when you destroyed mine. And now, what ship will bear you back\par
across so wide a sea?' he mocked. 'It will be a grey ship, and full of\par
ghosts.' He laughed, but his voice was cracked and hideous.\par
'Get up, you idiot!' he shouted to the other beggar, who had sat down on\par
the ground; and he struck him with his staff. 'Turn about! If these fine folk\par
are going our way, then we will take another. Get on, or I'll give you no\par
crust for your supper!'\par
The beggar turned and slouched past whimpering: 'Poor old Gr\'edma! Poor old\par
Gr\'edma! Always beaten and cursed. How I hate him! I wish I could leave him!'\par
'Then leave him!' said Gandalf.\par
But Wormtongue only shot a glance of his bleared eyes full of terror at\par
Gandalf, and then shuffled quickly past behind Saruman. As the wretched pair\par
passed by the company they came to the hobbits, and Saruman stopped and stared\par
at them; but they looked at him with pity.\par
'So you have come to gloat too, have you, my urchins?' he said. 'You\par
don't care what a beggar lacks, do you? For you have all you want, food and\par
fine clothes, and the best weed for your pipes. Oh yes, I know! I know where\par
it comes from. You would not give a pipeful to a beggar, would you?'\par
'I would, if I had any,' said Frodo.\par
'You can have what I have got left,' said Merry, 'if you will wait a\par
moment.' He got down and searched in the bag at his saddle. Then he handed to\par
