it; it came from the flotsam of Isengard.'\par
'Mine, mine, yes and dearly bought!' cried Saruman, clutching at the\par
pouch. 'This is only a repayment in token; for you took more, I'll be bound.\par
Still, a beggar must be grateful, if a thief returns him even a morsel of his\par
own. Well, it will serve you right when you come home, if you find things less\par
good in the Southfarthing than you would like. Long may your land be short of\par
leaf!'\par
'Thank you!' said Merry. 'In that case I will have my pouch back, which\par
is not yours and has journeyed far with me. Wrap the weed in a rag of your\par
own.'\par
'One thief deserves another,' said Saruman, and turned his back on Merry,\par
and kicked Wormtongue, and went away towards the wood.\par
'Well, I like that!' said Pippin. 'Thief indeed! What of our claim for\par
waylaying, wounding, and orc-dragging us through Rohan?'\par
'Ah!' said Sam. 'And _bought_ he said. How, I wonder? And I didn't like\par
the sound of what he said about the Southfarthing. It's time we got back.'\par
'I'm sure it is,' said Frodo. 'But we can't go any quicker, if we are to\par
see Bilbo. I am going to Rivendell first, whatever happens.'\par
'Yes, I think you had better do that,' said Gandalf. 'But alas for\par
Saruman! I fear nothing more can be made of him. He has withered altogether.\par
All the same, I am not sure that Treebeard is right: I fancy he could do some\par
mischief still in a small mean way.'\par
Next day they went on into northern Dunland, where no men now dwelt,\par
though it was a green and pleasant country. September came in with golden days\par
and silver nights, and they rode at ease until they reached the Swanfleet\par
river, and found the old ford, east of the falls where it went down suddenly\par
into the lowlands. Far to the west in a haze lay the meres and eyots through\par
which it wound its way to the Greyflood: there countless swans housed in a\par
land of reeds.\par
So they passed into Eregion, and at last a fair morning dawned,\par
shimmering above gleaming mists; and looking from their camp on a low hill the\par
travellers saw away in the east the Sun catching three peaks that thrust up\par
into the sky through floating clouds: Caradhras, Celebdil, and Fanuidhol. They\par
were near to the Gates of Moria.\par
Here now for seven days they tarried, for the time was at hand for\par
another parting which they were loth to make. Soon Celeborn and Galadriel and\par
their folk would turn eastward, and so pass by the Redhorn Gate and down the\par
Dimrill Stair to the Silverlode and to their own country. They had journeyed\par
thus far by the west-ways, for they had much to speak of with Elrond and with\par
Gandalf, and here they lingered still in converse with their friends. Often\par
long after the hobbits were wrapped in sleep they would sit together under the\par
stars, recalling the ages that were gone and all their joys and labours in the\par
world, or holding council, concerning the days to come. If any wanderer had\par
chanced to pass, little would he have seen or heard, and it would have seemed\par
to him only that he saw grey figures, carved in stone, memorials of forgotten\par
things now lost in unpeopled lands. For they did not move or speak with mouth,\par
looking from mind to mind; and only their shining eyes stirred and kindled as\par
their thoughts went to and fro.\par
But at length all was said, and they parted again for a while, until it\par
was time for the Three Rings to pass away. Quickly fading into the stones and\par
the shadows the grey-cloaked people of L\'f3rien rode towards the mountains; and\par
those who were going to Rivendell sat on the hill and watched, until there\par
came out of the gathering mist a flash; and then they saw no more. Frodo knew\par
that Galadriel had held aloft her ring in token of farewell.\par
Sam turned away and sighed: 'I wish I was going back to L\'f3rien!'\par
At last one evening they came over the high moors, suddenly as to\par
travellers it always seemed, to the brink of the deep valley of Rivendell and\par
saw far below the lamps shining in Elrond's house. And they went down and\par
crossed the bridge and came to the doors, and all the house was filled with\par
light and song for joy at Elrond's homecoming.\par
First of all, before they had eaten or washed or even shed their cloaks,\par
the hobbits went in search of Bilbo. They found him all alone in his little\par
room. It was littered with papers and pens and pencils; but Bilbo was sitting\par
in a chair before a small bright fire. He looked very old, but peaceful, and\par
sleepy.\par
He opened his eyes and looked up as they came in. 'Hullo, hullo!' he\par
said. 'So you've come back? And tomorrow's my birthday, too. How clever of\par
you! Do you know, I shall be one hundred and twenty-nine? And in one year\par
more, if I am spared, I shall equal the Old Took. I should like to beat him;\par
but we shall see.'\par
After the celebration of Bilbo's birthday the four hobbits stayed in\par
Rivendell for some days, and they sat much with their old friend, who spent\par
most of his time now in his room, except at meals. For these he was still very\par
punctual as a rule, and he seldom failed to wake up in time for them. Sitting\par
round the fire they told him in turn all that they could remember of their\par
journeys and adventures. At first he pretended to take some notes; but he\par
often fell asleep; and when he woke he would say: 'How splendid! How\par
wonderful! But where were we?' Then they went on with the story from the point\par
where he had begun to nod.\par
The only part that seemed really to rouse him and hold his attention was\par
the account of the crowning and marriage of Aragorn. 'I was invited to the\par
wedding of course,' he said. 'And I have waited for it long enough. But\par
somehow, when it came to it, I found I had so much to do here; and packing is\par
such a bother.'\par
When nearly a fortnight had passed Frodo looked out of his window and saw\par
that there had been a frost in the night, and the cobwebs were like white\par
nets. Then suddenly he knew that he must go, and say good-bye to Bilbo. The\par
weather was still calm and fair, after one of the most lovely summers that\par
people could remember; but October had come, and it must break soon and begin\par
to rain and blow again. And there was still a very long way to go. Yet it was\par
not really the thought of the weather that stirred him. He had a feeling that\par
it was time he went back to the Shire. Sam shared it. Only the night before he\par
had said:\par
'Well, Mr. Frodo, we've been far and seen a deal, and yet I don't think\par
we've found a better place than this. There's something of everything here, if\par
you understand me: the Shire and the Golden Wood and Gondor and kings' houses\par
and inns and meadows and mountains all mixed. And yet, somehow, I feel we\par
ought to be going soon. I'm worried about my gaffer, to tell you the truth.'\par
'Yes, something of everything, Sam, except the Sea,' Frodo had answered;\par
and he repeated it now to himself: 'Except the Sea.'\par
That day Frodo spoke to Elrond, and it was agreed that they should leave\par
the next morning. To their delight Gandalf said: 'I think I shall come too. At\par
least as far as Bree. I want to see Butterbur.'\par
In the evening they went to say good-bye to Bilbo. 'Well, if you must go,\par
you must,' he said. 'I am sorry. I shall miss you. It is nice just to know\par
that you are about the place. But I am getting very sleepy.' Then he gave\par
Frodo his mithril-coat and Sting, forgetting that he had already done so; and\par
he gave him also three books of lore that he had made at various times,\par
written in his spidery hand, and labelled on their red backs: _Translations\par
from the Elvish, by B.B._\par
