vintage,' he said. 'May come in useful, if you think of getting married,\par
Sam.' Sam blushed.\par
'I have nothing much to give to you young fellows,' he said to Merry and\par
Pippin, 'except good advice.' And when he had given them a fair sample of\par
this, he added a last item in Shire-fashion: 'Don't let your heads get too big\par
for your hats! But if you don't finish growing up soon, you are going to find\par
hats and clothes expensive.'\par
'But if you want to beat the Old Took,' said Pippin, 'I don't see why we\par
shouldn't try and beat the Bullroarer.'\par
Bilbo laughed, and he produced out of a pocket two beautiful pipes with\par
pearl mouth-pieces and bound with fine-wrought silver. 'Think of me when you\par
smoke them!' he said. 'The Elves made them for me, but I don't smoke now.' And\par
then suddenly he nodded and went to sleep for a little; and when he woke up\par
again he said: 'Now where were we? Yes, of course, giving presents. Which\par
reminds me: what's become of my ring, Frodo, that you took away?'\par
'I have lost it, Bilbo dear,' said Frodo. 'I got rid of it, you know.'\par
'What a pity!' said Bilbo. 'I should have liked to see it again. But no,\par
how silly of me! That's what you went for, wasn't it: to get rid of it? But it\par
is all so confusing, for such a lot of other things seem to have got mixed up\par
with it: Aragorn's affairs, and the White Council and Gondor, and the\par
Horsemen, and Southrons, and oliphaunts \endash  did you really see one, Sam? \endash  and\par
caves and towers and golden trees, and goodness knows what besides.\par
'I evidently came back by much too straight a road from my trip. I think\par
