said Merry. 'Two is enough.'\par
Merry and Pippin climbed the gate, and the hobbits fled. Another horn\par
sounded. Out of the bigger house on the right a large heavy figure appeared\par
against a light in the doorway.\par
'What's all this,' he snarled as he came forward. 'Gate-breaking? You\par
clear out, or I'll break your filthy little necks!' Then he stopped, for he\par
had caught the gleam of swords.\par
'Bill Ferny,' said Merry, 'if you don't open that gate in ten seconds,\par
you'll regret it. I shall set steel to you, if you don't obey. And when you\par
have opened the gates you will go through them and never return. You are a\par
ruffian and a highway-robber.'\par
Bill Ferny flinched and shuffled to the gate and unlocked it. 'Give me\par
the key!' said Merry. But the ruffian flung it at his head and then darted out\par
into the darkness. As he passed the ponies one of them let fly with his heels\par
and just caught him as he ran. He went off with a yelp into the night and was\par
never heard of again.\par
'Neat work, Bill,' said Sam, meaning the pony.\par
'So much for your Big Man,' said Merry. 'We'll see the Chief later. In\par
the meantime we want a lodging for the night, and as you seem to have pulled\par
down the Bridge Inn and built this dismal place instead, you'll have to put us\par
up.'\par
'I am sorry, Mr. Merry,' said Hob, 'but it isn't allowed.'\par
'What isn't allowed?'\par
Taking in folk off-hand like and eating extra food, and all that, said\par
Hob.\par
'What's the matter with the place?' said Merry. 'Has it been a bad year,\par
or what? I thought it had been a fine summer and harvest.'\par
'Well no, the year's been good enough,' said Hob. 'We grows a lot of\par
food, but we don't rightly know what becomes of it. It's all these\par
"gatherers" and "sharers", I reckon, going round counting and measuring and\par
taking off to storage. They do more gathering than sharing, and we never see\par
most of the stuff again.'\par
'Oh come!' said Pippin yawning. 'This is all too tiresome for me tonight.\par
We've got food in our bags. Just give us a room to lie down in. It'll be\par
better than many places I have seen.'\par
The hobbits at the gate still seemed ill at ease, evidently some rule or\par
other was being broken; but there was no gainsaying four such masterful\par
travellers, all armed, and two of them uncommonly large and strong-looking.\par
Frodo ordered the gates to be locked again. There was some sense at any rate\par
in keeping a guard, while ruffians were still about. Then the four companions\par
went into the hobbit guard-house and made themselves as comfortable as they\par
could. It was a bare and ugly place, with a mean little grate that would not\par
allow a good fire. In the upper rooms were little rows of hard beds, and on\par
every wall there was a notice and a list of Rules. Pippin tore them down.\par
There was no beer and very little food, but with what the travellers brought\par
and shared out they all made a fair meal; and Pippin broke Rule 4 by putting\par
most of next day's allowance of wood on the fire.\par
'Well now, what about a smoke, while you tell us what has been happening\par
in the Shire?' he said.\par
'There isn't no pipe-weed now,' said Hob; 'at least only for the Chief's\par
men. All the stocks seem to have gone. We do hear that waggon-loads of it went\par
away down the old road out of the Southfarthing, over Sarn Ford way. That\par
would be the end o' last year, after you left. But it had been going away\par
quietly before that, in a small way. That Lotho-'\par
'Now you shut up, Hob Hayward!' cried several of the others. 'You know\par
talk o' that sort isn't allowed. The Chief will hear of it, and we'll all be\par
in trouble.'\par
'He wouldn't hear naught, if some of you here weren't sneaks,' rejoined\par
Hob hotly.\par
'All right, all right!' said Sam. "That's quite enough. I don't want to\par
hear no more. No welcome, no beer, no smoke, and a lot of rules and orc-talk\par
instead. I hoped to have a rest, but I can see there's work and trouble ahead.\par
Let's sleep and forget it till morning!'\par
The new 'Chief' evidently had means of getting news. It was a good forty\par
miles from the Bridge to Bag End, but someone made the journey in a hurry. So\par
Frodo and his friends soon discovered.\par
They had not made any definite plans, but had vaguely thought of going\par
down to Crickhollow together first, and resting there a bit. But now, seeing\par
what things were like, they decided to go straight to Hobbiton. So the next\par
day they set out along the Road and jogged along steadily. The wind had\par
dropped but the sky was grey. The land looked rather sad and forlorn; but it\par
was after all the first of November and the fag-end of Autumn. Still there\par
seemed an unusual amount of burning going on, and smoke rose from many points\par
round about. A great cloud of it was going up far away in the direction of the\par
Woody End.\par
As evening fell they were drawing near to Frogmorton, a village right on\par
the Road, about twenty-two miles from the Bridge. There they meant to stay the\par
night; _The Floating Log_ at Frogmorton was a good inn. But as they came to\par
the east end of the village they met a barrier with a large board saying NO\par
ROAD; and behind it stood a large band of Shirriffs with staves in their hands\par
and feathers in their caps, looking both important and rather scared.\par
'What's all this?' said Frodo, feeling inclined to laugh.\par
This is what it is, Mr. Baggins, said the leader of the Shirriffs, a twofeather\par
hobbit: 'You're arrested for Gate-breaking, and Tearing up of Rules,\par
and Assaulting Gate-keepers, and Trespassing, and Sleeping in Shire-buildings\par
without Leave, and Bribing Guards with Food.'\par
'And what else?' said Frodo.\par
'That'll do to go on with,' said the Shirriff-leader.\par
'I can add some more, if you like it,' said Sam. 'Calling your Chief\par
Names, Wishing to punch his Pimply Face, and Thinking you Shirriffs look a lot\par
of Tom-fools.'\par
'There now, Mister, that'll do. It's the Chief's orders that you're to\par
come along quiet. We're going to take you to Bywater and hand you over to the\par
Chief's Men; and when he deals with your case you can have your say. But if\par
you don't want to stay in the Lockholes any longer than you need, I should cut\par
the say short, if I was you.'\par
To the discomfiture of the Shirriffs Frodo and his companions all roared\par
with laughter. 'Don't be absurd!' said Frodo. 'I am going where I please, and\par
in my own time. I happen to be going to Bag End on business, but if you insist\par
on going too, well that is your affair.'\par
'Very well, Mr. Baggins,' said the leader, pushing the barrier aside.\par
'But don't forget I've arrested you.'\par
'I won't,' said Frodo. 'Never. But I may forgive you. Now I am not going\par
any further today, so if you'll kindly escort me to _The Floating Log_, I'll\par
be obliged.'\par
'I can't do that, Mr. Baggins. The inn's closed. There's a Shirriff-house\par
at the far end of the village. I'll take you there. '\par
'All right,' said Frodo. 'Go on and we'll follow.'\par
Sam had been looking the Shirriffs up and down and had spotted one that\par
he knew. 'Hey, come here Robin Smallburrow!' he called. 'I want a word with\par
you.'\par
With a sheepish glance at his leader, who looked wrathful but did not\par
dare to interfere, Shirriff Smallburrow fell back and walked beside Sam, who\par
got down off his pony.\par
'Look here, Cock-robin!' said Sam. 'You're Hobbiton-bred and ought to\par
have more sense, coming a-waylaying Mr. Frodo and all. And what's all this\par
about the inn being closed?'\par
'They're all closed,' said Robin. 'The Chief doesn't hold with beer.\par
Leastways that is how it started. But now I reckon it's his Men that has it\par
all. And he doesn't hold with folk moving about; so if they will or they must,\par
then they has to go to the Shirriff-house and explain their business.'\par
'You ought to be ashamed of yourself having anything to do with such\par
nonsense,' said Sam. 'You used to like the inside of an inn better than the\par
outside yourself. You were always popping in, on duty or off.'\par
'And so I would be still, Sam, if I could. But don't be hard on me. What\par
can I do? You know how I went for a Shirriff seven years ago, before any of\par
this began. Gave me a chance of walking round the country and seeing folk, and\par
hearing the news, and knowing where the good beer was. But now it's\par
different.'\par
'But you can give it up, stop Shirriffing, if it has stopped being a\par
respectable job,' said Sam.\par
'We're not allowed to,' said Robin.\par
'If I hear _not allowed_ much oftener,' said Sam, 'I'm going to get\par
angry.'\par
'Can't say as I'd be sorry to see it,' said Robin lowering his voice. 'If\par
we all got angry together something might be done. But it's these Men, Sam,\par
the Chief's Men. He sends them round everywhere, and if any of us small folk\par
stand up for our rights, they drag him off to the Lockholes. They took old\par
Flourdumpling, old Will Whitfoot the Mayor, first, and they've taken a lot\par
more. Lately it's been getting worse. Often they beat 'em now.'\par
'Then why do you do their work far them?' said Sam angrily. 'Who sent you\par
to Frogmorton?'\par
'No one did. We stay here in the big Shirriff-house. We're the First\par
Eastfarthing Troop now. There's hundreds of Shirriffs all told and they want\par
more, with all these new rules. Most of them are in it against their will, but\par
not all. Even in the Shire there are some as like minding other folk's\par
business and talking big. And there's worse than that: there's a few as do\par
spy-work for the Chief and his Men.'\par
'Ah! So that's how you had news of us, is it?'\par
'That's right. We aren't allowed to send by it now, but they use the old\par
Quick Post service, and keep special runners at different points. One came in\par
from Whitfurrows last night with a "secret message", and another took it on\par
from here. And a message came back this afternoon saying you was to be\par
arrested and taken to Bywater, not direct to the Lockholes. The Chief wants to\par
see you at once, evidently.'\par
'He won't be so eager when Mr. Frodo has finished with him,' said Sam.\par
The Shirriff-house at Frogmorton was as bad as the Bridge-house. It had\par
only one storey, but it had the same narrow windows, and it was built of ugly\par
pale bricks, badly laid. Inside it was damp and cheerless, and supper was\par
served on a long bare table that had not been scrubbed for weeks. The food\par
deserved no better setting. The travellers were glad to leave the place. It\par
was about eighteen miles to Bywater, and they set off at ten o'clock in the\par
morning. They would have started earlier, only the delay so plainly annoyed\par
the Shirriff-leader. The west wind had shifted northward and it was turning\par
colder, but the rain was gone.\par
It was rather a comic cavalcade that left the village, though the few\par
folk that came out to stare at the 'get-up' of the travellers did not seem\par
quite sure whether laughing was allowed. A dozen Shirriffs had been told off\par
as escort to the 'prisoners'; but Merry made them march in front, while Frodo\par
and his friends rode behind. Merry, Pippin, and Sam sat at their ease laughing\par
and talking and singing, while the Shirriffs stumped along trying to look\par
stern and important. Frodo, however, was silent and looked rather sad and\par
thoughtful.\par
The last person they passed was a sturdy old gaffer clipping a hedge.\par
'Hullo, hullo!' he jeered. 'Now who's arrested who?'\par
Two of the Shirriffs immediately left the party and went towards him.\par
'Leader!' said Merry. 'Order your fellows back to their places at once, if you\par
don't want me to deal with them!'\par
The two hobbits at a sharp word from the leader came back sulkily. 'Now\par
get on!' said Merry, and after that the travellers saw to it that their\par
ponies' pace was quick enough to push the Shirriffs along as fast as they\par
could go. The sun came out, and in spite of the chilly wind they were soon\par
puffing and sweating.\par
At the Three-Farthing Stone they gave it up. They had done nearly\par
fourteen miles with only one rest at noon. It was now three o'clock. They were\par
hungry and very footsore and they could not stand the pace.\par
'Well, come along in your own time!' said Merry. 'We are going on.'\par
'Good-bye, Cock-robin!' said Sam. 'I'll wait for you outside _The Green\par
Dragon_, if you haven't forgotten where that is. Don't dawdle on the way!'\par
'You're breaking arrest, that's what you're doing,' said the leader\par
ruefully, 'and I can't be answerable.'\par
'We shall break a good many things yet, and not ask you to answer ' said\par
Pippin. 'Good luck to you!'\par
The travellers trotted on, and as the sun began to sink towards the White\par
Downs far away on the western horizon they came to Bywater by its wide pool;\par
and there they had their first really painful shock. This was Frodo and Sam's\par
own country, and they found out now that they cared about it more than any\par
other place in the world. Many of the houses that they had known were missing.\par
Some seemed to have been burned down. The pleasant row of old hobbit-holes in\par
the bank on the north side of the Pool were deserted, and their little gardens\par
that used to run down bright to the water's edge were rank with weeds. Worse,\par
there was a whole line of the ugly new houses all along Pool Side, where the\par
Hobbiton Road ran close to the bank. An avenue of trees had stood there. They\par
were all gone. And looking with dismay up the road towards Bag End they saw a\par
tall chimney of brick in the distance. It was pouring out black smoke into the\par
evening air.\par
Sam was beside himself. 'I'm going right on, Mr. Frodo!' he cried. 'I'm\par
going to see what's up. I want to find my gaffer.'\par
'We ought to find out first what we're in for, Sam,' said Merry. 'I guess\par
that the "Chief" will have a gang of ruffians handy. We had better find\par
someone who will tell us how things are round here.'\par
But in the village of Bywater all the houses and holes were shut, and no\par
one greeted them. They wondered at this, but they soon discovered the reason\par
of it. When they reached _The Green Dragon_, the last house on the Hobbiton\par
side, now lifeless and with broken windows, they were disturbed to see half a\par
dozen large ill-favoured Men lounging against the inn-wall; they were squinteyed\par
and sallow-faced.\par
'Like that friend of Bill Ferny's at Bree,' said Sam.\par
'Like many that I saw at Isengard,' muttered Merry.\par
The ruffians had clubs in their hands and horns by their belts, but they\par
had no other weapons, as far as could be seen. As the travellers rode up they\par
left the wall and walked into the road, blocking the way.\par
'Where d'you think you're going?' said one, the largest and most evillooking\par
of the crew. 'There's no road for you any further. And where are those\par
precious Shirriffs?'\par
'Coming along nicely,' said Merry. 'A little footsore, perhaps. We\par
promised to wait for them here.'\par
'Garn, what did I say?' said the ruffian to his mates. 'I told Sharkey it\par
was no good trusting those little fools. Some of our chaps ought to have been\par
sent.'\par
'And what difference would that have made, pray?' said Merry. 'We are not\par
used to footpads in this country, but we know how to deal with them.'\par
'Footpads, eh?' said the man: 'So that's your tone, is it? Change it, or\par
we'll change it for you. You little folk are getting too uppish. Don't you\par
trust too much in the Boss's kind heart. Sharkey's come now and he'll do what\par
Sharkey says.'\par
'And what may that be?' said Frodo quietly.\par
'This country wants waking up and setting to rights,' said the ruffian,\par
'and Sharkey's going to do it; and make it hard, if you drive him to it. You\par
need a bigger Boss. And you'll get one before the year is out, if there's any\par
more trouble. Then you'll learn a thing or two, you little rat-folk.'\par
'Indeed. I am glad to hear of your plans,' said Frodo. 'I am on my way to\par
call on Mr. Lotho, and he may be interested to hear of them too.'\par
The ruffian laughed. 'Lotho! He knows all right. Don't you worry. He'll\par
do what Sharkey says. Because if a Boss gives trouble, we can change him. See?\par
And if little folks try to push in where they're not wanted, we can put them\par
out of mischief. See?'\par
'Yes, I see,' said Frodo. 'For one thing, I see that you're behind the\par
times and the news here. Much has happened since you left the South. Your day\par
is over, and all other ruffians'. The Dark Tower has fallen, and there is a\par
King in Gondor. And Isengard has been destroyed, and your precious master is a\par
beggar in the wilderness. I passed him on the road. The King's messengers will\par
ride up the Greenway now not bullies from Isengard.'\par
The man stared at him and smiled. 'A beggar in the wilderness!' he\par
mocked. 'Oh, is he indeed? Swagger it, swagger it, my little cock-a-whoop. But\par
that won't stop us living in this fat little country where you have lazed long\par
enough. And' \endash  he snapped his fingers in Frodo's face \endash  'King's messengers!\par
That for them! When I see one, I'll take notice, perhaps.'\par
This was too much for Pippin. His thoughts went back to the Field of\par
Cormallen, and here was a squint-eyed rascal calling the Ring-bearer 'little\par
cock-a-whoop'. He cast back his cloak, flashed out his sword, and the silver\par
and sable of Gondor gleamed on him as he rode forward.\par
'I am a messenger of the King,' he said. 'You are speaking to the King's\par
friend, and one of the most renowned in all the lands of the West. You are a\par
ruffian and a fool. Down on your knees in the road and ask pardon, or I will\par
set this troll's bane in you!'\par
The sword glinted in the westering sun. Merry and Sam drew their swords\par
also and rode up to support Pippin; but Frodo did not move. The ruffians gave\par
back. Scaring Breeland peasants, and bullying bewildered hobbits, had been\par
their work. Fearless hobbits with bright swords and grim faces were a great\par
surprise. And there was a note in the voices of these newcomers that they had\par
not heard before. It chilled them with fear.\par
'Go!' said Merry. 'If you trouble this village again, you will regret\par
it.' The three hobbits came on, and then the ruffians turned and fled running\par
away up the Hobbiton Road; but they blew their horns as they ran.\par
'Well, we've come back none too soon,' said Merry.\par
'Not a day too soon. Perhaps too late, at any rate to save Lotho,' said\par
Frodo. 'Miserable fool, but I am sorry for him.'\par
'Save Lotho? Whatever do you mean?' said Pippin. 'Destroy him I should\par
say.'\par
'I don't think you quite understand things, Pippin,' said Frodo. 'Lotho\par
never meant things to come to this pass. He has been a wicked fool, but he's\par
caught now. The ruffians are on top, gathering, robbing and bullying, and\par
running or ruining things as they like, in his name. And not in his name even\par
for much longer. He's a prisoner in Bag End now, I expect, and very\par
frightened. We ought to try and rescue him.'\par
'Well I am staggered!' said Pippin. 'Of all the ends to our journey that\par
is the very last I should have thought of: to have to fight half-orcs and\par
ruffians in the Shire itself \endash  to rescue Lotho Pimple!'\par
'Fight?' said Frodo. 'Well, I suppose it may come to that. But remember:\par
there is to be no slaying of hobbits, not even if they have gone over to the\par
other side. Really gone over, I mean; not just obeying ruffians' orders\par
because they are frightened. No hobbit has ever killed another on purpose in\par
the Shire, and it is not to begin now. And nobody is to be killed at all, if\par
it can be helped. Keep your tempers and hold your hands to the last possible\par
moment!'\par
'But if there are many of these ruffians,' said Merry, 'it will certainly\par
mean fighting. You won't rescue Lotho, or the Shire, just by being shocked and\par
sad, my dear Frodo.'\par
'No,' said Pippin. 'It won't be so easy scaring them a second time. They\par
were taken by surprise. You heard that horn-blowing? Evidently there are other\par
ruffians near at hand. They'll be much bolder when there's more of them\par
together. We ought to think of taking cover somewhere for the night. After all\par
we're only four, even if we are armed.'\par
'I've an idea,' said Sam. 'Let's go to old Tom Cotton's down South Lane!\par
He always was a stout fellow. And he has a lot of lads that were all friends\par
of mine.'\par
'No!' said Merry. 'It's no good "getting under cover". That is just what\par
people have been doing, and just what these ruffians like. They will simply\par
come down on us in force, corner us, and then drive us out, or burn us in. No,\par
we have got to do something at once.'\par
'Do what?' said Pippin.\par
'Raise the Shire!' said Merry. 'Now! Wake all our people! They hate all\par
this, you can see: all of them except perhaps one or two rascals, and a few\par
fools that want to be important, but don't at all understand what is really\par
going on. But Shire-folk have been so comfortable so long they don't know what\par
to do. They just want a match, though, and they'll go up in fire. The Chief's\par
Men must know that. They'll try to stamp on us and put us out quick. We've\par
only got a very short time.\par
'Sam, you can make a dash for Cotton's farm, if you like. He's the chief\par
person round here, and the sturdiest. Come on! I am going to blow the horn of\par
Rohan, and give them all some music they have never heard before.'\par
They rode back to the middle of the village. There Sam turned aside and\par
galloped off down the lane that led south to Cotton's. He had not gone far\par
when he heard a sudden clear horn-call go up ringing into the sky. Far over\par
hill and field it echoed; and so compelling was that call that Sam himself\par
almost turned and dashed back. His pony reared and neighed.\par
'On, lad! On!' he cried. 'We'll be going back soon.'\par
Then he heard Merry change the note, and up went the Horn-cry of\par
Buckland, shaking the air.\par
_Awake! Awake! Fear, Fire, Foes! Awake!\par
Fire, Foes! Awake!_\par
Behind him Sam heard a hubbub of voices and a great din and slamming of\par
doors. In front of him lights sprang out in the gloaming; dogs barked; feet\par
came running. Before he got to the lane's end there was Farmer Cotton with\par
three of his lads, Young Tom, Jolly, and Nick, hurrying towards him. They had\par
axes in their hands, and barred the way.\par
'Nay! It's not one of them ruffians,' Sam heard the farmer say. 'It's a\par
hobbit by the size of it, but all dressed up queer. Hey!' he cried. 'Who are\par
you, and what's all this to-do?'\par
'It's Sam, Sam Gamgee. I've come back.'\par
Farmer Cotton came up close and stared at him in the twilight. 'Well!' he\par
exclaimed. 'The voice is right, and your face is no worse than it was, Sam.\par
But I should a' passed you in the street in that gear. You've been in foreign\par
parts, seemingly. We feared you were dead.'\par
'That I ain't!' said Sam. 'Nor Mr. Frodo. He's here and his friends. And\par
that's the to-do. They're raising the Shire. We're going to clear out these\par
ruffians, and their Chief too. We're starting now.'\par
'Good, good!' cried Farmer Cotton. 'So it's begun at last! I've been\par
itching for trouble all this year, but folks wouldn't help. And I've had the\par
wife and Rosie to think of. These ruffians don't stick at nothing. But come on\par
now, lads! Bywater is up! We must be in it!'\par
'What about Mrs. Cotton and Rosie?' said Sam. 'It isn't safe yet for them\par
to be left all alone.'\par
'My Nibs is with them. But you can go and help him, if you have a mind,'\par
said Farmer Cotton with a grin. Then he and his sons ran off towards the\par
village.\par
Sam hurried to the house. By the large round door at the top of the steps\par
from the wide yard stood Mrs. Cotton and Rosie, and Nibs in front of them\par
grasping a hay-fork.\par
'It's me!' shouted Sam as he trotted up. 'Sam Gamgee! So don't try\par
prodding me, Nibs. Anyway, I've a mail-shirt on me.'\par
He jumped down from his pony and went up the steps. They stared at him in\par
silence. 'Good evening, Mrs. Cotton!' he said. 'Hullo Rosie!'\par
'Hullo, Sam!' said Rosie. 'Where've you been I They said you were dead;\par
but I've been expecting you since the Spring. You haven't hurried have you?'\par
'Perhaps not,' said Sam abashed. 'But I'm hurrying now. We're setting\par
about the ruffians, and I've got to get back to Mr. Frodo. But I thought I'd\par
have a look and see how Mrs. Cotton was keeping, and you, Rosie.'\par
'We're keeping nicely, thank you,' said Mrs. Cotton. 'Or should be, if it\par
weren't for these thieving ruffians.'\par
'Well, be off with you!' said Rosie. 'If you've been looking after Mr.\par
Frodo all this while, what d'you want to leave him for, as soon as things look\par
dangerous?'\par
This was too much for Sam. It needed a week's answer, or none. He turned\par
away and mounted his pony. But as he started off, Rosie ran down the steps.\par
'I think you look fine, Sam,' she said. 'Go on now! But take care of\par
yourself, and come straight back as soon as you have settled the ruffians!'\par
When Sam got back he found the whole village roused. Already, apart from\par
many younger lads, more than a hundred sturdy hobbits were assembled with\par
axes, and heavy hammers, and long knives, and stout staves: and a few had\par
hunting-bows. More were still coming in from outlying farms.\par
Some of the village-folk had lit a large fire, just to enliven things,\par
and also because it was one of the things forbidden by the Chief. It burned\par
bright as night came on. Others at Merry's orders were setting up barriers\par
across the road at each end of the village. When the Shirriffs came up to the\par
lower one they were dumbfounded; but as soon as they saw how things were, most\par
of them took off their feathers and joined in the revolt. The others slunk\par
away.\par
Sam found Frodo and his friends by the fire talking to old Tom Cotton,\par
while an admiring crowd of Bywater folk stood round and stared.\par
'Well, what's the next move?' said Farmer Cotton.\par
'I can't say,' said Frodo, 'until I know more. How many of these ruffians\par
are there?'\par
'That's hard to tell,' said Cotton. 'They moves about and comes and goes.\par
There's sometimes fifty of them in their sheds up Hobbiton way; but they go\par
out from there roving round, thieving or "gathering" as they call it. Still\par
there's seldom less than a score round the Boss, as they names him. He's at\par
Bag End, or was; but he don't go outside the rounds now. No one s seen him at\par
