together.\par
The hobbits opened the barrier and stood aside. 'Thank you!' the Men\par
jeered. 'Now run home to bed before you're whipped.' Then they marched along\par
the street shouting: 'Put those lights out! Get indoors and stay there! Or\par
we'll take fifty of you to the Lockholes for a year. Get in! The Boss is\par
losing his temper.'\par
No one paid any heed to their orders; but as the ruffians passed, they\par
closed in quietly behind and followed them. When the Men reached the fire\par
there was Farmer Cotton standing all alone warming his hands.\par
'Who are you, and what d'you think you're doing?' said the ruffianleader.\par
Farmer Cotton looked at him slowly. 'I was just going to ask you that,'\par
he said. 'This isn't your country, and you're not wanted.'\par
'Well, you're wanted anyhow,' said the leader. 'We want you. Take him\par
lads! Lockholes for him, and give him something to keep him quiet!'\par
The Men took one step forward and stopped short. There rose a roar of\par
voices all round them, and suddenly they were aware that Farmer Cotton was not\par
