The leader looked round. He was trapped. But he was not scared, not now\par
with a score of his fellows to back him. He knew too little of hobbits to\par
understand his peril. Foolishly he decided to fight. It would be easy to break\par
out.\par
'At 'em lads!' he cried. 'Let 'em have it!'\par
With a long knife in his left hand and a club in the other he made a rush\par
at the ring, trying to burst out back towards Hobbiton. He aimed a savage blow\par
at Merry who stood in his way. He fell dead with four arrows in him:\par
That was enough for the others. They gave in. Their weapons were taken\par
from them, and they were roped together, and marched off to an empty hut that\par
they had built themselves, and there they were tied hand and foot, and locked\par
up under guard. The dead leader was dragged off and buried.\par
'Seems almost too easy after all, don't it?' said Cotton. 'I said we\par
could master them. But we needed a call. You came back in the nick o' time,\par
Mr. Merry.'\par
'There's more to be done still,' said Merry. 'If you're right in your\par
reckoning, we haven't dealt with a tithe of them yet. But it's dark now. I\par
think the next stroke must wait until morning. Then we must call on the\par
Chief.'\par
'Why not now?' said Sam. 'It's not much more than six o'clock. And I want\par
to see my gaffer. D'you know what's come of him, Mr. Cotton?'\par
'He's not too well, and not too bad, Sam,' said the farmer. 'They dug up\par
Bagshot Row, and that was a sad blow to him. He's in one of them new houses\par
that the Chief's Men used to build while they still did any work other than\par
burning and thieving: not above a mile from the end of Bywater. But he comes\par
around to me, when he gets a chance, and I see he's better fed than some of\par
the poor bodies. All against _The Rules_, of course. I'd have had him with me,\par
but that wasn't allowed.'\par
'Thank'ee indeed, Mr. Cotton, and I'll never forget it,' said Sam. 'But I\par
want to see him. That Boss and that Sharkey, as they spoke of, they might do a\par
mischief up there before the morning.'\par
'All right, Sam,' said Cotton. 'Choose a lad or two, and go and fetch him\par
to my house. You'll not have need to go near the old Hobbiton village over\par
Water. My Jolly here will show you.'\par
Sam went off. Merry arranged for look-outs round the village and guards\par
at the barriers during the night. Then he and Frodo went off with Farmer\par
Cotton. They sat with the family in the warm kitchen, and the Cottons asked a\par
few polite questions about their travels, but hardly listened to the answers:\par
they were far more concerned with events in the Shire.\par
'It all began with Pimple, as we call him,' said Farmer Cotton; 'and it\par
began as soon as you'd gone off, Mr. Frodo. He'd funny ideas had Pimple. Seems\par
he wanted to own everything himself, and then order other folk about. It soon\par
came out that he already did own a sight more than was good for him; and he\par
was always grabbing more, though where he got the money was a mystery: mills\par
and malt-houses and inns, and farms, and leaf-plantations. He'd already bought\par
Sandyman's mill before he came to Bag End, seemingly.\par
'Of course he started with a lot of property in the Southfarthing which\par
he had from his dad; and it seems he'd been selling a lot o' the best leaf,\par
and sending it away quietly for a year or two. But at the end o' last year he\par
began sending away loads of stuff, not only leaf. Things began to get short,\par
and winter coming on, too. Folk got angry, but he had his answer. A lot of\par
Men, ruffians mostly, came with great waggons, some to carry off the goods\par
south-away, and others to stay. And more came. And before we knew where we\par
were they were planted here and there all over the Shire, and were felling\par
trees and digging and building themselves sheds and houses just as they liked.\par
At first goods and damage was paid for by Pimple; but soon they began lording\par
it around and taking what they wanted.\par
'Then there was a bit of trouble, but not enough. Old Will the Mayor set\par
off for Bag End to protest, but he never got there. Ruffians laid hands on him\par
and took and locked him up in a hole in Michel Delving, and there he is now.\par
And after that, it would be soon after New Year, there wasn't no more Mayor,\par
and Pimple called himself Chief Shirriff, or just Chief, and did as he liked;\par
and if anyone got "uppish" as they called it, they followed Will. So things\par
went from bad to worse. There wasn't no smoke left, save for the Men; and the\par
Chief didn't hold with beer, save for his Men, and closed all the inns; and\par
everything except Rules got shorter and shorter, unless one could hide a bit\par
of one's own when the ruffians went round gathering stuff up "for fair\par
distribution": which meant they got it and we didn't, except for the leavings\par
which you could have at the Shirriff-houses, if you could stomach them. All\par
very bad. But since Sharkey came it's been plain ruination.'\par
'Who is this Sharkey?' said Merry. 'I heard one of the ruffians speak of\par
him.'\par
'The biggest ruffian o' the lot, seemingly,' answered Cotton. 'It was\par
about last harvest, end o' September maybe, that we first heard of him. We've\par
never seen him, but he's up at Bag End; and he's the real Chief now, I guess.\par
All the ruffians do what he says; and what he says is mostly hack, burn, and\par
ruin; and now it's come to killing. There's no longer even any bad sense in\par
it. They cut down trees and let 'em lie, they burn houses and build no more.\par
'Take Sandyman's mill now. Pimple knocked it down almost as soon as he\par
came to Bag End. Then he brought in a lot o' dirty-looking Men to build a\par
bigger one and fill it full o' wheels and outlandish contraptions. Only that\par
fool Ted was pleased by that, and he works there cleaning wheels for the Men,\par
where his dad was the Miller and his own master. Pimple's idea was to grind\par
more and faster, or so he said. He's got other mills like it. But you've got\par
to have grist before you can grind; and there was no more for the new mill to\par
do than for the old. But since Sharkey came they don't grind no more corn at\par
all. They're always a-hammering and a-letting out a smoke and a stench, and\par
there isn't no peace even at night in Hobbiton. And they pour out filth a\par
purpose; they've fouled all the lower Water and it's getting down into\par
Brandywine. If they want to make the Shire into a desert, they're going the\par
right way about it. I don't believe that fool of a Pimple's behind all this.\par
It's Sharkey, I say.'\par
'That's right!' put in Young Tom. 'Why, they even took Pimple's old ma,\par
that Lobelia, and he was fond of her, if no one else was. Some of the Hobbiton\par
folk, they saw it. She comes down the lane with her old umbrella. Some of the\par
ruffians were going up with a big cart.\par
' "Where be you a-going?" says she.\par
' "To Bag End," says they.\par
' "What for?" says she.\par
' "To put up some sheds for Sharkey," says they.\par
' "Who said you could?" says she.\par
' "Sharkey," says they. "So get out o' the road, old hagling!"\par
' "I'll give you Sharkey, you dirty thieving ruffians!" says she, and ups\par
with her umbrella and goes for the leader. near twice her size. So they took\par
her. Dragged her off to the Lockholes, at her age too. They've took others we\par
miss more, but there's no denying she showed more spirit than most.'\par
Into the middle of this talk came Sam, bursting in with his gaffer. Old\par
Gamgee did not look much older, but he was a little deafer.\par
'Good evening. Mr. Baggins!' he said. 'Glad indeed I am to see you safe\par
back. But I've a bone to pick with you, in a manner o' speaking, if I may make\par
so bold. You didn't never ought to have a' sold Bag End, as I always said.\par
That's what started all the mischief. And while you're been trapessing in\par
foreign parts, chasing Black Men up mountains from what my Sam says, though\par
what for he don't make clear, they've been and dug up Bagshot Row and ruined\par
my taters!'\par
'I am very sorry, Mr. Gamgee,' said Frodo. 'But now I've come back, I'll\par
do my best to make amends.'\par
'Well, you can't say fairer than that,' said the gaffer. 'Mr. _Frodo_\par
Baggins is a real gentlehobbit, I always have said, whatever you may think of\par
some others of the name, begging your pardon. And I hope my Sam's behaved\par
hisself and given satisfaction?'\par
'Perfect satisfaction, Mr. Gamgee,' said Frodo. 'Indeed, if you will\par
believe it, he's now one of the most famous people in all the lands, and they\par
are making songs about his deeds from here to the Sea and beyond the Great\par
River.' Sam blushed, but he looked gratefully at Frodo, for Rosie's eyes were\par
shining and she was smiling at him.\par
'It takes a lot o' believing,' said the gaffer, 'though I can see he's\par
been mixing in strange company. What's come of his weskit? I don't hold with\par
wearing ironmongery, whether it wears well or no.'\par
Farmer Cotton's household and all his guests were up early next morning.\par
Nothing had been heard in the night, but more trouble would certainly come\par
before the day was old. 'Seems as if none o' the ruffians were left up at Bag\par
End,' said Cotton; 'but the gang from Waymeet will be along any time now.'\par
After breakfast a messenger from the Tookland rode in. He was in high\par
spirits. 'The Thain has raised all our country,' he said, 'and the news is\par
going like fire all ways. The ruffians that were watching our land have fled\par
off south, those that escaped alive. The Thain has gone after them, to hold\par
off the big gang down that way; but he's sent Mr Peregrin back with all the\par
other folk he can spare.'\par
The next news was less good. Merry, who had been out all night, came\par
riding in about ten o'clock. 'There's a big band about four miles away,' he\par
said. 'They're coming along the road from Waymeet, but a good many stray\par
ruffians have joined up with them. There must be close on a hundred of them;\par
and they're fire-raising as they come. Curse them!'\par
'Ah! This lot won't stay to talk, they'll kill, if they can,' said Farmer\par
Cotton. 'If Tooks don't come sooner, we'd best get behind cover and shoot\par
without arguing. There's got to be some fighting before this is settled, Mr.\par
Frodo.'\par
The Tooks did come sooner. Before long they marched in, a hundred strong,\par
from Tuckborough and the Green Hills with Pippin at their head. Merry now had\par
enough sturdy hobbitry to deal with the ruffians. Scouts reported that they\par
were keeping close together. They knew that the countryside had risen against\par
them, and plainly meant to deal with the rebellion ruthlessly, at its centre\par
in Bywater. But however grim they, might be, they seemed to have no leader\par
among them who understood warfare. They came on without any precautions. Merry\par
laid his plans quickly.\par
The ruffians came tramping along the East Road, and without halting\par
turned up the Bywater Road, which ran for some way sloping up between high\par
banks with low hedges on top. Round a bend, about a furlong from the main\par
road, they met a stout barrier of old farm-carts upturned. That halted them.\par
At the same moment they became aware that the hedges on both sides, just above\par
their heads, were all lined with hobbits. Behind them other hobbits now pushed\par
out some more waggons that had been hidden in a field, and so blocked the way\par
back. A voice spoke to them from above.\par
'Well, you have walked into a trap,' said Merry. 'Your fellows from\par
Hobbiton did the same, and one is dead and the rest are prisoners. Lay down\par
your weapons! Then go back twenty paces and sit down. Any who try to break out\par
will be shot.'\par
But the ruffians could not now be cowed so easily. A few of them obeyed,\par
but were immediately set on by their fellows. A score or more broke back and\par
charged the waggons. Six were shot, but the remainder burst out, killing two\par
hobbits, and then scattering across country in the direction of the Woody End.\par
Two more fell as they ran. Merry blew a loud horn-call, and there were\par
answering calls from a distance.\par
'They won't get far,' said Pippin. 'All that country is alive with our\par
hunters now.'\par
Behind, the trapped Men in the lane, still about four score, tried to\par
climb the barrier and the banks, and the hobbits were obliged to shoot many of\par
them or hew them with axes. But many of the strongest and most desperate got\par
out on the west side, and attacked their enemies fiercely, being now more bent\par
on killing than escaping. Several hobbits fell, and the rest were wavering,\par
when Merry and Pippin, who were on the east side, came across and charged the\par
ruffians. Merry himself slew the leader, a great squint-eyed brute like a huge\par
orc. Then he drew his forces off, encircling the last remnant of the Men in a\par
wide ring of archers.\par
At last all was over. Nearly seventy of the ruffians lay dead on the\par
field, and a dozen were prisoners. Nineteen hobbits were killed, and some\par
thirty were wounded. The dead ruffians were laden on waggons and hauled off to\par
an old sand-pit nearby and there buried: in the Battle Pit, as it was\par
afterwards called. The fallen hobbits were laid together in a grave on the\par
hill-side, where later a great stone was set up with a garden about it. So\par
ended the Battle of Bywater, 1419, the last battle fought in the Shire, and\par
the only battle since the Greenfields, 1147, away up in the Northfarthing. In\par
consequence, though it happily cost very few lives, it has a chapter to itself\par
in the Red Book, and the names of all those who took part were made into a\par
Roll, and learned by heart by Shire-historians. The very considerable rise in\par
the fame and fortune of the Cottons dates from this time; but at the top of\par
the Roll in all accounts stand the names of Captains Meriadoc and Peregrin.\par
Frodo had been in the battle, but he had not drawn sword, and his chief\par
part had been to prevent the hobbits in their wrath at their losses, from\par
slaying those of their enemies who threw down their weapons. When the fighting\par
was over, and the later labours were ordered, Merry, Pippin, and Sam joined\par
him, and they rode back with the Cottons. They ate a late midday meal, and\par
then Frodo said with a sigh: 'Well, I suppose it is time now that we dealt\par
with the "Chief".'\par
'Yes indeed; the sooner the better,' said Merry. 'And don't be too\par
gentle! He's responsible for bringing in these ruffians, and for all the evil\par
they have done.'\par
Farmer Cotton collected an escort of some two dozen sturdy hobbits. 'For\par
it's only a guess that there is no ruffians left at Bag End,' he said. 'We\par
don't know.' Then they set out on foot. Frodo, Sam, Merry, and Pippin led the\par
way.\par
It was one of the saddest hours in their lives. The great chimney rose up\par
before them; and as they drew near the old village across the Water, through\par
rows of new mean houses along each side of the road, they saw the new mill in\par
all its frowning and dirty ugliness: a great brick building straddling the\par
stream, which it fouled with a steaming and stinking overflow. All along the\par
Bywater Road every tree had been felled.\par
As they crossed the bridge and looked up the Hill they gasped. Even Sam's\par
vision in the Mirror had not prepared him for what they saw. The Old Grange on\par
the west side had been knocked down, and its place taken by rows of tarred\par
sheds. All the chestnuts were gone. The banks and hedgerows were broken. Great\par
waggons were standing in disorder in a field beaten bare of grass. Bagshot Row\par
was a yawning sand and gravel quarry. Bag End up. beyond could not be seen for\par
a clutter of large huts.\par
'They've cut it down!' cried Sam. 'They've cut down the Party Tree!' He\par
pointed to where the tree. had stood under which Bilbo had made his Farewell\par
Speech. It was lying lopped and dead in the field. As if this was the last\par
straw Sam burst into tears.\par
A laugh put an end to them. There was a surly hobbit lounging over the\par
low wall of the mill-yard. He was grimy-faced and black-handed. 'Don't 'ee\par
like it, Sam?' he sneered. 'But you always was soft. I thought you'd gone off\par
in one o' them ships you used to prattle about, sailing, sailing. What d'you\par
want to come back for? We've work to do in the Shire now.'\par
'So I see,' said Sam. 'No time for washing, but time for wall-propping.\par
But see here, Master Sandyman, I've a score to pay in this village, and don't\par
you make it any longer with your jeering, or you'll foot a bill too big for\par
your purse.'\par
Ted Sandyman spat over the wall: 'Garn!' he said. 'You can't touch me.\par
I'm a friend o' the Boss's. But he'll touch you all right, if I have any more\par
of your mouth.'\par
'Don't waste any more words on the fool, Sam!' said Frodo. 'I hope there\par
are not many more hobbits that have become like this. It would be a worse\par
trouble than all the damage the Men have done.'\par
'You are dirty and insolent, Sandyman,' said Merry. 'And also very much\par
out of your reckoning. We are just going up the Hill to remove your precious\par
Boss. We have dealt with his Men.'\par
Ted gaped, for at that moment he first caught sight of the escort that at\par
a sign from Merry now marched over the bridge. Dashing back into the mill he\par
ran out with a horn and blew it loudly.\par
'Save your breath!' laughed Merry. 'I've a better.' Then lifting up his\par
silver horn he winded it, and its clear call rang over the Hill; and out of\par
the holes and sheds and shabby houses of Hobbiton the hobbits answered, and\par
came pouring out, and with cheers and loud cries they followed the company up\par
the road to Bag End.\par
At the top of the lane the party halted, and Frodo and his friends went\par
on; and they came at last to the once beloved place. The garden was full of\par
huts and sheds, some so near the old westward windows that they cut off all\par
their light. There were piles of refuse everywhere. The door was scarred; the\par
bell-chain was dangling loose, and the bell would not ring. Knocking brought\par
no answer. At length they pushed and the door yielded. They went in. The place\par
stank and was full of filth and disorder: it did not appear to have been used\par
for some time.\par
'Where is that miserable Lotho hiding?' said Merry. They had searched\par
every room and found no living thing save rats and mice. 'Shall we turn on the\par
others to search the sheds?'\par
'This is worse than Mordor!' said Sam. 'Much worse in a way. It comes\par
home to you, as they say; because it is home, and you remember it before it\par
was all ruined.'\par
'Yes, this is Mordor,' said Frodo. 'Just one of its works. Saruman was\par
doing its work all the time, even when he thought he was working for himself.\par
And the same with those that Saruman tricked, like Lotho.'\par
Merry looked round in dismay and disgust. 'Let's get out!' he said. 'If I\par
had known all the mischief he had caused, I should have stuffed my pouch down\par
Saruman's throat.'\par
'No doubt, no doubt! But you did not, and so I am able to welcome you\par
home.' There standing at the door was Saruman himself, looking well-fed and\par
well-pleased; his eyes gleamed with malice and amusement.\par
A sudden light broke on Frodo. 'Sharkey!' he cried.\par
Saruman laughed. 'So you have heard the name, have you? All my people\par
used to call me that in Isengard, I believe. A sign of affection, possibly.\par
But evidently you did not expect to see me here.'\par
'I did not,' said Frodo. 'But I might have guessed. A little mischief in\par
a mean way: Gandalf warned me that you were still capable of it.\par
'Quite capable,' said Saruman, 'and more than a little. You made me\par
laugh, you hobbit-lordlings, riding along with all those great people so\par
secure and so pleased with your little selves. You thought you had done very\par
well out of it all, and could now just amble back and have a nice quiet time\par
in the country. Saruman's home could be all wrecked, and he could be turned\par
out, but no one could touch yours. Oh no! Gandalf would look after your\par
affairs.'\par
Saruman laughed again. 'Not he! When his tools have done their task he\par
drops them. But you must go dangling after him, dawdling and talking, and\par
riding round twice as far as you needed. "Well," thought I, "if they're such\par
fools, I will get ahead of them and teach them a lesson. One ill turn deserves\par
another." It would have been a sharper lesson, if only you had given me a\par
little more time and more Men. Still I have already done much that you will\par
find it hard to mend or undo in your lives. And it will be pleasant to think\par
of that and set it against my injuries.'\par
'Well, if that is what you find pleasure in,' said Frodo, 'I pity you. It\par
will be a pleasure of memory only, I fear. Go at once and never return!'\par
The hobbits of the villages had seen Saruman come out of one of the huts,\par
and at once they came crowding up to the door of Bag End. When they heard\par
Frodo's command, they murmured angrily:\par
'Don't let him go! Kill him! He's a villain and a murderer. Kill him!'\par
Saruman looked round at their hostile faces and smiled. 'Kill him!' he\par
mocked. 'Kill him, if you think there are enough of you, my brave hobbits!' He\par
drew himself up and stared at them darkly with his black eyes. 'But do not\par
think that when I lost all my goods I lost all my power! Whoever strikes me\par
shall be accursed. And if my blood stains the Shire, it shall wither and never\par
again be healed.'\par
The hobbits recoiled. But Frodo said: 'Do not believe him! He has lost\par
all power, save his voice that can still daunt you and deceive you, if you let\par
it. But I will not have him slain. It is useless to meet revenge with revenge:\par
it will heal nothing. Go, Saruman, by the speediest way!'\par
